<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 00:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Facing Recruiting Troubles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A report on the nation's military culture says America's
armed forces face formidable challenges in the 21st century, especially
recruiting problems caused by the robust economy and a lack of role models.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington think tank,
says its two-year study, based on responses from thousands of military men and
women, finds the U.S. military is entering a critical period.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For many of today's youth, enlisting in the military is an alien thought.
With the number of veterans dwindling, local advocates and role models are
fading in number,'' according to the report, which was being released Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   All military branches face tremendous pressures in recruiting and retaining
qualified men and women for today's computerized high-tech warfare, the study
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Opportunities offered by the booming economy and record low unemployment
make it increasingly difficult to fill the ranks of an all-volunteer military
force.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation no longer has an identifiable major military adversary. But at no
comparable period in peacetime history has the United States leaned more heavily
or frequently on its armed forces for such missions as peacekeeping and drug
intervention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In an era when `peacetime' America has never been safer from military
aggression, ... this volunteer force has never been busier,'' the report says.
``Today the smallest force in four decades -- with 56 percent married -- is
overworked, underpaid and underresourced at the cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Cmdr. Terry Sutherland, a Pentagon spokesman, could not comment on the
study because he said he has not seen it. ``We look forward to reading it,''
Sutherland said.
</P>
<P>
	   The report's authors say there is little doubt that conditions within the
armed forces are far less favorable than they were even 10 years ago, and the
U.S. military faces ``potentially serious rifts in its culture.''
</P>
<P>
	   Today's soldiers are older and more often married than in the days when the
ranks were filled with young draftees. Consequently, the study finds, modern
warriors have higher expectations on matters that affect the quality of their
lives and the satisfaction they experience in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Military policy-makers face difficult choices on how best to spend their
budgets on new gear, maintaining bases and facilities, training personnel,
repairing aging equipment, increasing pay and finding money for unforeseen
contingencies.
</P>
<P>
	   The study offers numerous recommendations the authors maintain could help
military leaders better cope with the needs of its recruits.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said the public must be better educated about how military
culture and the demands it makes on soldiers and their families differ from
civilian life.
</P>
<P>
	   It also said the stress level must be reduced by either increasing the
military's resources or reducing or redesigning the services' missions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0001 </TRAILER>
