<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Runner Dies at Marathon  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- A Canadian runner died from an apparent heart
attack Sunday after collapsing just over a mile into the Disney Marathon.
</P>
<P>
	Warren Plumb, of Sharon, Ontario, fell at the 1.2-mile marker, Orange County
sheriff's spokesman Cpl. Angelo Nieves said.
</P>
<P>
	Several runners, including emergency medical workers, stopped to perform CPR
before paramedics arrived.
</P>
<P>
	``This wasn't what we came here to do,'' said Mike Hadden, one of the paramedic
runners.
</P>
<P>
	Plumb, 56, was pronounced dead at 7:24 a.m. at Florida Hospital Celebration
Health less than an hour after he collapsed.
</P>
<P>
	According to Nieves, Plumb had a history of heart problems and witnesses said
he carried nitroglycerin tablets while running.
</P>
<P>
	Plumb's wife, Beverly, was notified after she finished the marathon with a time
of six hours, 49 minutes and 57 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
