<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor's budget to include most extensive debt reform proposal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - With New York facing both the highest-in-the-nation
debt and credit ratings at the bottom of Wall Street's heap, the state must
attack its debt problem, Gov. George Pataki says.
<P>
	   Pataki's 2000-01 budget presentation to the Legislature this Tuesday will
call for the end to all "back-door" borrowing - the bonding not approved
beforehand by voters, the imposition of caps on debt growth and debt service
costs and a prohibition against debt being used to finance non-capital projects.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor said the state has made "tremendous progress" in restoring some
responsibility to its debt practices since he took over in 1995. But Pataki
declared Sunday, "We can do even more."
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki plan joins those anti-debt proposals put forward in the past year
or so by the other key players in Albany: the Republican majority in the Senate,
the Democratic majority in the Assembly and state Comptroller H. Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican governor's proposal is probably most similar to the
Democratic comptroller's, Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We think this is the year when we can get bipartisan agreement on this
issue," McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
	   McCall on Sunday said it was about time that Pataki makes a serious
commitment to hack away at the state's borrowing practices, though, in truth,
Pataki has been talking about ways to approach the problem for years.
</P>
<P>
	   "We may finally see some progress toward reform," McCall said. "I'm anxious
to work together with the governor and Legislature to finally see some progress
toward reform."
</P>
<P>
	   Wall Street has long looked askance at the state's loose borrowing practices
under which New York has accumulated a nation's-high $37.5 billion in debt. It
is one of the factors that continues to prevent the state from improving its
credit rating when it seeks to borrow money, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts were especially critical of such Cuomo-era moves as the state's
"sale" of Attica state prison to itself, calling them nothing more than gimmicks
that are highly damaging to the state's fiscal integrity.
</P>
<P>
	   Said McCall on Sunday, "New York has borrowed the wrong way for the wrong
reasons" for many years.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said he would also ask legislators when unveiling his budget on
Tuesday to boost the state's Debt Reduction Reserve Fund from $250 million to
$750 million. That fund, created in 1996, has been used to shift the funding of
some projects from bonds to a pay-as-you-go approach.
</P>
<P>
	   That, in turn, saves taxpayers' money by avoiding long-term financing costs
on bonds.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor said he'd ask to use $500 million in fiscal 2000-01 to reduce
debt and the other $250 million in the following fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki will fund that increase in part by applying leftover money due the
state through its settlement with tobacco companies to the debt reserve fund,
McKeon said. At first, Pataki said he'd like to put the entire settlement money
toward debt reduction, but agreed last month with the Legislature to use the
bulk of it - roughly $1 billion between now and 2003 - to fund health coverage
programs for the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
	   Roughly $250 million would be left over for debt-reduction purposes, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said he would propose capping new debt at 3.5 percent of personal
income in the state - the current level is about 6 percent - and cap new debt
service costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the debt-practice changes can be done legislatively. Others have to
be approved by voters by amending the state constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 0111 </TRAILER>
