<HEADLINE> Stuart, Mickey Reign at Box Office  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The mouse invasion continues at movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stuart Little," with Michael J. Fox providing the voice of E.B. White's
amiable rodent, was the No. 1 movie for the second straight weekend, grossing
$11.5 million, according to industry estimates Sunday. The movie has taken in
$95.6 million in four weeks and should pass the $100 million mark by next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fantasia/2000," featuring Mickey Mouse, did elephantine business in a
limited run at Imax theaters, playing to sold-out houses in many places.
</P>
<P>
	   And the prison saga "The Green Mile," which co-stars a Death Row inmate's
pet mouse, remained strong as the No. 3 movie with $9.7 million, pushing its
total gross to $91.3 million in five weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   With no new movies out this weekend, holdovers rounded out the top 10. "The
Talented Mr. Ripley" was second with $9.8 million, "Any Given Sunday" was fourth
with $9 million, and "Galaxy Quest" was fifth with $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fantasia/2000," Disney's update of the 1940 animated classic, took in $2.7
million this weekend in 54 Imax theaters in the United States and Canada. The
film had a phenomenal per-theater average of $50,000, compared with $3,860 for
"Stuart Little," playing on 2,979 screens.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fantasia/2000" also played at 21 Imax theaters overseas but Disney did not
have the weekend results yet. Overall, it has grossed at least $8.5 million
worldwide since opening on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
	   Like its predecessor, "Fantasia/2000" features short segments set to
classical music and includes the Mickey Mouse episode, "The Sorcerer's
Apprentice," from the original film.
</P>
<P>
	   The movie has a four-month run at Imax theaters before hitting regular
cinemas this summer. Disney chose Imax, with its huge screens and superior sound
systems, to give "Fantasia/2000" more of an event status.
</P>
<P>
	   The late Walt Disney had conceived of "Fantasia" as a work in progress, with
periodic updates planned. But the original was received coolly by critics and
did not break even financially until a re-release in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think he would be so happy that his dream has been fulfilled now both
artistically and commercially," said Chuck Viane, head of distribution for
Disney.
</P>
<P>
	   Two movies that expanded to wider theatrical runs cracked the top 10.
"Magnolia," from director Paul Thomas Anderson, was No. 7 with $6.6 million in
1,034 theaters, up from nine theaters the previous weekend. The movie averaged
$6,359 per screen, impressive considering its three-hour length.
</P>
<P>
	   An ensemble film interweaving multiple plots on a single day, "Magnolia" has
received generally positive reviews, particularly for Tom Cruise as a TV guru
who teaches men to "seduce and destroy" women.
</P>
<P>
	   "Snow Falling on Cedars," adapted from the best-selling novel, was No. 10
with $4 million after expanding to 1,150 theaters, up from three last weekend.
</P>
<P>
	   "Toy Story 2" had $7.5 million for a total of $220.1 million, passing
"Aladdin's" $217 million. It is now Disney's third-biggest movie ever, behind
"The Lion King" at $312 million and "The Sixth Sense" at $276 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at North American theaters,
according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final figures were to be released
today.
</P>
<P>
	   1. "Stuart Little," $11.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   2. "The Talented Mr. Ripley," $9.8 million.
</P>
<P>
	   3. "The Green Mile," $9.7 million.
</P>
<P>
	   4. "Any Given Sunday," $9 million.
</P>
<P>
	   5. "Galaxy Quest," $8.3 million.
</P>
<P>
	   6. "Toy Story 2," $7.5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   7. "Magnolia," $6.6 million.
</P>
<P>
	   8. "Bicentennial Man," $5.2 million.
</P>
<P>
	   9. "Deuce Bigalow: Male Gigolo," $5 million.
</P>
<P>
	   10. "Snow Falling on Cedars," $4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
