<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Option for War Ruled Out for Syria  </HEADLINE>
   By ZEINA KARAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- There was a time not too long ago when Syria
believed war was the best, and perhaps only, way to win back the Golan Heights
it lost to Israel 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
	   But over the years, Syria -- which has fought three wars against the Jewish
state, the last in 1973 -- has gradually dismissed the military option in its
confrontation. It has opted instead for negotiations as a means to recover its
territory.
</P>
<P>
	   Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak have been meeting during the past week in Shepherdstown, W. Va., their
second round of talks after an icebreaking session in Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, the U.S.-brokered negotiations have made little headway,
underscoring the long-standing tension between the two nations. The talks
appeared to be winding down today without even a tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   The collapse of the Soviet Union, Syria's traditional political backer, and
peace treaties between Israel and Arab countries who were once Syria's partners
in war are among a handful of other reasons that forced leaders to resort to
peace talks with their bitterest foe.
</P>
<P>
	   There has been a gradual transformation in Syria's political rhetoric, said
Imad Shuaibi, a Syrian journalist and political analyst.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The focus has slowly shifted from the conflict over Israel's right to
exist to a border conflict,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``But Syrians have other ways of going to war.'' He cited the ongoing
conflict between Israeli occupation troops in southern Lebanon and Shiite Muslim
guerrillas seeking to drive them out. Iran and Syria, the main power broker in
Lebanon, both support the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Syria realizes it cannot recover the Golan through direct military
pressure now'' but it uses the conflict in southern Lebanon to exert indirect
pressure, Shuaibi said.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, a senior Syrian official admitted as much.
</P>
<P>
	   In a rare acknowledgment, Parliament Speaker Abdul-Kader Kaddoura said Arab
nations were incapable of regaining through war territory occupied by the Jewish
state since the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I say it frankly that we are not capable of liberation -- not only Syria,
but also all the Arabs,'' he told foreign journalists.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say President Hafez Assad, who was Syria's defense minister when
Syria lost the Golan Heights in 1967, has always been behind the concept of
military parity with Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, during the 1973 Mideast War, Syrian troops who took Israel by
surprise managed to regain a sizable chunk of the strategic territory.
</P>
<P>
	   Since he seized power in a bloodless coup in 1970, Assad has dreamed of
recovering the entire Golan Heights, driving the Israelis into the sea and
uniting the Arab world with Syria at its head.
</P>
<P>
	   That dream began fading with Egypt's peace treaty with Israel in 1979. Egypt
had fought alongside Syria in the 1948, 1967 and 1973 Arab-Israeli wars.
</P>
<P>
	   Assad felt largely abandoned with the 1991 fall of his former patron and
main arms provider, the Soviet Union, and peace accords between Israel and the
Palestinians in 1990 and Jordan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Arabs in general seem to have given up on the military option,'' said
Ghassan Beshara, editor of the New York-based Middle East Report.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Add to all that Syria's troubled economy and the fact that Syrian weaponry
is quite old and outdated, and you find that all these factors crystallized into
a new Syrian mode of thinking leading up to political negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
	   Some Syrians, though, cling to old rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we are not able to secure our rights through negotiations, we are ready
to use force because this land must be returned someday, one way or another,''
said Abboud Sarraj, dean of the law faculty at Damascus University. ``It is our
legitimate, undeniable right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0126 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
