<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Fighters Used in Sri Lanka  </HEADLINE>
   By DILIP GANGULY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Huddling under rice straw and dry leaves on his
verandah, 70-year-old Rankothabendi Peter watched in silent terror as scores of
women waving machetes and assault guns descended on his village out of the
night.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 90 minutes before daybreak, 100 Tamil guerrillas -- most of them
women -- hacked, slashed and shot to death 48 Sinhalese villagers as they slept
or tried to flee through surrounding rice fields. Among the carnage were the
dismembered bodies of 11 children.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter survived the slaughter at Borapola, 125 miles west of Sri Lanka's
capital, Colombo, only because the marauders never found his hiding place.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sept. 18 attack was carried out by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
a rebel group known for the high number of fiercely committed women, many
recruited as children, who fight alongside the men.
</P>
<P>
	   Tamil rebels have been fighting for a separate homeland on this island off
India's southeast coast since 1983, accusing the majority Sinhalese of
widespread discrimination in education and jobs. The Sinhalese, who control the
government and military, comprise 76 percent of Sri Lanka's 18.6 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sri Lankan Defense Ministry says a female member of an elite suicide
squad known as the Black Tigers blew herself up last week, killing 12 other
people outside the office of Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike. When guards
closed in, suspicious because the woman had a Sinhalese identity card but could
not speak the language, she ignited explosives strapped beneath her clothing.
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 18, another woman blew herself up at an election rally for President
Chandrika Kumaratunga. That blast killed 23 people and wounded the president,
who may lose sight in her right eye as a result of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
	   Tamil Tiger leader Velupillai Prabhakaran, who founded the rebel group in
1976 as a high school dropout, described the suicide bombers as ``the
self-protective armor of our race,'' last July when marking the Black Tigers'
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
	   From a ragtag band of fighters who attacked a group of soldiers in 1983, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam have developed into a sophisticated force
banned in Sri Lanka, India and the United States. They have Web sites and use
satellite phones to transmit daily battlefield reports to offices in London and
Paris, where supporters raise funds and handle public relations.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sri Lankan military believes half the Tigers' estimated fighting force
of 5,000 are women. These ``Birds of Freedom,'' as their fellow rebels call
them, have carried out the highest profile attacks -- the assassination of
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi in 1991 and the two recent bombings in
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
	   While Sri Lankan women are much more likely to work outside the home than
those in other South Asian countries, most Tamil women maintain traditional
appearance -- richly colored saris, brilliant jewelry, flowers in their flowing
hair, silver anklets and red dots on their foreheads.
</P>
<P>
	   The rebel women, however, ``are in combat fatigues, in boots, with no
makeup, jewelry or ostentation, often with their hair cut in short, male style,
wearing a cyanide capsule around their necks,'' says Radhika Coomaraswamy, a
Tamil academic who studies violence against women for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   The new image ``puts forward androgyny as ideal,'' she said. ``Both men and
women are aspiring for the same thing with an identity and style.''
</P>
<P>
	   Children, male and female, are chosen as young as 10 to become suicide
bombers. Some families willingly allow their children to join the rebel cause,
perhaps not realizing their intended tasks. But a few young rebels captured in
battle say they were snatched on their way home from school or errands.
</P>
<P>
	   All receive combat training, and the girls are told stories of glory from
Hindu epics about women who battled enemies of the Tamil people.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They first use the girls as spies and constantly tell them they are doing
a great service for the homeland cause,'' said retiring Gen. Sarath Munasinghe,
who until three weeks ago was military commander in the Tamil city of Jaffna,
where he interrogated captured rebels.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The attention they get makes their tender hearts feel very good, and then
the indoctrination starts,'' he said, adding that the female fighters are
generally kept in a confined area and are not allowed to meet outsiders. ``They
are shown video films and are constantly fed with stories of how Tamils are
oppressed and killed.''
</P>
<P>
	   The rebels deliberately choose women as suicide bombers, Munasinghe said,
because women may not undergo as close a body search as men at checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
	   Cultural expectations of women may also be a factor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In our society, women sacrifice a lot. You can't see it because most women
suffer silently,'' says Maheswary Velautham, a Tamil lawyer who handles human
rights cases. ``In a normal home, the sacrifice may look simple, like eating
last so others in the family don't go hungry. It is this element of sacrifice
that manifests one million times stronger when a woman militant is asked to die
for the cause of the Tamil homeland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0127 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accuser's grandma supports Jovanovic in cybersex case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Oliver Jovanovic, who was freed from prison after his
conviction in a kidnapping and sex torture case was overturned, is getting moral
support from his accuser's relatives.
<P>
	   The accuser's grandmother, who identified herself as Fay Webster, hugged
Jovanovic and his family at a press conference Sunday and cast doubt on her
granddaughter's credibility.
</P>
<P>
	   "She caused a lot of trouble in a lot of people's lives by her lying," Ms.
Webster said of her granddaughter. "It's a very sad case. ... There have just
been other incidents that happened."
</P>
<P>
	   She added: "I felt bad for Oliver because he didn't need to go through
this."
</P>
<P>
	   Jovanovic, 32, said the charges against him were fabricated.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a hoax," he said. "My accuser's family saw right through them."
</P>
<P>
	   Jovanovic's brother, Adrian Jovanovic, said the accuser "has a history of
making false allegations."
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Ms. Webster nor anyone else at the press conference would elaborate,
but they referred to a column in the New York Post that said the accuser "stole
from her father on a constant basis and once falsely accused her father and
uncle of sexually molesting her at the age of 17."
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Webster's son is the accuser's father. She lives in a small town near
Buffalo, where the accuser, a college student at the time of the alleged attack,
grew up.
</P>
<P>
	   The accuser's mother appeared to fully support her daughter during the
trial, testifying that she had notified campus police of Jovanovic's alleged
attack over the young woman's objections.
</P>
<P>
	   The accuser admitted at trial that she had used her father's credit cards
and personal checks without his permission.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokeswoman for the Manhattan district attorney's office, Barbara
Thompson, had no comment Sunday. The accuser could not be reached for comment as
she does not have a lawyer or a listed telephone number.
</P>
<P>
	   Laurie Poole, an aunt of the accuser, also appeared at the press conference
in support of Jovanovic and Ms. Webster, but she did not speak.
</P>
<P>
	   Jovanovic's girlfriend, Marinza Bruineman, attested to her belief in his
innocence.
</P>
<P>
	   "As a woman who has slept nightly with this man ... there is nothing vile,
weird or evil about him," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Webster said she had not been in contact with her granddaughter for
several years.
</P>
<P>
	   "We didn't have a good relationship," she acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
	   Jovanovic was two weeks away from defending his doctoral dissertation at
Columbia University in molecular biology when he was arrested in 1996. He was
convicted in 1998 on charges of kidnapping, sex abuse and assault, but the
conviction was overturned last month and he was freed from prison after serving
20 months.
</P>
<P>
	   The Appellate Division overturned the conviction on the grounds that the
jury should have been allowed to see e-mails sent by the accuser to Jovanovic in
which she expressed an interest in sadomasochism.
</P>
<P>
	   During trial, his lawyers asserted that everything that went on between them
was consensual.
</P>
<P>
	   Jovanovic met his accuser, a Barnard College sophomore, in an Internet chat
room. She told authorities he then lured her to his Washington Heights
apartment, tied her up and tortured her for 20 hours, biting her, beating her
and dripping hot candle wax on her body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 0128 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Syrian Talks Near an End  </HEADLINE>
   By BARRY SCHWEID AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton renewed his efforts to push
Israeli and Syrian negotiators toward a land-for-peace treaty with a series of
meetings Sunday evening, but the talks appeared to be winding down without even
a tentative agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Clearly we are coming to the end of the leaders' participation here this
week,'' the State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   In a post-midnight session with reporters, Rubin said he did not expect an
agreement to emerge and that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa were likely to meet again ``sooner rather than
later.''
</P>
<P>
	   An administration official said, meanwhile, Clinton was unlikely to return
to the negotiations on Monday. ``At the leader level this round is pretty much
concluded,'' said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   That left open the possibility Barak and al-Sharaa would leave experts
behind to try to keep whittling away at the issues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think there have been a lot of positive developments,'' Rubin said
after Clinton met for 2 1/2 hours with Barak and al-Sharaa and then separately
with each of them.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli foreign minister, David Levy, left for Morocco and a meeting
there with King Mohamed VI.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak, describing the weeklong talks over territory, peace terms, water and
security as complex and difficult, was making plans to depart for home Monday
and diplomatic sources said al-Sharaa was likely to follow on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   On the sensitive issue of establishing a new border, once Israel pulls back
on the Golan Heights, Levy said before departing that ``nothing has been agreed
upon.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, who had intervened in the negotiations four times before Sunday,
returned to the site of the talks after nightfall Sunday. ``He's going for
meetings,'' a White House official said. ``The process continues.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is an ongoing process,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
``The issues are difficult and complex.''
</P>
<P>
	   A source close to the Syrian delegation said the focus of the working dinner
would be the seven-page document, which is a summary of points of accord and
discord, that Clinton presented to both leaders on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Syrians have made
revisions to the document that they would bring up during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The source stressed that the Israelis had to accept Syria's border terms,
adding that Damascus would not make compromises on that issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, Barak and al-Sharaa all were dressed casually as waiters served
tenderloin of beef with morel sauce, along with chardonnay and merlot wines.
</P>
<P>
	   Committees met Sunday on all the key issues, and the State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said the two sides responded positively to the
statement presented Friday by the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   The document could become the basis for an eventual ``core agreement,''
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   But he said Israel and Syria still faced ``enormous decisions'' and ``we
don't expect those decisions to be made in a matter of days,''
</P>
<P>
	   American mediators had not offered ``bridging proposals'' designed to close
the gap where the two sides were in disagreement, Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
	   In Jerusalem, Israel Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon said Syria had refused to
permit Israel to retain an early warning station on the Golan Heights once it is
relinquished.
</P>
<P>
	   But, Ramon said, Syria was prepared to consider a station manned mostly by
American and French personnel, with a Syrian presence and a symbolic Israeli
presence.
</P>
<P>
	   Yielding the plateau would strip Israel of a capability to watch any Syrian
military preparations, including tanks rolling down toward the border.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak and al-Sharaa could leave behind experts to continue deliberations.
But Rubin said there was no decision on how negotiations would proceed, although
he said the United States wanted full-blown negotiations to reconvene ``sooner
rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no doubt that the negotiation is difficult,'' Barak told Israeli
reporters while touring the Antietam National Battlefield, a Civil War site in
Sharpsburg, Md., with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
	   In his first public remarks since the talks began Jan. 3, Barak said ``the
negotiation is very complex.''
</P>
<P>
	   The prime minister, speaking Hebrew, also gave assurances to the Israeli
public that ``we will not sign an agreement unless, in our opinion, it will
strengthen the security of Israel and address its vital needs.''
</P>
<P>
	   Israel is contemplating a withdrawal from the Golan Heights, a border
highground with a commanding view of Syria, in exchange for a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak, his wife, Nava, and Levy were shown a 26-minute documentary film
recreating the Antietam battle in which North and South suffered 22,726
casualties on Sept. 17, 1862.
</P>
<P>
	   They also listened to a lecture about the bloody day from a National Park
Service ranger and Bruce Reidel, who is on the Near East desk at the National
Security Council and a Civil War buff.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright then hosted a luncheon for Barak at Hillsboro, her Virginia retreat
across the border from West Virginia, and returned to the secluded negotiations
site just outside Shepherdstown to meet with al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Sunday, Al-Hayat, a Saudi newspaper published in London, said Israel
had agreed to pull back to the 1923 border with Syria and that Syria was
insisting on a deeper pullback, to the border that existed at the eve of the
1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said the account was not credible. He told reporters the newspaper's
report differed in ``substantive ways'' from the document prepared at Albright's
direction and presented by Clinton to Barak and al-Sharaa on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   In Syria, the state-run Al-Thawra newspaper, said Sunday that the West
Virginia peace talks are ``in serious danger.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is clear that there are Israeli directives to ... break up the talks in
an attempt to add hurdles and hamper them to leave the political process
spinning in place,'' the newspaper said in an editorial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
