<DOCNO> APW20000110.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lives Saved in Venezuela Slum  </HEADLINE>
   By BART JONES Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- When killer floods sent an avalanche of mud and
boulders raging through the Catuche slum in northern Caracas, community leaders
quickly took to the streets with megaphones to warn people to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents helped neighbors salvage clothes and furniture. Families streamed
out of their homes and fled to higher ground.
</P>
<P>
	   While hundreds were killed in similar slums along a mountain that collapsed
on itself on Dec. 15, in Catuche -- a slum noted for its extraordinary community
organization -- roughly a dozen people died.
</P>
<P>
	   The unspeakable death toll in Venezuela's worst natural disaster this
century -- authorities say it could reach 30,000 -- has been partly blamed on
corrupt leaders who abandoned shantytowns to their fate after allowing them to
sprout up uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
	   But the people of Catuche have long fought against the kind of neglect that
made other Venezuelan slumdwellers so vulnerable when the mudslides hit. And
their efforts paid off.
</P>
<P>
	   Catuche has been recognized by the U.N. Development Program as a model for
improving conditions in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
	   The neighborhood is a hodgepodge of clay block houses crammed on top of each
other on the sides of a river ravine near Venezuela's Supreme Court. The
mudslides demolished 800 homes, leaving 5,000 people -- half the slum's
population -- homeless.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the neighborhood is now pushing ahead with plans to rebuild while
other slums are busy mourning their dead.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The community organization saved our lives,'' said Jesuit priest Jose
Virtuoso, whose religious order has worked in the slum for a decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The community has cut crime, cemented over parts of a sewage-filled river
with walkways, established after-school study and enrichment programs, and
created a community newspaper.
</P>
<P>
	   Gang members who used to terrorize the neighborhood with shootouts were
persuaded to take on jobs cleaning up garbage, planting trees and installing
lightposts. In parts of the slum where sewers were installed, the river has come
back to life, with fish, crabs and ducks reappearing for the first time in
years.
</P>
<P>
	   By the time the mudslides hit, some residents had already been moved out of
shacks that were perched over the river on makeshift bridges. Had they still
been there, they would have been crushed by torrents of mud and water reaching
three stories high.
</P>
<P>
	   Today they live in attractive two- and three-bedroom apartments on higher,
safer ground. From their apartment windows they screamed warnings for residents
below them to run.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fact that they were already organized ... naturally helped them in the
immediate and rapid response they made to evacuate,'' said Angel Rangel,
Venezuela's national civil defense director.
</P>
<P>
	   Catuche's residents still have the daunting task of rebuilding. Much of the
neighborhood is barely recognizable.
</P>
<P>
	   Community leader Margarita Hernandez, 52, comes back every day to stare at
the spot where she lived for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That was my house,'' she said, pointing to a mound of dirt. At night, she
replays scenes of the floods in nightmares.
</P>
<P>
	   Community leaders already had plans to build new housing to relocate 4,000
people who live in Catuche's most dangerous zones. The $15 million project was
to take 10 years. Now the timetable has been compressed to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
	   ``During 10 years, a social fabric has developed, a community that is still
alive,'' Virtuoso said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
