<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brown Mulls First Year in Office  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHELLE LOCKE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Sitting in a sun-splashed city square, Jerry Brown
reflected on 1999: Crime was down, jobs were up and the media buzz went on,
stoked by curiosity over what happens when a governor turns mayor.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's been a very positive year,'' said Brown of his first year in office.
</P>
<P>
	   Elected on a promise to bring change to this struggling city of about
400,000, Brown made good. He booted out the police chief, engineered the hasty
retreat of the school superintendent and said so long to his press secretary.
</P>
<P>
	   He also created an arts council, negotiated with developers to refurbish
vacant buildings, presided over a technology summit that drew 300 civic leaders
and appointed revered tattoo artist Don Ed Hardy to the Oakland Cultural Arts
Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Change is good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   After Brown's promises to reclaim the streets, the schools, the city, just
how much has changed in the past year?
</P>
<P>
	   -- Developers are putting millions of dollars into new stores and apartments
downtown and a new five-star hotel is planned.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Serious crime is down 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Oakland has attracted a number of high-tech firms, including Cybergold,
the Internet marketing firm stolen away from Berkeley and employing 130 people,
and Zhone Technologies, which promises 1,500 workers.
</P>
<P>
	   There has been quite a bit of change going on inside City Hall, too.
</P>
<P>
	   Saying that the status quo had to go in a town plagued by high crime and low
test scores, Brown used the strong-mayor powers given to him by voters to demand
the resignation of the police chief. He worked with state Sen. Don Perata to put
pressure on the school superintendent to resign.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown's press secretary abruptly stepped down at year's end amid reports
that her replacement was quietly being recruited.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown's take-no-prisoners style has ruffled some.
</P>
<P>
	   At a city council meeting in November, he was booed as he spoke in favor of
his proposed ballot measure that would give him the power to appoint three
additional members to the school board.
</P>
<P>
	   Councilwoman Nancy Nadel, one of four on the eight-member council to oppose
the measure, called the proposal a ``combination of democracy and
dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
	   Brown carried the day with his tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
	   But so far, the majority of people seem to like it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I feel strongly he's got ideas that already has most people looking up to
a higher horizon,'' said Ralph Williams, known as the ``Mayor of West Oakland,''
the once jazzy, now blighted section of town that is attempting a comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   While community support for Brown appears to be strong, some are dismayed to
see him courting the corporations he once berated as a radio talk show host.
</P>
<P>
	   JerryWatch, a group formed by detractors to monitor Brown's doings, has
lampooned his current incarnation as ``Me the People,'' a play on the name of
his grassroots political organization, ``We the People.''
</P>
<P>
	   They are worried that Brown's plan to liven up Oakland's forlorn inner city
with 10,000 new residents will force out the poor and minorities. Oakland today
is 43 percent black, 14 percent Hispanic, 14 percent Asian and 28 percent white.
</P>
<P>
	   Brown said his critics are not thinking clearly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know how many people really are against taking the necessary steps
to create a more prosperous Oakland. It's a very strange position to sustain
except rhetorically.''
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview at an outdoor cafe near City Hall this week, the flimsy
table reverberated as Brown smacked the surface with his hand to punctuate a
passionate explanation of why it's important to recognize Oakland's virtues --
housing bargains, great weather, easy access to San Francisco -- and its vices.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is a tendency toward denial and denial blocks improvement. So while
it might be painful to expose some of the warts, it's the only way we really get
full recovery.''
</P>
<P>
	   Brown doesn't take credit for all the improvements that have happened in his
first year. ``The market pressure has certainly lifted Oakland,'' he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
	   What's next for the former Buddhist scholar, former two-term California
governor, former three-time presidential candidate and former Democrat? (He
re-registered as nonpartisan after moving to Oakland six years ago.)
</P>
<P>
	   Brown said he hasn't decided whether he wants a second term as mayor after
his four years are up.
</P>
<P>
	   As to whether he'd like to swap his current digs, for something, say, larger
and whiter with a view of the Washington Mall, he said, ``That's not a question
you can ask the mayor of Oakland after Year One.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
