<HEADLINE> Cardinal honored during Mass for 80th birthday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The first of several events honoring Cardinal John
O'Connor's upcoming 80th birthday took place at St. Patrick's Cathedral with the
cardinal standing during most of the Mass and sounding strong.
<P>
	   O'Connor, who has complained of weakness in his legs as an aftereffect of
brain surgery and radiation treatment, did not mount the steps to the pulpit,
where he traditionally gives his sermon. But he stood for 20 minutes at a
stretch near the high altar, where he has sat for the past few Sundays.
</P>
<P>
	   The service ended with a vicar from the New York Archdiocese wishing the
cardinal a happy birthday. The cardinal turns 80 on Saturday and is to be feted
that night at a dinner celebrating his 16-year tenure as spiritual leader of the
area's 2 million Catholics. There will also be one more Mass at St. Patrick's
Cathedral next weekend in honor of his birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   While his voice was strong Sunday, O'Connor failed at a couple of points in
his sermon to remember the year World War II ended.
</P>
<P>
	   The lapses came as O'Connor recalled that the dropping of nuclear bombs on
Hiroshima and Nagasaki inspired a flood of young men and women to devote their
lives to the church as nuns, monks and priests.
</P>
<P>
	   "We don't want the horror repeated, but we do want the sacrifices, we do
want the vocations," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In describing the bombings, he said: "It was a horror back in 19--," but he
never finished the sentence. After a brief pause, he added: "At the end of World
War II. It's eluding me."
</P>
<P>
	   The cardinal was ordained to the priesthood at age 25 in late 1945, a few
months after the nuclear bombings of the two Japanese cities and the end of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor's self-deprecating wit was very much in evidence as he joked about
the weight he's gained since the brain tumor was removed in August.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that as he left his residence Sunday morning, "One of my trusted
associates said, 'You look fatter than ever."'
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor credited his interest in the priesthood to the Christian Brothers
who taught him at West Catholic High School in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was because of those brothers that I ultimately entered the seminary,"
he said. "I was very young. People might have said I was too young to be trained
for the seminary."
</P>
<P>
	   O'Connor has said that he does not expect to head the archdiocese much
longer. On Sunday, he repeated several times a quote from the Gospel reading
that seemed to hint at his readiness to have the pope appoint his successor:
"One more powerful than I is to come after me. I am not worthy to stoop and
untie his sandal."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
