<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain To Unveil Tax Plan Tuesday  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. (AP) -- A tax cut plan that Sen. John McCain will roll out
Tuesday is structured to give reductions to 25 million Americans, most of them
lower- and middle-income.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan would also let people invest up to 20 percent of their payroll
taxes in private retirement accounts, based on an investment manual provided by
the government.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, aides said the plan, which the Republican presidential
candidate will fully describe in a speech to the Concord, N.H., Chamber of
Commerce, would:
</P>
<P>
	   --Expand the children's tax credit from $500 per child to $1,000;
</P>
<P>
	   --Introduce a deduction for long-term health care insurance;
</P>
<P>
	   --Create a package of tax incentives for savings targeted toward education,
medical expenses and retirement.
</P>
<P>
	   Previously, McCain said the plan would also propose broadening the bottom,
15 percent tax bracket to cover a couple's first $70,000 of taxable income.
Aides said that if the federal budget surplus grows even more than projected,
McCain would increase the income range a proportional amount.
</P>
<P>
	   Speaking with reporters after addressing a youth forum, McCain contrasted
his proposal with a five-year, $483 billion tax cut proposed by his chief rival
for the GOP nomination, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe that my plan is the far wiser one, and more responsible one,
because it does not assume that these (budget) surpluses are going to be there
forever,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm very optimistic about the economic future of this country, but to bank
it all on unending surpluses at the possible risk of the Social Security trust
fund is our fundamental disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past week, Bush has pounded McCain for opposing his plan, noting in
speeches and GOP debates that it also faces opposition from a Democratic
presidential candidate, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush says his tax plan protects Social Security by creating a ``lockbox''
around the payroll taxes that fund it. On Sunday, after his own speech to the
youth forum, he agreed that the tax debate highlights a ``fundamental
disagreement'' between McCain and himself.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe it is unwise to leave unspent money in Washington, because it
will be spent on bigger government,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush noted that White House and congressional budget analysts are expected
to soon report that budget surpluses for the coming decade may be $800 billion
bigger than last year's $3 trillion estimate.
</P>
<P>
	   The extra money is expected to come from unanticipated federal revenue the
nation's red-hot economy is producing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``That makes the idea of having a paltry tax cut even more risky,'' Bush
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans' Dyson Has Big Highlight Now  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Kevin Dyson has a new favorite moment.
</P>
<P>
	   He gave himself and NFL fans everywhere a play for the history books
Saturday when he took a cross-field lateral from Frank Wycheck and ran 75 yards
for a touchdown with 3 seconds left, lifting the Tennessee Titans to an
improbable 22-16 AFC wild-card victory over the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
	   Tennessee will play at Indianapolis next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   For Dyson, the return topped his previous career highlight of a one-handed
touchdown catch against Arizona in the Freedom Bowl during his freshman year at
Utah.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is definitely No. 1," Dyson said Sunday. "You're in the NFL, your
dream, the playoffs, the first playoff game -- you can't beat that."
</P>
<P>
	   His runback provided a highlight for the ages and ammunition for the critics
who have compared him to the receiver taken five slots after him in 1998's draft
-- Randy Moss. As he spent a quiet rookie year catching two touchdown passes,
Moss turned in a Pro Bowl season with Minnesota and set a rookie record with 19
TD catches.
</P>
<P>
	   Tennessee officials were criticized for choosing Dyson over Moss with the
16th pick overall, and Dyson got tired of being compared him.
</P>
<P>
	   Teammate Derrick Mason, who would have been on the field instead of Dyson if
not for a mild concussion, said maybe people finally will realize that Dyson can
make plays in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't see why everybody should continue to compare him to Randy Moss
because they're two different players. He plays for Minnesota, and that's a
wide-open kind of offense over there. We play over here, and we've kind of got a
balanced offense," Mason said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dyson started this season off with a bang in the season opener, and it
looked like he had finally arrived. He caught nine passes for 162 yards, the
best game by an Oilers-Titans receiver since Haywood Jefferies totaled 186 yards
on Oct. 12, 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   But Steve McNair went out with back surgery for the next five games, and
backup Neil O'Donnell turned more to his favorite receiver, Yancey Thigpen.
Dyson didn't catch more than six passes in a game the rest of the season. When
Thigpen missed five games with a sprained ankle, Dyson struggled with only 10
receptions in his absence.
</P>
<P>
	   Coach Jeff Fisher said he hoped Dyson's return would boost his confidence
after a frustrating season.
</P>
<P>
	   Dyson, Tennessee's second-leading receiver with 54 receptions this season,
is too busy enjoying the attention he's now getting for his astounding return.
</P>
<P>
	   He spent much of Saturday night returning at least 40 telephone messages. He
woke up at least three times to watch the replay of his return on ESPN, and he
watched the play again Sunday at the Titans' practice facility.
</P>
<P>
	   Dyson had no doubts whatsoever about the lateral immediately after the game,
and he said the replays made him realize why so many people were fussing about
referee Phil Luckett upholding the play, calling it "real, real close."
</P>
<P>
	   But he isn't changing his position.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was a lateral. After seeing it, I was at the 25 and he threw it right
about the 25," Dyson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000 Jewish Students Seek Identity  </HEADLINE>
   By DINA KRAFT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The college sophomore from New Jersey tucked a note in the
Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, and stepped back in awe.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can't believe I'm here, it's kind of overwhelming,'' Jessie Oser said,
her blue eyes wide. ``There is a feeling of being connected to all these other
Jews and to history.''
</P>
<P>
	   Oser, 19, who previously felt only tenuous ties to Judaism, is one of 5,000
college students flown here for the launch of Birthright Israel, a $210 million
project that pays for young Jews to travel to Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   The expense-free trip is an expensive new weapon in the Jewish Diaspora's
battle against assimilation. Organizers hope the tour through history will
foster Jewish belonging.
</P>
<P>
	   In the north, participants slosh through the muddy hills of the Golan
Heights and hear from settlers who are both for and against returning the area
captured from Syria in the 1967 Mideast War, an issue at the core of renewed
Israeli-Syria peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   In the south, they climb the stone-strewn path to the ancient fortress of
Masada, where tradition says Jewish zealots killed themselves en masse 2,000
years ago rather than be conquered by Roman troops.
</P>
<P>
	   Oser, a sociology and anthropology major at Tufts University near Boston who
grew up in Princeton, N.J., said she had felt ``disconnected'' from Judaism
because she was not religiously observant.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the program, she knew very few of her fellow Jewish college students
and rarely made it to synagogue.
</P>
<P>
	   This trip ``made me understand that it is more about an identity of
belonging to a people than just a belief in God,'' she said. ``I feel that a
whole new world has just opened up to me.''
</P>
<P>
	   Alarmed by intermarriage rates of 40 percent in the United States, the
project's donors hope to target unaffiliated students like Oser.
</P>
<P>
	   Billionaire Charles Bronfman, who helped launch and fund the project, hopes
to encourage Jews to marry Jewish by instilling participants with a sense of
heritage that will continue when they return home.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our job is to see to it that a society that has done so well materially
and every other way voluntarily wants to stay Jewish,'' Bronfman told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   The money pays for airfare and 10 days of educational programs in Israel for
any Jewish person in the world between the ages of 15 and 26. Most students in
the launch group came from the United States, but there were others from
Australia, the former Soviet Union and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
	   But not everyone thinks the money is well-spent. Some Jewish leaders say
heritage is better preserved by investing in Jewish schools and summer camps in
the Diaspora.
</P>
<P>
	   Israelis are shocked by their own government's pledge of $70 million to the
program over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel, built largely by contributions from the Diaspora, is used to
receiving donations from overseas Jews -- not giving them.
</P>
<P>
	   Bronfman, however, said the trip could form the cornerstone for a renewed
sense of identity.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The soul of the Jewish people is in Jerusalem,'' he said. ``It always has
been and always will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
