<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Scores With Farmers  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CRESTON, Iowa (AP) -- His shiny black shoe propped on a livestock pen rail
smeared with mud and manure, Bill Bradley had an applause-winning answer for
every agriculture question thrown at him. Farmers walked out smiling.
</P>
<P>
	   The exchange at the auction house in sleepy Creston was part of an almost
Jekyll-and-Hyde performance by Bradley on Sunday as the Democratic presidential
candidate tried to keep criticism of his agriculture record from pushing him
farther behind Vice President Al Gore in this farm state.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's two-day bus tour through southwest Iowa was soured from the start
by Gore's dredging up of Bradley votes in the Senate against some emergency aid
to farmers and ethanol subsidies dear to corn growers.
</P>
<P>
	   At a sendoff outside his Des Moines campaign headquarters, Bradley lashed
out at Gore in a raised voice. And he later complained to reporters, ``He's
going around saying I don't have a good record on agriculture policy.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The administration doesn't have a leg to stand on. Where was Al Gore when
we needed a safety net'' for family farmers suffering their worst economic
downturn in a decade, Bradley asked.
</P>
<P>
	   Creston voters heard none of Bradley's complaints about Gore, only a stump
speech newly swollen with talk about the plight of small farmers and specific
aid proposals -- including a new ``Made on a family farm'' label that Bradley
said could add cachet to the products of family farmers the same way designer
labels make blue jeans more appealing.
</P>
<P>
	   By his last appearance of the day, in Council Bluffs, farm policy
disappeared altogether from Bradley's speech and he gamely answered for two high
school girls the same two questions he recently declined in a Wall Street
Journal survey -- his favorite movie recently (``The Green Mile'') and of all
time (``The Loneliness of the Long-distance Runner'').
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley later joked with the girls that he'd been putting them on with the
latter answer.
</P>
<P>
	   The only sign in Creston of a farm-policy problem for Bradley was in the
parking lot: A Gore campaign volunteer dressed as a giant ear of corn and
handing out indictments of the Bradley record.
</P>
<P>
	   Even then, the demonstrator's point was lost on some in Bradley's audience
who mistook him for an oversized pickle.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane noted that the vice president has proposed a
debate specifically on farm issues. ``If Senator Bradley is so interested in
agriculture why won't he debate Al Gore on agriculture?'' Lehane asked.
</P>
<P>
	   With two weeks to go before Iowa's delegate caucuses, Bradley is battling to
reduce Gore's 21-point lead in statewide polls.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said he's aiming to do at least as well here as Sen. Edward
Kennedy's losing 31 percent against Jimmy Carter in 1980. ``We have to do better
than expected,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   By Jan. 24, the caucus date, Bradley will have spent a whopping $1.4 million
on television advertising here -- a sum that campaign manager Gina Glantz said
was equivalent to Gore's Iowa ad expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   The Gore campaign, trying to heighten expectations for Bradley and thus
worsen his fall whatever vote percentage he gets, cites the ad sum as evidence
that Bradley is really out to win here.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley did tell voters gathered at a cafe in Indianola: ``On election
night, I want to surprise a lot of people not only in Iowa but in this
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0236 </TRAILER>
