<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> D.C. Weathers 'a Fiery Trial'  </HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When the year 1800 opened, the straggling settlement on
the Potomac River was more map than city, more hope than reality.
</P>
<P>
	   Two hundred years ago this winter the embryo capital, soon to be called
Washington City, was a construction project with an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
	   But real progress was finally being made against a November deadline. The
U.S. government intended to occupy the city as its permanent home by year's end.
</P>
<P>
	   George Washington, however, was gone. The retired first president had been
the chief patron of a capital on the Potomac. His unexpected death just days
before the new year opened removed the city's steadiest human pillar.
</P>
<P>
	   It also sent a shiver through the city's promoters, who feared that without
him, Congress would refuse to leave the comforts of civilized Philadelphia for a
scraggly landscape of ruts and tree stumps.
</P>
<P>
	   For George Washington, bringing the city this far had been ``a fiery
trial,'' a decade-long fight against greedy self-promoters, quarreling rivals,
shoddy workmanship and a laggard and miserly Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   For a struggling young republic, creating a wholly new city was an enormous
undertaking.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The founding of Washington was the moon shot, the Panama Canal of the
1790s,'' author Bob Arnebeck writes in ``Through a Fiery Trial, Building
Washington, 1790-1800.'' ``How ineptly the politicians, financiers, lawyers and
engineers managed the affair has been forgotten ...''
</P>
<P>
	   But it was all fresh for Isabella Clark, whose contractor husband had been
driven to ruin and madness while working on the city, She drew up a list of
Potomac villains, including ``French poltroons, dolts ..., quacks, bankrupts,
... speculators, monopolizers, extortioners, traitors (and) ham bricklayers.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Washington, who had kept an eye on the slowly rising city from his
retirement roost at nearby Mount Vernon, Va., concluded just days before his
death on Dec. 14, 1799, that the city had navigated the most dangerous eddies of
``local interest, destructive jealousies and inveterate prejudices.''
</P>
<P>
	   By the winter of 1800 it was time to take stock.
</P>
<P>
	   One wing of the Capitol would clearly be finished on time, down to the 16
columns of ``the ancient Ionic order'' on the facade. The rest of the building,
including the dome, would remain a paper monument for years.
</P>
<P>
	   The Treasury building was roofed and the woodwork and floors ready to
install. The War Department walls were up to street level.
</P>
<P>
	   Work on the President's House had been suspended for lack of ready cash, but
most of the interior woodwork was ready to go.
</P>
<P>
	   But there was much mud and no paved roads. A narrow stone footpath connected
the public buildings to the boarding houses where most members of Congress were
expected to live.
</P>
<P>
	   Amid the grumbling, the city's backers rekindled George Washington's spirit.
</P>
<P>
	   Nine days after his death, the House of Representatives voted to ask his
widow, Martha, to permit his body to be transferred to a marble memorial to be
erected under the still-unbuilt Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
	   There was a major obstacle. Washington's will directed that his body rest
permanently in the family's Mount Vernon vault.
</P>
<P>
	   But on New Year's Eve, Martha Washington reluctantly agreed, sacrificing,
she said, her innermost feelings to ``a sense of public duty.''
</P>
<P>
	   For those seeking to move the hero's body practical concerns were at least
as important as patriotism and public duty.
</P>
<P>
	   Entombing Washington's remains in the Capitol would be ``a very great
inducement'' to finishing the building as planned, one advocate said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the shuffle of circumstances, Washington's body never left his native
Virginia. But a place in the Capitol was reserved for it for decades.
</P>
<P>
	   More practically, the city's commissioners worried that the house designated
for President John Adams was a ``naked, ugly-looking building.''
</P>
<P>
	   Adams sent word through his secretary that he hoped the mansion would be
quickly plastered and painted so ``that it may be perfectly dry when he takes
possession.''
</P>
<P>
	   Abigail Adams confessed she was discouraged at the prospects of living in a
house described as ``like to be uncomfortably cold, situated (away) from all
society (and) without furniture.''
</P>
<P>
	   As the winter turned into spring, walls rose, floors were laid, windows were
glazed and buildings were completed. Much of the work was done by slaves hired
from local masters.
</P>
<P>
	   Confidence rose that the new capital might endure and one day prosper.
</P>
<P>
	   ''1800 was the year of the city's destiny,'' Arnebeck wrote. ``And there was
preparation to meet it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House, Congress and
Washington history for The Associated Press for more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0237 </TRAILER>
