<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Older Americans Avoid Crime  </HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elderly Americans are far less likely than younger men
and women to be attacked by violent criminals, and the Justice Department says
it may well be because older people stay home at night more often.
</P>
<P>
	   Each year from 1992 through 1997, there were an average of 5.3 violent
crimes for every 1,000 U.S. residents aged 65 or older, the department's Bureau
of Justice Statistics said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   That was less than one-tenth the rate of violent attacks on younger
Americans; those aged 12-64 suffered an annual average of 56 violent attacks for
every 1,000 residents during each of the same six years.
</P>
<P>
	   The data was based on Census Bureau interviews every six months during the
period with 85,000 Americans 12 and older. In 1997, the elderly, defined by the
report as those 65 or older, made up 12.7 percent of the U.S. population but
accounted for only 7 percent of the crime victims identified in the interviews.
</P>
<P>
	   The report's author, statistician Patsy A. Klaus, said differences in
lifestyle appeared to play a major role in the incidence of violent crime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Elderly victims of nonlethal violence were less likely than younger
victims to go out at night,'' she wrote. About 22 percent of elderly violence
victims reported they never went out at night for entertainment, shopping or
other activities. By comparison, only 3 percent of violence victims under age 50
stayed home at night.
</P>
<P>
	   Klaus also found that the elderly were less likely than younger people to
fight back when attacked. Only 49 percent of elderly violence victims reported
arguing with the assailant, running away, calling for help or attacking the
offender. By comparison, more than 70 percent of those under age 50 took some
self-protective step.
</P>
<P>
	   Crimes against the elderly were more likely to occur in or near their homes
and in the day rather than the night, compared with crimes against younger
victims. Among elderly victims of violent crime, 70 percent of the attacks
occurred in daytime. For all younger victims, daylight attacks comprised less
than 60 percent of the total, and for those aged 25-49 less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Violent attacks near home represented 43 percent of those against the
elderly, but only 26 percent of those against younger people.
</P>
<P>
	   The elderly had lower victimization rates than younger people for every type
of violent and property crime measured by the victimization interviews: rape,
robbery, aggravated assault, simple assault, household burglary, auto theft and
theft.
</P>
<P>
	   The Census Bureau does no victimization interviews in institutions, so
crimes against people in nursing homes are not counted in the estimates, the
Justice Department noted. In 1995, 4 percent of the elderly, or 1.4 million
people 65 or older, were in nursing homes or long-term care institutions.
</P>
<P>
	   The interviews also do not cover fraud and thus do not measure the high rate
at which elderly people are victimized by crooked telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
	   Of all crimes reported by older people during the six-year period, 92
percent were property crimes, compared with 72 percent for younger Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   During the study period, the elderly suffered an annual average of 2.5
million burglaries, thefts and auto thefts; 46,090 purse snatchings or pocket
pickings, 165,330 non-lethal violent crimes and 1,000 murders. The murder data
comes from FBI statistics reported by police departments.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the annual average of 165,330 older people who suffered non-lethal
violence, 22 percent were injured and 6 percent received treatment at a
hospital. Among victims of violence, the rate of serious injury -- gunshots and
stab wounds, broken bones, unconsciousness -- was about the same, 13 percent,
for the elderly as for the overall population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
