<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Monday, Jan. 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Australia Won't Reopen Nazi Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The Australian government on Monday defended its
decision not to reopen an investigation into Nazi war crimes suspect Konrad
Kalejs. Kalejs, 68, a Latvian-born Australian citizen, went into hiding after
returning to Australia last Friday. The Simon Wiesenthal Center, which searches
the world for suspected former Nazis, has said Kalejs served in the notorious
Arajs Kommando, a Nazi killing squad responsible for the death of 30,000 people,
mostly Jews, in Latvia during World War II. He has denied the allegations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israeli-Syrian Talks Winding Down
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton renewed his efforts to push
Israeli and Syrian negotiators toward a land-for-peace treaty with a series of
meetings Sunday evening, but the talks appeared to be winding down without even
a tentative agreement. In a post-midnight session with reporters, Rubin said he
did not expect an agreement to emerge and that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa were likely to meet again "sooner
rather than later."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecuador Head Fixes Exchange Rate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Besieged by calls for his resignation amid a
deepening economic crisis, Ecuador's president announced late Sunday that he was
fixing the exchange rate to stabilize the nation's plummeting currency. n a
20-minute televised address to the nation, President Jamil Mahuad also said that
his 15-member Cabinet had tendered its resignation and that he would name
replacements for the ministers in the coming days. A deal had been hammered out
with Congress to pave the way for approval of several economic reforms, he said,
including "the modernization of the state" -- a term interpreted by many to mean
the privatization of state industries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Machine Tool Production Falls
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Spending on machine tools in November fell 18 percent from
the previous month and was down 7 percent from the year-ago November, according
to two industry groups. Companies spent an estimated $452 million for machine
tools in November, the Association for Manufacturing Technology and the American
Machine Tool Distributors' Association said in a joint statement released
Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Korean War Probe Limited by Army
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The United States will not investigate every
battle of the 1950-53 Korean War, despite allegations that U.S. forces killed
unarmed civilians in dozens of incidents. In an interview with The Associated
Press, Army Secretary Louis Caldera said it is not possible to investigate every
incident of the war in detail. U.S. investigators are already devoting
extraordinary resources to the allegations of a mass killings by U.S. soldiers
at No Gun Ri, South Korea, in the early weeks of the conflict.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban Boy Protests Suspended
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Citywide protests over plans to send Elian Gonzalez back to
Cuba remained on hold Sunday and the six-year-old and his family watched a
parade in Miami. The parade celebrated Three Kings Day, a religious holiday
commemorating the three kings who were said to have traveled to Bethlehem
bearing gifts for the Christ child.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Korea To Buy 100 Israeli Planes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea will buy 100 Israeli-made pilotless
planes this year to beef up its defense against communist North Korea, the
Defense Ministry said Monday. The $52 million deal is part of South Korea's
long-term force improvement program, which puts emphasis on strengthening air
defenses. The Korean peninsula was divided into the communist North and the
capitalist South in 1945. Tension between them remains high, with no peace
treaty signed at the end of the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
SuperSonics 100, Warriors 95 (OT)
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Rashard Lewis hit a go-ahead 3-pointer in overtime
as the Seattle SuperSonics beat the Golden State Warriors 100-95 Sunday night.
Vin Baker's 30 points and 18 rebounds led the Sonics, who beat Golden State for
the third time in three meetings this season. It was the Warriors' ninth
straight loss. Lewis finished with 19 points and Brent Barry added 17.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kings 116, Pacers 113
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Webber had 31 points on 15-of-26 shooting
and Nick Anderson added a season-high 25 points as the Kings defeated the Pacers
116-113 Sunday night. Corliss Williamson had 23 points and nine rebounds for the
Kings and Vlade Divac, playing his first home game since shaving off his
mustache and beard, added 16 points. Jason Williams had 15 assists.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</P>
