<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Syrian Talks Winding Down  </HEADLINE>
   By DONNA ABU-NASR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Peace talks between Israel and Syria dwindled
down to an inconclusive recess, with President Clinton trying to narrow
differences in what his spokesman called ``difficult and complex'' issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Today was to be the last working day in which the Israeli and Syrian
delegation leaders would participate. It was not clear whether the four working
groups of experts handling the technical negotiations would stay behind.
</P>
<P>
	   An administration official said Clinton was unlikely to return to
Shepherdstown today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Clearly we are coming to the end of the leaders' participation here this
week,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said he did not expect an agreement to emerge but that Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa were likely to
meet again ``sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
	   Barak was making plans to depart for home later today. Al-Sharaa was likely
to follow on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   On Sunday, Clinton renewed his efforts to energize the talks, returning to
the negotiating site 70 miles northwest of Washington for the fifth time in the
weeklong negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is an ongoing process. The issues are difficult and complex,'' said
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
	   The president brought together Barak and al-Sharaa for their third
face-to-face meeting, this time over a 2 1/2-hour dinner at the National
Conservation Training Center during which the Israeli and Syrian leaders broke
bread together for the first time. The leaders enjoyed a meal of tenderloin of
beef with morel sauce, along with chardonnay and merlot wines.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton later held separate meetings with al-Sharaa and Barak.
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said Clinton felt that ``it was a very good and serious exchange of
views'' and all issues came up at dinner.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was a fairly warm atmosphere,'' the spokesman added. ``It was pretty
cordial.''
</P>
<P>
	   A source close to the Syrian delegation said the trilateral meeting focused
on the work of the four committees, especially the border committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The source said al-Sharaa told Clinton the function of that panel was the
demarcation of borders and not again discussing withdrawal proposals.
</P>
<P>
	   Al-Sharaa said that Syria stands by its demand that Israel pull back to the
June 4, 1967, border and that Damascus will not compromise on the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Committees met Sunday on all the key issues -- the demarcation of borders,
security arrangements, normal peaceful relations and water sharing.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Department's Rubin said the seven-page document could become the
basis for an eventual ``core agreement.'' But he said Israel and Syria still
faced ``enormous decisions'' and ``we don't expect those decisions to be made in
a matter of days,''
</P>
<P>
	   American mediators had not offered ``bridging proposals'' designed to close
the gap where the two sides were in disagreement, Rubin added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0301 </TRAILER>
