<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afrikaners Urged To Join ANC  </HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW SELSKY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- During apartheid, the world came to know
Pik Botha as a defender of white rule. Now, the former foreign minister
describes Nelson Mandela as a great man and expresses interest in joining his
African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the 1994 all-race elections ended white rule, several high-profile
members of the National Party have defected.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think I can associate myself with (the ANC's) fundamental principles,''
Botha told South African Broadcasting Corp. today. ``All of us changed. The
present day ANC is not the ANC that was when we were in conflict with each
other.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Sunday, he was quoted in a Johannesburg newspaper as saying: ``Whites,
especially the Afrikaners, must get down from their pedestals.''
</P>
<P>
	   For some, it may be an awakening to new moral values. For others, it is
simple pragmatism. The National Party did poorly in elections last year and
faces possible extinction as whites split their votes among a handful of
opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The National Party is gone ... its history is just too heavy,'' said Roelf
Meyer, a former top National Party official who resigned in 1997 and formed the
United Democratic Movement.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the latest converts is Botha, who as the apartheid state's foreign
minister for 17 years defended the system in international forums. Botha is now
urging other Afrikaners -- the descendants of European settlers who largely
supported the National Party -- to support the ANC, although he has ruled out
any active political role for himself.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The process of healthy political regrouping and restructuring will only
start when Afrikaners join the ANC,'' Botha said Sunday, adding that he liked
the ruling party's policies of freedom of speech and religion, and the
protection of private property.
</P>
<P>
	   In the interview with City Press, he took a few shots at F.W. de Klerk, the
country's last apartheid-era president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Mandela succeeded in his bid to reach out to whites without bitterness. De
Klerk did not manage to reach out to blacks,'' Botha was quoted as saying. Botha
also said there was a higher level of debate in Mandela's Cabinet than in de
Klerk's.
</P>
<P>
	   After the ANC won the 1994 elections, Botha served in Mandela's government
of national unity for two years as Cabinet minister of minerals and energy. When
de Klerk, who was deputy president in the unity government, pulled out, Botha
followed suit and largely disappeared from public view.
</P>
<P>
	   The 67-year-old Botha's reappearance in recent interviews indicated a
transformation. But it was not so surprising for a man who had begun moderating
his views on apartheid in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1986, Botha was criticized in National Party circles when he expressed
his belief that South Africa might one day have a black leader.
</P>
<P>
	   In City Press, Botha said he thought Mandela's successor, President Thabo
Mbeki, was continuing with the process of racial reconciliation that Mandela
started.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
