<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skins May Face Bucs Without Davis  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSEPH WHITE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Imagine having two seldom-used offensive linemen and no
power runner on the field against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' fearsome defense.
</P>
<P>
	   That's the scenario the Washington Redskins might face Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's very, very scary," coach Norv Turner said. "We've been fortunate to go
through the season with great health."
</P>
<P>
	   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen Davis, the NFC's leading rusher, and center Cory Raymer are
classified as "doubtful," and left tackle Andy Heck is already ruled out for the
divisional playoff game at Tampa.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis sat in the basement of Redskin Park on Sunday with ice on his left
ankle and right knee. He sprained the ankle three weeks ago at Indianapolis and
made his return in Saturday's 27-13 first-round victory over Detroit. He wasn't
100 percent, but he ran for 119 yards and two touchdowns before spraining a knee
ligament when his leg was hooked by defensive tackle Dan Owens five minutes into
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if he'll be able to play against Tampa Bay, Davis said: "I'll be ready
-- hopefully."
</P>
<P>
	   Turner also tried to be hopeful, but he threw in a heavy dash of realism.
</P>
<P>
	   "Stephen says the right things," Turner said. "He certainly wants to play.
I'm an optimist and think he'll play, hope he'll play. Medically, the problems
have been doubled. His ankle is sore from playing on it, and his knee is sore. I
think he's sorer than he's letting on. There's a reason we're listing him
doubtful."
</P>
<P>
	   Davis rushed for 1,405 yards this season, made the Pro Bowl and averaged 4.8
yards per carry. His backup, Skip Hicks, rushed for 257 yards, averaged 3.3
yards and lacks Davis' vision when it comes to following his blockers. In
Saturday's game, Davis averaged 7.9 yards on 15 carries, Hicks just 2.0 on 23
carries for 46 yards.
</P>
<P>
	   Heck suffered a torn hamstring on an extra-point attempt in the first
quarter. He was on crutches Sunday and is probably done for the season.
</P>
<P>
	   His backup is fifth-year tackle Kipp Vickers, who actually started a playoff
game with Indianapolis four years ago. Vickers also started six regular-season
games for the Colts in 1996, but hasn't started a game since. He was used
sparingly in 11 of 16 regular-season games this season.
</P>
<P>
	   "He doesn't have the experience Andy has, but one thing is, he's very
physical in the running game," Turner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Turner said he will play Vickers ahead of Brad Badger, who moved from guard
to start 10 games at left tackle last season in an experiment that didn't work.
</P>
<P>
	   Raymer's situation is the most muddled. He pulled a muscle in the right side
of his rib cage and stayed in the game. Turner said he felt Raymer would be
fine, but trainer Bubba Tyer was much more cautious.
</P>
<P>
	   "He'd be doubtful today," Tyer said. "But we'll just take him day to day."
</P>
<P>
	   Raymer's backup is Mark Fischer, a second-year center who has never played
an offensive snap in the NFL. He was used on special teams for six games last
season and has not played at all this season.
</P>
<P>
	   There's an outside chance the Redskins could lose a fourth starter. Pro Bowl
guard Tre Johnson will almost certainly be fined by the league for striking an
official in the head during a fight in the second half of the victory over the
Lions, and a suspension is also possible.
</P>
<P>
	   "It certainly wasn't intentional," Turner said. "It was poor judgment on
Tre's part, and from everything I've heard it would be a case of being fined."
</P>
<P>
	   The Redskins have been one of the healthiest teams in the NFL this season,
one of the big reasons they went 10-6 and won the NFC East. They lost only 11
man-games due to injuries -- nine on offense, two on defense. Five of those came
when guard Keith Smith had a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
	   Now disaster has hit all at once, and it came amid the joyous celebrations
of a victory in the franchise's first playoff game in seven years.
</P>
<P>
	   Tampa Bay is ranked third in total defense. Four linemen -- Warren Sapp,
Marcus Jones, Chidi Ahanotu, Brad Culpepper -- have six sacks or more.
</P>
<P>
	   "Their defensive front, it's so quick, so fast," Turner said. "They've got
an outstanding blitz package. If you're not ready to play, it can be humbling."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0307 </TRAILER>
