<DOCNO> APW20000110.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 03:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins 20, Seahawks 17  </HEADLINE>
    By STEVEN WINE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Dan Marino's last game could be three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
	   "If he wins the Super Bowl, he's done," said his agent, Marvin Demoff. "If
that happens, I think everyone would like to see him retire."
</P>
<P>
	   Marino moved one win closer to his first championship ring Sunday, leading
the Miami Dolphins to a 20-17 victory over the Seattle Seahawks in an AFC
wild-card playoff game.
</P>
<P>
	   The victory temporarily delayed questions whether Marino, 38, will retire.
Instead, the question becomes how far the sentimental favorite in these playoffs
can go.
</P>
<P>
	   "Maybe Dan will get the Super Bowl ring he deserves to cap off a great
career," Seattle quarterback Jon Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dolphins, who earned their first road playoff victory since 1972, still
face a tough path to the title game. They play Saturday at Jacksonville (14-2)
and would also be on the road in the AFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
	   "If we win two more, we've got a shot," Marino said.
</P>
<P>
	   He won Sunday by playing exactly the way Jimmy Johnson wants. There was no
sign of the simmering discord between quarterback and coach, and both credited a
conservative game plan for the victory.
</P>
<P>
	   Marino handed off more than he passed and -- for only the fourth time this
season -- he threw no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
	   "We talked about running the ball, and we ran it a lot," the most prolific
passer in NFL history said. "We wanted to play good defense, not turn it over
and have a chance to win at the end. It worked out perfect."
</P>
<P>
	   But Miami (10-7) needed a little Marino magic in the final quarter to pull
out the victory. With nine minutes left and the Dolphins trailing 17-13, he went
4-for-7 for 84 yards on a drive that produced the decisive touchdown.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense did the rest. Trace Armstrong had three of Miami's six sacks, and
Seattle (9-8) totaled only 32 yards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have no clue as to how they were able to push us around like they did,"
Seahawks running back Ricky Watters said. "They controlled us and really handled
us. They made us look pretty bad."
</P>
<P>
	   Miami's fourth-quarter comeback was the 37th of Marino's career.
</P>
<P>
	   "Dan did a great job of executing the plan," Johnson said. "And he did a
great job of throwing the ball."
</P>
<P>
	   Marino and Johnson have clashed repeatedly this season over the
quarterback's play, and tension between them has fueled speculation that both
will retire after this season.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not an easy relationship," Demoff said while watching the game from
the press box. "But they can work together without being best friends."
</P>
<P>
	   They proved it Sunday. Johnson, annoyed by Marino's risky decisions and 17
interceptions this season, was delighted that a cautious attack rolled up 108
yards rushing against Seattle and controlled the ball for nearly 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   Marino finished 17-for-30 for a modest 196 yards.
</P>
<P>
	   "I know Dan probably wants to hang back there and wing it a little more,"
Johnson said, "but it helps to run for 100 yards."
</P>
<P>
	   Marino completed his first pass for 17 yards, but the Dolphins netted just 6
yards through the air the rest of the first half. Once Miami even ran on
third-and-6 at midfield.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservative strategy produced five first downs in the opening half and
a 10-3 deficit for the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
	   "There were some situations where we could have thrown it more," Marino
said. "But we wanted to wait."
</P>
<P>
	   "We knew we were going to pound and pound," receiver Oronde Gadsden said.
"Then the safeties come up and you get one-on-one coverage, and that plays into
Dan's hands."
</P>
<P>
	   Marino began throwing more on the opening series of the second half, and a
60-yard drive ended with his 1-yard touchdown pass to Gadsden, making the score
10-10. Seattle regained the lead when rookie Charlie Rogers returned the ensuing
kickoff 85 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
	   The game's pivotal play came with 8:26 left and the Dolphins trailing 17-13.
On third-and-17 at the Miami 8, Marino hit Tony Martin for 23 yards to start the
winning drive. He later hit Gadsden on third-and-10 for 24 yards to set up the
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
	   Marino said he never considered the possibility that the possession could be
the last of his career if the Dolphins were stopped.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's so much going on, with crowd noise and everything, I'm not that
smart," he said. "I'm worried about just trying to win."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0309 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
