<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 03:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hockey Today  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press SCOREBOARD Monday, Jan. 10
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Phoenix at N.Y. Islanders (7:30 p.m. EST). The Pacific Division-leading
Coyotes visit the Islanders, the NHL's worst team.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Doug Gilmour, Blackhawks, had a goal and an assist as Chicago defeated
Colorado 5-3.
</P>
<P>
	   -- Arturs Irbe, Hurricanes, made 30 saves as Carolina blanked the New York
Rangers 1-0.
</P>
<P>
	   Arturs Irbe, pulled in the second period of Friday night's 4-4 tie with
Anaheim after giving up three goals, was sharp on Sunday night. Irbe, despite a
small battle with the flu, stopped 30 shots for his third shutout of the season
and 22nd of his career as Carolina blanked the New York Rangers 1-0.
</P>
<P>
	   Colorado's Peter Forsberg scored two goals, but the Avalanche couldn't come
back Sunday night, losing 5-3 to the Blackhawks. Forsberg, who scored his goals
two minutes apart in the second period, also extended his point streak to eight
straight games.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest Division-leading Colorado had its five-game (4-0-1) unbeaten
streak snapped by a 5-3 loss to Chicago on Sunday night. The Blackhawks, who
have the league's third-worst home record, posted consecutive home victories for
the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
	   Wendel Clark signed a contract with Toronto on Sunday, contingent on him
being in shape to play. It will be the left wing's third stint with the Maple
Leafs and comes after his release by the Blackhawks last month. The 14-year
veteran had two goals in 13 games with Chicago this season. Last season, Clark
played with Tampa Bay (28 goals, 42 points in 65 games) and Detroit (four goals,
six points in 12 games and two goals, three assists in 10 playoff games).
</P>
<P>
	   Peter White had a goal and two assists as the Philadelphia Phantoms tied a
club record with five power-play goals in a 7-4 victory over the Springfield
Falcons in AHL action Sunday. Seven players scored to help Philadelphia extend
its season-high winning streak to seven games. Both teams combined for 256
penalty minutes in a fight-marred contest, with the Phantoms accumulating 130
for a new team mark.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was pretty much dead meat from 6 o'clock last night until midnight, and
today I felt like I was laboring hard. Usually, I am just gliding in the net and
barely break a sweat in a game." -- Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe, who played with
a fever and chills, on his 30-save, shutout performance in the Hurricanes' 1-0
victory over the New York Rangers on Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
