<HEADLINE> National Hockey League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID DROSCHAK AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- After a dismal December, the Carolina Hurricanes are
starting to turn things in their favor.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a good time to be playing well," Carolina coach Paul Maurice said
following Sunday night's 1-0 victory over the New York Rangers, improving the
Hurricanes' record to 4-2-1 in their last seven contests. "All these games are
so important."
</P>
<P>
	   A tight playoff chase has developed between about six Eastern Conference
teams for a couple of postseason spots. The Hurricanes have 42 points and trail
sixth-place Pittsburgh by two heading into a seven-game stretch against
conference foes.
</P>
<P>
	   After losing seven of nine in one December stretch, Carolina rebounded in
with wins over Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "It shows what we have here, that we don't collapse under pressure and
really pull off the best efforts when it's necessary," said Arturs Irbe, who
stopped 30 shots for his 22nd career shutout.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is great news," Irbe said of Carolina's recent surge. "We should be
able to pull if off in the end when it counts. But hopefully we can win some
games when it's not a must-win situation."
</P>
<P>
	   In the only other NHL game, Chicago beat Colorado 5-3.
</P>
<P>
	   Irbe, 3-1 against New York last season with a stellar 1.56 goals against
average, stymied the Rangers again despite playing with the flu.
</P>
<P>
	   The 32-year-old goalie, pulled from Friday night's tie with Anaheim after
giving up three goals, was sharp this time in notching his third shutout of the
season.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was important to the rest of the team to see him bounce back," Maurice
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Andrei Kovalenko's second-period goal was the game-winner. He has 10 goals
in 22 games against the Rangers, one of the teams trailing Carolina in the
playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
	   New York, coming off a pair of wins over Toronto, couldn't string together
its third three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not frustrated at all," Rangers coach John Muckler said. "We played
well enough to win the hockey game, we just had the misfortune of losing it
because we couldn't score goals. That's where the improvement has to be."
</P>
<P>
	   The Hurricanes, urged by coach Paul Maurice to shoot more, complied for a
third straight game. Carolina, which moved back to the .500 mark, fired 28 shots
at New York goalie Mike Richter, who was spectacular at times.
</P>
<P>
	   "You hate to spoil a performance like that and not get a goal for him,"
Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kovalenko's goal came on a great individual effort 6:34 into the second. The
left winger circled into the slot with a New York defenseman trailing and lifted
a back-handed shot over Richter's glove.
</P>
<P>
	   "His strength is such that if he gets beside you, he's got you beat,"
Maurice said. "He has been a heck of a player for us this year."
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Roberts picked up one of the assists on Kovalenko's eighth goal to
extend his point streak to eight games.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rangers, who scored at least one power-play goal in five straight road
games, were shut out Sunday by the NHL's best home penalty-killing unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Gilmour had a goal and an assist as Chicago snapped Colorado's
five-game unbeaten streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Dean McAmmond, Eric Daze, Tony Amonte, Alex Zhamnov also scored for Chicago,
which has consecutive home victories for the first time this season. Steve
Sullivan assisted on two goals for the Blackhawks, who have the league's
second-worst home record at 6-12-3.
</P>
<P>
	   Colorado's Peter Forsberg scored goals two minutes apart in the second
period, extending his point streak to eight games.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Drury had the other Colorado goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0314 </TRAILER>
