<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Basketball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID GINSBURG AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Duke has once again established itself as the team
to beat in the Atlantic Coast Conference.
</P>
<P>
	   Maryland, on the other hand, now faces the task of climbing out of a very
unfamiliar position: the ACC cellar.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Carrawell scored 20 points and freshman Carlos Boozer had 17 points
and 15 rebounds as the sixth-ranked Blue Devils cruised past No. 18 Maryland
80-70 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Duke (11-2, 2-0) never trailed after a 14-point run made it 14-4. The
victory came just four days after the Blue Devils won in overtime at Virginia.
</P>
<P>
	   "Any time you can start your ACC schedule 2-0, home or away, that's huge,"
said Carrawell, the only senior on the Duke roster. "But two games on the road
against two tough teams, I've never done that before in my career. Now we get to
go home."
</P>
<P>
	   The Terrapins (11-4, 0-2) hoped to rebound from Thursday's road loss against
North Carolina State, but Duke took control early and ended a 14-game home
winning streak that began immediately after last season's game against the Blue
Devils.
</P>
<P>
	   "They've had success everywhere over the years," Maryland coach Gary
Williams said. "They're a good basketball team. That's why they win here."
</P>
<P>
	   The Blue Devils have won six straight over Maryland, including the last
three at Cole Field House by a total of 60 points. Duke has reeled off 11
straight wins after starting 0-2 and have a 24-game winning streak in the ACC,
including 13 in a row on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   "We feel very good about beating a very good basketball team on their home
court and to start out the league with two road wins," Blue Devils coach Mike
Krzyzewski said. "It's sensational for our team."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked if his team has established some momentum, Krzyzewski replied, "Our
club is too young to even understand momentum. We're still on one-syllable
words.
</P>
<P>
	   "I just know that you keep getting better by being in tough situations,
especially if you end up being successful," he said. "We've had a very tough
schedule. If we didn't play early on the road the first few weeks of the season,
I don't think we would have won these two games."
</P>
<P>
	   In the other only game involving a ranked team on Sunday, No. 17 Ohio State
beat Minnesota 71-63.
</P>
<P>
	   The Terrapins missed 20 of their first 25 shots from the field, but were
only down 39-34 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
	   A jumper in the lane by Juan Dixon pulled Maryland to 51-47 with 11:06 to
play, but Carrawell hit a 3-pointer to start a 13-1 run. He again connected from
beyond the arc to make it 61-48 with 7:58 left, effectively ending any hope the
Terrapins had of mounting a comeback.
</P>
<P>
	   Terence Morris had 18 points and 13 rebounds for the Terrapins, while Lonny
Baxter added 14 points and 16 rebounds. But Morris was 6-for-15 from the field
and Baxter was 7-for-23, a big reason why Maryland finished at 34 percent for
the game.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was one of those days," said Baxter, who missed 13 of his first 16
shots. "We had great shots; they just didn't fall."
</P>
<P>
	   And now Maryland has tumbled all the way into last place in the conference.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why we didn't shoot the ball well, I don't know," Williams said. "We've got
some time to work on some things. We will get better offensively."
</P>
<P>
	   In each of the past two games, the Terrapins found themselves working to dig
themselves out of an early hole. Maryland fell behind N.C. State 18-4 and
trailed Duke 14-4 with less than six minutes elapsed.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had easy shots; we just didn't finish," said Dixon, who was 6-for-18
from the field. "We make those shots early and we're in it at the end. The last
two games, we're always playing catch up. We can't keep doing that."
</P>
<P>
	   The backcourt of Michael Redd and Scoonie Penn accounted for 45 points, and
the Buckeyes (9-3, 1-1) came up big at the free-throw line, making 10 of 12 in
the final five minutes. Ohio State was the Big Ten's worst free-throw shooting
team last season. Penn, who finished with 20 points, made four free throws in
the final 21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Joel Przybilla had 15 points, 14 rebounds and seven blocks for the visiting
Golden Gophers (9-3, 1-1).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0317 </TRAILER>
