<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Facing Recruiting Troubles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the economy booming, jobs plentiful and expectations
high, the American military faces a critical watershed as the new millennium
opens, a private study group reported today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``For many of today's youth, enlisting in the military is an alien
thought,'' the Center for Strategic and International Studies said in a two-year
study of military culture. ``With the number of veterans dwindling, local
advocates and role models are fading in number.''
</P>
<P>
	   All branches of the all-volunteer armed services face tremendous pressures
in recruiting and retaining qualified men and women for today's computerized
high-tech warfare, the study said.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation no longer has an identifiable major military adversary. But at no
comparable period in peacetime history has the United States leaned more heavily
or frequently on its armed forces for such missions as peacekeeping and drug
intervention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In an era when `peacetime' America has never been safer from military
aggression, ... this volunteer force has never been busier,'' the
Washington-based center said. 'Today, the smallest force in four decades -- with
56 percent married -- is overworked, underpaid and underresourced at the cutting
edge.''
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Cmdr. Terry Sutherland, a Pentagon spokesman, could not comment on the
study because he said he has not seen it. ``We look forward to reading it,''
Sutherland said.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said there is little doubt that conditions within the armed
forces are far less favorable than they were even 10 years ago, and the U.S.
military faces ``potentially serious rifts in its culture.''
</P>
<P>
	   Today's soldiers are older and more often married than in the days when the
ranks were filled with young draftees. Consequently, the study found, modern
warriors have higher expectations on matters that affect the quality of their
lives and the satisfaction they experience in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   Military policy-makers face difficult choices on how best to spend their
budgets on new weapons, maintaining bases and facilities, training personnel,
repairing aging equipment, increasing pay and finding money for unforeseen
contingencies.
</P>
<P>
	   The study, based on responses by thousands of military men and women, offers
numerous recommendations that the authors maintain could help Pentagon leaders
better cope with the needs of their troops.
</P>
<P>
	   The public must be better educated about how military culture and the
demands it makes on soldiers and their families differ from civilian life, the
report said. And, it said, the stress level must be reduced by either increasing
the military's resources or reducing or redesigning its missions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 0319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0059 </DOCNO>
