<HEADLINE> China, Singapore Plan Data Links  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SINGAPORE (AP) -- StarHub, a Singapore telecommunications company, said
Monday it has concluded an agreement with China Telecom that allows direct voice
and data links between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Singapore's outgoing phone call traffic to China is growing at an estimated
20 percent a year, StarHub said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   "This robust rate is expected to continue in coming years, given the healthy
economic investment and bilateral trade between the two countries," StarHub
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said Singapore is the seventh largest route for China's outgoing
call traffic. China Telecom is the largest telecommunications operator in China.
</P>
<P>
	   More than three-quarters of Singapore's 3.2 million people are ethnic
Chinese, and the Chinese language is widely spoken in the prosperous island
republic.
</P>
<P>
	   StarHub's commercial operations will begin April 1.
</P>
<P>
	   With the latest agreement, StarHub has deals with 16 international carriers
in 12 countries, including the United States, the United Kingdom and various
Asia-Pacific nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
