<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 100.59; Nasdaq Up 128.70  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened sharply higher today as the market's
enthusiasm soared on the news of the $166 billion combination of America Online
and Time Warner. Technology stocks led the gains.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 100.59 at 11,623.15, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 128.70
at 4,011.32.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 21.86 at 1,463.33.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL was up 5 3/4 to 79 1/2 and Time Warner was up 34 1/4 to 99 after their
early morning announcement of their deal, the largest ever between a
traditional, old-line media company and an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's bold move to acquire Time Warner gave investors added evidence that
the Internet will be one of the most dominant features in the economy of the
future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service providers: Yahoo! rose
35 47/64 to 442 63/64 and Lycos rose 6 13/16 to 77 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Also today, Alcoa rose  5/8 to 85 1/4 after reporting it earned 89 cents per
share in the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per
share. Alcoa's board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its
stock 2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 140.29 million shares, behind Friday's busy
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 8.74 to 497.05.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.1 percent. European market
measures rose sharply, with Germany's DAX index up 2.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE
100 up 1.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 up 3.0 percent in afternoon trading.
</P>
