<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 10, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   AOL To Buy Time Warner for $166B
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner, the world's largest media and
entertainment company, is being acquired by America Online for
about $166 billion in stock in what would be the biggest corporate
merger ever. The deal announced today raises the stakes in the
consolidation scramble in the media industry and comes just four
months after another blockbuster media merger, the proposed
combination of CBS Corp. and Viacom Inc. The merger unites the
biggest name in the traditional media world the biggest name in the
new media world, marking the biggest bet yet that the Internet will
be one of the most dominant features in the media landscape of the
future.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Gains 70.73; Nasdaq Up 108.11
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened sharply higher today as the
market's enthusiasm soared on the news of the $166 billion
combination of America Online and Time Warner. Technology stocks
led the gains. Just before 11 a.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 70.73 at 11,593.29, and the Nasdaq composite index
was up 108.11 at 3990.73. AOL stock was up 2 1/8 at 75 9/16 and Time
Warner was up 34 1/4 at 99 after their early morning announcement of
their deal. The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service
providers: Yahoo! rose 35 47/64 to 442 63/64 and Lycos rose 6 13/16
to 77 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EST:
