</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft Temps May Be Rewarded
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused for the second
time in two years to free Microsoft from possibly having to pay
thousands of former temporary employees who were not allowed to
join the company's lucrative stock-purchase program. The justices,
without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that,
according to Microsoft's unsuccessful appeal, ``has far-reaching
implications for the field of employment law.'' Eight people who
once worked for the computer software company sued in 1992, saying
they and thousands more ``permatemps'' illegally had been illegally
shut out of an employee stock purchase plan that allows employees
to buy Microsoft stock at a discount.
</P>
<P>
	   New Cases of Mad Cow Disease Found
</P>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- French officials have discovered two new cases of
mad cow disease, the Agriculture Ministry said today. The cases,
detected late last year, bring to 31 the number of cows discovered
with the disease in France in 1999. One of the diseased cows was in
the northwest region of Brittany, while the other was found in the
central region of Creuse. Their herds, a total of 341 cows, were
slaughtered late last week. New cases of the disease are expected
to appear until 2001, five years after stringent prevention
measures were taken to prevent outbreaks, the Agriculture Ministry
has said. The disease has an average incubation period of five
years.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Health Care Bill Grew in 1998
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pushed by rising costs for prescription drugs
and insurance premiums, growth in the nation's health care bill
accelerated in 1998. Private health care spending increased by 6.9
percent, compared with a 4.8 percent rise in 1997. Growth in
government spending -- on programs such as Medicare, for the elderly
and disabled -- slowed to 4.1 percent, according to an annual report
from the Health Care Financing Administration. Total health care
spending rose 5.6 percent in 1998, compared with 4.7 percent in
1997. The increase was the biggest since an 8.7 percent jump in
1993.
</P>
<P>
	   LA Times Promotes Two Editors
</P>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times has promoted newsroom
veteran Leo Wolinsky to executive editor and created a new position
to oversee the relationship between the editorial and business
departments. Wolinsky, one of four managing editors, was promoted
to the new position. Ardith Hilliard, editor of the paper's San
Fernando Valley edition, was named associate editor with
responsibility for implementing new ethical guidelines. Both will
report to Editor Michael Parks. The new guidelines were adopted by
the paper in response to a much-criticized revenue-sharing deal
with the city's Staples Center arena.
</P>
<P>
	   Sino-i.com To Use IBM Software
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- A Hong Kong group said today it will use
software from International Business Machines Corp. for an
electronic-commerce Web site targeting small- and medium-sized
businesses in mainland China. Sino-i.com Ltd. expects to have its
Chinese-language site fully operational by the third quarter of
2000. Company officials estimated that the site could generate $1
billion in wholesale transactions this year. Chinese companies will
be able to use the ChinaEnterprise.com site to shop for more than
15,000 products ranging from clothing to tractors, executives said
today.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador Pegs Currency to U.S. Dollar
</P>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's president sought to stabilize
the nation's plummeting currency by pegging it to the U.S. dollar,
despite opposition from the central bank. Amid calls for his
resignation and a worsening economic crisis, President Jamil Mahuad
also announced late Sunday in a 20-minute televised address to the
nation that his 15-member Cabinet had tendered its resignation. He
said he would name replacements in the coming days. A deal was
hammered out with Congress to pave the way for approval of several
economic reforms, he said, including ``the modernization of the
state'' -- a term interpreted by many to mean the privatization of
state industries.
</P>
<P>
	   Asian Stock Markets Close Higher
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed sharply higher
Monday, boosted by Friday's record gains on Wall Street. In Hong
Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 442.52 points, or 2.9
percent, closing at 15,848.15. South Korean shares also soared,
with the main index surging 4.1 percent on the back of gains on
Wall Street. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 38.59
points to 987.24. Taiwan shares closed at a 21-month high, powered
by ample liquidity and rallies in international markets. The Taipei
exchange's Weighted Stock Price Index rose 257.13 points, or 2.9
percent, to 9,102.60. Tokyo financial markets were closed today for
Coming-of-Age Day, a national holiday. Markets reopen tomorrow.
</P>
