<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Pushing China for WTO  </HEADLINE>
    By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House plans a campaign-style push to convince
Congress that China belongs in the trade-regulating World Trade Organization, a
Clinton administration official said today.
</P>
<P>
	   The press in Congress is likely to be the last big trade fight of President
Clinton's two terms in office. Like trade deals before it, the China-WTO fight
will make strange bedfellows; Republicans tend to support the deal while the
pro-union Democrats who are Clinton's traditional allies oppose it.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House will concentrate on rounding up Republican votes to admit
China to the WTO this year, White House officials said. Clinton will meet with
his full Cabinet on Jan. 19 to gin up ideas to reach out to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was to announce today that a team headed by Commerce Secretary
William Daley and White House deputy chief of staff Steve Ricchetti will lead
the effort. Ricchetti is a veteran lobbyist. Daley led the White House war room
in 1993 in the administration's successful drive to win approval of the North
American Free Trade Agreement with Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   The leading opponent of trade deals with China are organized labor,
environmental groups and human rights organizations. On the other side are
business leaders who view China, the world's most populous country, as a vast
untapped market.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents argue that China should be held to the same environmental and
labor standards as American companies and workers. China and other poor
countries see that as an attempt by rich nations to strip them of the
competitive advantages they enjoy with lower wage levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
