<HEADLINE> Dow Up 50.88; Nasdaq Up 92.92  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were sharply higher today as investors reacted
enthusiastically to the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner. Technology stocks led the gains.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 50.88 at 11,573.44, extending a Friday rally that left the
blue-chip index at an all-time closing high of 11,522.56.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader market indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite index was
up 92.92 at 3,975.54, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 10.46 at
1,451.93.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared 24 5/16 to 89 1/16 and AOL slipped 1 3/8 to 72 1/16 after
the early morning announcement of their deal, the largest ever between a
traditional, old-line media company and an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's bold move to acquire Time Warner gave investors added evidence that
the Internet will be one of the most dominant features in the economy of the
future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This deal took great vision and courage," said Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. "It shows that the high valuations that many
analysts have been uncomfortable with may be justified."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service providers as investors
looked ahead to further combinations with media companies. Yahoo! rose 17 17/64
to 432 17/64 and Lycos rose 4 1/4 to 76 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Disney rose 3 11/16 to 34 13/16, leading the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa rose 11/16 to 85 5/16 after reporting it earned 89 cents per share in
the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per share.
Alcoa's board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its stock
2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 350.13 million shares, behind Friday's busy
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 8.60 to 496.91.
</P>
</TEXT>
