<HEADLINE> Soybeans Fall on S. American Rain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices fell sharply in early dealings today on the
Chicago Board of Trade after weekend rains doused soybean-growing regions in
South America and more rain was expected this week.
</P>
<P>
	   Grains also were lower.
</P>
<P>
	   The showers improved prospects for the soybean crop in southern Brazil,
where months of dry weather have raised questions about the next harvest.
</P>
<P>
	   A pair of wet weather systems are expected to dump more rain on that region
as well as eastern Argentina this week, improving crop chances while pressuring
futures prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn opened lower in sympathy with soybeans.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat initially edged higher but also was dragged down by soybeans.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery fell 2 cents to $2.49 3/4 a bushel; March corn fell
1 cent to $2.06 a bushel; March oats fell 1 cent to $1.08 1/2 a bushel; March
soybeans fell 5 cents to $4.73 3/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle fell .05 cent to 70.82 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle fell .10 cent to 86.77 cents a pound; February lean hogs rose 1.13 cents
to 56.30 cents a pound; February frozen pork bellies fell .82 cent to 81.40
cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
