<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
    By ERIC FIDLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   "Cruel Moon" (Hightone) -- Buddy Miller
</P>
<P>
	   Buddy Miller makes country music the way God and Hank Williams intended it,
and he has reached greatness with his third Hightone release, "Cruel Moon."
</P>
<P>
	   Miller, with help from wife Julie and other country musicians so traditional
they're considered alternative, has crafted an album so full of grit and passion
it blurs the lines between country and soul. In fact, it's not hard to imagine
Solomon Burke or Al Green doing "Sometimes I Cry," Miller's powerful ode to a
lost love. But where a soul singer might take such a song to the emotional edge,
Miller's vocals are restrained, the sound of a man just barely keeping it
together in the face of searing pain.
</P>
<P>
	   Miller and his wife are just about the best thing coming out of Nashville
these days, and "Cruel Moon" is an album not to be missed. The Millers seem to
hit new heights with each release.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   "Hey You" (Lucky Dog) -- Jack Ingram
</P>
<P>
	   Jack Ingram is the real deal, a Texas singer-songwriter along the lines of
Robert Earl Keen. And while Ingram has a ways to go before he is in Keen's
league as a songwriter, he's clearly getting there.
</P>
<P>
	   Oh, and he rocks, too, as several of the barn-burners on "Hey You" clearly
show. The song that really stands out here, though, is "Biloxi," in which a man
tries to come to terms with a father who left his family for the good times and
pretty girls of Biloxi.
</P>
<P>
	   When Ingram can write everything at that level, he will have arrived as a
major force. In the meantime, he's good listening for those tired of the
watered-down mush that generally masquerades as country music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'The War Zone'  </HEADLINE>
    By CHRISTY LEMIRE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   "The War Zone" will make little money at the box office.
</P>
<P>
	   It's about incest -- not exactly a topic that blockbusters are made of. And
the film's long, silent moments and languid pace will frustrate many.
</P>
<P>
	   But this dark, startling film is admirable for its gutsiness in tackling
such taboo terrain and for a strong performance from its young star.
</P>
<P>
	   "The War Zone" is about the drastic changes that occur when a family moves
from London to the quiet of the Devon countryside.
</P>
<P>
	   Gawky, 15-year-old Tom (Freddie Cunliffe) misses his friends in the city,
and spends time during Easter break with his worldlier 17-year-old sister,
Jessie (Lara Belmont). Their mother (Tilda Swinton) is extremely pregnant with
her third child and their father (Ray Winstone) is always on the phone, talking
business.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite their close living quarters, these people rarely speak to each
other. They sit silently in the same room, sipping tea, or spy each other in
dark hallways. A tension boils beneath the surface for the film's first
half-hour, then explodes when Tom learns an ugly secret.
</P>
<P>
	   One night, he returns home and sees his father and Jessie through a window
in what appears to be an inappropriate position. And the more time Tom spends
with Jessie, the more suspicious he becomes.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a sick world," Tom comments to his mother early on, not realizing how
right he is. The rest of the movie follows his quest to expose the truth, and
the denial he encounters from everyone around him.
</P>
<P>
	   Actor Tim Roth ("Reservoir Dogs," "Pulp Fiction") directs, and his work
behind the camera is often haunting. From the breathtaking opening shot of waves
crashing mercilessly against a rocky seashore under a cloudy sky, it's clear
this is a film of strong images.
</P>
<P>
	   But Roth tends to be heavy-handed in conveying his themes of abuse and
loneliness.
</P>
<P>
	   In their tiny house on the coast with no neighbors for miles, the family is
isolated. But even when they go out in public, they are completely alone. Dad,
Jessie and Tom eat at a London restaurant where they're the only patrons. The
family visits a pub for some pints and there isn't even a bartender.
</P>
<P>
	   And does it constantly have to be raining or windy? Must the sky always
appear so dark and dreary that it could open up any minute and swallow the
family whole? Incest obviously is a bleak subject, but Roth need not bang us
over the head with symbolism.
</P>
<P>
	   Belmont's raw performance, however, serves as the movie's heart. At times
she is all sultry attitude and smoldering eyes. At other times, she is confused,
trembling and helplessly alone with her secret. Even more amazing is that this
is the young actress' first role; the filmmakers discovered her as she walked
down a London street.
</P>
<P>
	   Cunliffe, also a newcomer, simply plays varying shades of sullen. We only
see Swinton as a mother caring for her newborn. We don't learn much about
Winstone's character, either, aside from the despicable things he does to his
daughter. More detailed character development would have made us care more about
these people.
</P>
<P>
	   But that's an easy answer. Despite a climactic -- and surprising -- ending,
there are no easy answers for this damaged family.
</P>
<P>
	   "The War Zone," a Lot 47 Films release, is not rated but contains nudity,
language, some violence and a scene of incest. Alexander Stuart adapted the
screenplay from his novel of the same name. Running time: 99 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1221 </TRAILER>
