<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Program May Add Income Aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will seek significant changes
in federal farm programs to provide additional income assistance to producers,
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said today.
</P>
<P>
	   Glickman declined to discuss the proposals, which will be part of the
president's proposed 2001 budget. Last Friday, the administration announced that
the budget would include an extra $1.3 billion for farm conservation programs,
partly to help farmers cope with depressed commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have an obligation to bring some significant proposals to the table and
we will,'' Glickman said at a news conference. He acknowledged the difficulty of
getting broad support among agricultural interests for major changes in farm
policy.
</P>
<P>
	   Glickman says the 1996 Freedom to Farm law, which scaled back on government
crop subsidies, left farmers without sufficient support for periods when crop
prices are low.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress has provided $15 billion in emergency aid over the past two years
to reimburse farmers for weather-related crop failures and to compensate for a
collapse in grain prices that occurred in 1998. Farm income is expected to drop
$7.6 billion this year unless lawmakers approve another bailout.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to help our farmers over the long-term, not just year to year. In
2000, I will work with Congress to seek significant changes to the 1996 farm
bill, strengthening the safety net and increasing conservation initiatives,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
