<HEADLINE> Dow Up 83.38; Nasdaq Up 113.19  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply higher today as investors reacted
enthusiastically to the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner. Technology stocks led the gains.
</P>
<P>
	   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
83.38 at 11,605.94, extending a Friday rally that put the blue-chip index at an
all-time closing high of 11,522.56.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader market indicators also rose today. The Nasdaq composite index was up
113.19 at 3,995.81, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 14.18 at
1,455.65.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared 30 11/16 to 95 7/16 and AOL rose 3 1/16 to 76 1/2 after
the early morning announcement of their deal, which would be the largest
corporate merger ever.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's bold move to acquire Time Warner, an old-line traditional media
powerhouse, gave investors added evidence that the Internet will be one of the
most dominant features in the economy of the future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This deal took great vision and courage," said Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. "It shows that the high valuations that many
analysts have been uncomfortable with may be justified."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service providers as investors
looked ahead to further combinations with media companies. Yahoo! rose 24 1/8 to
439 1/8 and Lycos rose 4 1/4 to 76 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Media companies also rose following news of the AOL deal. Disney rose 3
11/16 to 34 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology companies provided the strongest boost to the Dow today.
Hewlett-Packard was up 6 15/16 at 110 13/16, and IBM rose 4 3/8 to 117 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   But the industrial companies that led the Dow higher last week while
technology stocks languished in a midweek slump continued to provide good news.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa rose 11/16 to 85 5/16 after reporting it earned 89 cents per share in
the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per share.
Alcoa's board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its stock
2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 548.12 million shares, behind Friday's busy
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 9.98 to 498.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
