<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Eyes Case-Assignment Probe  </HEADLINE>
   By PETE YOST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican congressman today demanded an inquiry into
why a judge assigned the cases of four Democratic fund-raisers and presidential
friend Webster Hubbell to judicial appointees of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Howard Coble revealed that in one case, Clinton confidant Vernon Jordan
asked the sentencing judge to be lenient with the defendant, a prominent
businessman whose punishment consisted of community service work for his crimes.
</P>
<P>
	   Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson of Washington ``bypassed
the random case-assignment process in four campaign finance cases potentially
embarrassing to the president, the DNC, and Democrats generally and one case
involving President Clinton's close personal friend Webster Hubbell,'' Coble
wrote to the federal court of appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   Coble of North Carolina, who is chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee
on courts, said Johnson may have breached the code of conduct for federal judges
by assigning the cases.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Did Chief Judge Johnson abuse her discretion ... and should she have
allowed the normal random case-assignment process to occur?'' asked Coble.
</P>
<P>
	   The Associated Press disclosed last August that Johnson sent the Hubbell
case and the prosecutions of Clinton friend Charlie Trie and fund-raiser Pauline
Kanchanalak to Clinton appointees.
</P>
<P>
	   Coble revealed that Johnson also sent the fund-raising prosecutions of
Howard Glicken and Mark Jimenez to Clinton-appointed judges. Jimenez, of Miami,
fled the country last year after being accused of making illegal contributions
to Clinton, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., and other Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson's administrative aide, Joe Alexander, had no immediate comment
today. The judge has said she assigned the Hubbell, Trie and Kanchanalak cases
herself, instead of using computerized random assignment, to assure that the
high-profile cases were handled expeditiously.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The revelation that Chief Judge Johnson bypassed ... the random
case-assignment system ... may, without an adequate public explanation, erode
public confidence in the court's ability to discharge its obligations
impartially,'' Coble wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Jordan and former Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, wrote
letters seeking leniency for Glicken, who is a friend of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson assigned the Trie and Kanchanalak cases to U.S. District Judge Paul
Friedman and sent the Hubbell case to Judge James Robertson. Johnson assigned
the Glicken case to U.S. District Judge Henry Kennedy and the Jimenez case to
Judge Emmet Sullivan. The Jimenez case subsequently was reassigned to Friedman.
</P>
<P>
	   There are eight Democrats, all appointed by Clinton, and four Republicans on
the district court in the District of Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1317 </TRAILER>
