<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court To Hear Rape Lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL TOLME Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- In a case that could redefine the legal boundary
between federal and state government, the U.S. Supreme Court will hear arguments
Tuesday on whether a former Virginia Tech student can sue two men who allegedly
raped her.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices will decide whether Congress overstepped its authority in 1994
when it passed the Violence Against Women Act, the federal law under which
Christy Brzonkala sued for damages.
</P>
<P>
	   In March, the U.S. 4th Circuit Court of Appeals threw out Ms. Brzonkala's
lawsuit, saying Congress' power to regulate interstate commerce and ensure equal
protection did not authorize it to enact such a law.
</P>
<P>
	   Calling the 1994 law a ``sweeping intrusion'' into matters traditionally
handled by the states, the appeals court said violence against women has only an
``indirect relationship with interstate commerce.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Brzonkala's lawyers claim the law is needed because state justice
systems do not adequately protect women from rape, sexual assault and domestic
violence. Such victimization costs the U.S. economy billions of dollars every
year, they say.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're concerned that the justices understand the devastating economic
impact that violence against women has on the economy,'' said Martha Davis,
legal director of the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Battered women are frequently stalked at work, with the goal of having them
lose their jobs, she said. In addition, half of the women on welfare are victims
of violence and half of all rape victims have their ability to work impaired,
she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The law is backed by the Clinton administration and most state attorneys
general. It was co-sponsored by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, a Republican
presidential hopeful and chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   Opponents counter that, regardless of the law's sympathetic intent of
helping women, the federal government should not have unlimited power to
regulate state matters such as crime.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The states have been defending Americans' right to be free of violence
before there was a federal government,'' said Curt Levey, spokesman for the
Center for Individual Rights in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Congress enacted the law because it was politically correct, he said.
``Congress figured, `We have nothing to lose. We will win some votes and nobody
will object,''' Levey said.
</P>
<P>
	   Defending the law under the interstate commerce clause, which says the
federal government can regulate national economic interests, is stretching the
Constitution to the breaking point, he argued.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You could say Congress could regulate sleep because that affects
commerce,'' Levey said.
</P>
<P>
	   In striking down the law, the appeals court relied heavily on a 1995 Supreme
Court decision that struck down as unconstitutional the federal Gun-Free School
Zones Act, which made it a federal crime to possess a gun within 1,000 feet of
any school.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Brzonkala said she was attacked in a dormitory. She did not report the
alleged incident for several months and no criminal charges were filed against
Antonio Morrison and James Crawford, both players on the school's football team.
She contended that Virginia Tech protected them because they were athletes.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Brzonkala, who has consented to releasing her name to the public,
declined a request for an interview from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   The only personal information her lawyers would reveal is that she lives in
Washington, is in her early 20s, never returned to Virginia Tech following her
freshman year and attended another college for a brief time.
</P>
<P>
	   Her lone public appearance was Friday, when she spoke at a news conference
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Rape is like having your soul torn out,'' she said. ``This violence
happens to too many women, and we need laws on the books to fight it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1405 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
