<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 133.04; Dow Up 27.30  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks rose sharply today as investors reacted
enthusiastically to the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner. Blue-chips gave up some of their early momentum and were modestly
higher.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
27.30 at 11,549.86, struggling to extend a Friday rally that put the blue-chip
index at an all-time closing high of 11,522.56. In earlier trading, the Dow had
risen as much as 115.10 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was up 133.04 at 4,015.66, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 11.72 at 1,453.19.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared 28 to 92 3/4 and AOL slipped  5/8 to 72 13/16 after the
early morning announcement of their deal, which would be the largest corporate
merger ever.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's bold move to acquire Time Warner, an old-line traditional media
powerhouse, gave investors added evidence that the Internet will be one of the
most dominant features in the economy of the future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This deal took great vision and courage," said Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. "It shows that the high valuations that many
analysts have been uncomfortable with may be justified."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service providers as investors
looked ahead to further combinations with media companies. Yahoo! rose 30 5/8 to
437 7/8 and Lycos rose 4 1/4 to 76 1/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Media companies also rose following news of the AOL deal. Disney rose 3 7/8
to 35, and Times Mirror rose 3 to 66 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts suggested the combination of AOL and Time Warner stimulated
interest in cable and wireless companies as well as Internet and media
companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology companies provided the strongest boost to the Dow today.
Hewlett-Packard was up 7 1/2 at 111 3/8, and IBM rose 3 1/16 to 116 9/16.
</P>
<P>
	   But the industrial companies that led the Dow higher last week while
technology stocks languished in a midweek slump continued to provide good news.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa rose 11/16 to 85 5/16 after reporting it earned 89 cents per share in
the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per share.
Alcoa's board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its stock
2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Corporate earnings for the recently ended fourth quarter are widely expected
to show strong growth, setting a stage for further gains by U.S. stocks. Later
this week, high-profile technology companies including Yahoo! and Intel will
release their fourth-quarter figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 715.58 million shares, behind Friday's busy
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 11.80 to 500.11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
