<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intimate Murders Prompt Concern  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID CRARY AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A mother doused with gasoline and set afire. The pregnant
girlfriend of a pro football player. A woman desperate to get her ex-husband
arrested.
</P>
<P>
	   Police say each was a recent victim of the grimmest oxymoron in the criminal
justice lexicon: intimate murder.
</P>
<P>
	   On average, nearly four American women are killed each day by a husband,
ex-husband or boyfriend. The nation has made impressive strides in confronting
domestic violence, but high-profile cases of the past month have hammered home
the fact that difficult, costly challenges remain.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When you see these headlines, it's very frustrating,'' said Bonnie
Campbell, director of the Justice Department's Violence Against Women Office.
``We have a ways to go in terms of changing attitudes. I expect that will take
decades, but we're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
	   According to the latest figures from the Bureau of Justice Statistics, the
number of women killed in intimate murders dropped from 1,600 in 1976 to 1,326
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, improvements are needed in many areas, activists say: more space in
battered women's shelters, more domestic-violence awareness programs for judges,
more money to hire more staff for casework, more communication among different
agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we want them to do all those additional things, we need to give them
the money to hire the personnel,'' said Michaele Cohen, executive director of
the Maryland Network Against Domestic Violence. ``They have real concerns about
being able to do the job right.''
</P>
<P>
	   Maryland was the scene of one of the most wrenching recent killings,
involving a woman who knew she was in danger and took repeated legal steps to
protect herself. Janice Lancaster's ex-husband killed her with a shotgun last
week, then killed himself, as a judge's order for his arrest on harassment
charges lay unprocessed in a clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere:
</P>
<P>
	   -- In Texas, prosecutors charged a businessman last week with arranging the
1997 murder in Florida of his ex-wife. Her quadruplet toddlers from a later
marriage were found crawling around in her blood.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In North Carolina, pro football player Rae Carruth faces charges of
masterminding the fatal drive-by shooting of his pregnant girlfriend. The child
survived.
</P>
<P>
	   -- In California, a mother who obtained a restraining order against her
estranged husband died last week after he set her on fire.
</P>
<P>
	   Murders like those in Maryland and California -- where the victims sought
protection -- are especially dismaying to anti-violence activists.
</P>
<P>
	   Rita Smith, executive director of Denver-based Coalition Against Domestic
Violence, said better early-warning systems are needed, even in the cases where
a woman did not complain to police.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's rare that someone just out of the blue decides to kill his wife,''
Smith said. ``The signs of escalation, and stalking behavior that these guys
give off are not being paid attention to the way they need to.''
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past five years, nearly $1.4 billion has been allocated to state
and local programs under the 1994 federal Violence Against Women Act. Congress
is expected to renew and strengthen the act this year, increasing shelter space
and toughening penalties for interstate stalking.
</P>
<P>
	   The act comes under scrutiny Tuesday as the U.S. Supreme Court hears
arguments on whether a former Virginia Tech student can sue two men who
allegedly raped her. In March, a federal appeals court threw out Christy
Brzonkala's lawsuit, saying Congress overstepped its powers when it allowed rape
victims to sue for financial damages.
</P>
<P>
	   Recent federal and state initiatives have made it easier for women to escape
abusive relationships, so much so that many more shelters are needed to
accommodate the demand. One result has been a dramatic decrease in the number of
men killed by abused women who felt there was no other way out.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the Bureau of Justice Statistics, the number of men killed by
female partners fell from 1,357 to 516 between 1976 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Overwhelmingly, the men are killed by women in self-defense,'' said Kim
Gandy, a vice president of the National Organization for Women. ``But the women
are in greatest danger after they leave. The men are pursuing, not defending.''
</P>
<P>
	   When embittered men do pursue, a woman's best option might be to seek a
protection order from the courts. But Campbell said this can be a fateful
decision.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The act of leaving, that act of independence, may be a trigger for more
violence and sometimes homicide,'' she said. ``And leaving isn't just that one
day. It's a process that can go on for many months. It's a hard thing for the
justice system to monitor, but we have to find ways to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
