<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 10, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   AOL To Buy Time Warner for $166B
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner, the world's largest media and
entertainment company, is being acquired by America Online for
about $166 billion in stock in what would be the biggest corporate
merger ever. The deal announced today raises the stakes in the
consolidation scramble in the media industry and comes just four
months after another blockbuster media merger, the proposed
combination of CBS Corp. and Viacom Inc. Time Warner and AOL said
they expect their deal to be finalized by the end of the year. It's
subject to certain conditions, including regulatory approvals and
the approval of AOL and Time Warner shareholders.The Justice
Department said today it was unclear whether it or the Federal
Trade Commission will be asked to approve the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasdaq Up 160.36; Dow Up 64.53
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks rose sharply today as
investors reacted enthusiastically to the $166 billion planned
merger of America Online and Time Warner. Blue-chips gave up some
of their early momentum and were modestly higher. Just before 3
p.m. EST, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 64.53 at
11,587.09, seeking to extend a Friday rally that put the blue-chip
index at an all-time closing high of 11,522.56. In earlier trading,
the Dow had risen as much as 115.10 points. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 160.36 at 4,042.98. Time Warner soared 28 to 92 3/4 and
AOL slipped  5/8 to 72 13/16 after the early morning announcement of
their deal, which would be the largest corporate merger ever.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
Dow Industrials:        11587.09  + 64.53
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1695  Declines 1393  Unchgd  437
