</P>
<P>
	   IBM Gives a Nod to Linux
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM today announced that all of its powerful
network computers will be able to run on the Linux operating
system, embracing the fast-growing rival to other Unix formats and
Microsoft's Windows as the best platform for Internet commerce. The
leading manufacturer of computer servers said all four of its
product lines will now be compatible with Linux, a Unix-based
operating system that has grown hugely popular among independent
software developers since its Finnish creator started giving it
away for free. Coming from IBM, the announcement essentially
finalizes the mainstreaming of Linux.
</P>
<P>
	   GM To Buy Remainder of Saab
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. continued its international
shopping spree Monday, picking up the 50 percent of Swedish luxury
automaker Saab Automobile AB that it does not already own. The
deal, terms of which were not disclosed, was the latest GM has made
with foreign automakers as it shores up positions in overseas
markets. Last year, GM bought 20 percent of Subaru, agreed to buy
engines from Honda Motor Co. and began negotiations to buy
struggling Korean automaker Daewoo. GM bought a 50 percent stake
and management control of Saab in December 1989 for $600 million
and a $100 million investment in Saab's operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford Plans Line of Electric Vehicles
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. said it would begin producing a
line of electric vehicles and bikes under a new brand name -- Th!nk
-- that will become the company's home for vehicles powered by
alternatives to internal combustion engines. Th!nk -- the name of a
Norwegian electric car that Ford bought a year ago -- will sell its
models over the Internet and deliver them to customers, in addition
to selling through Ford dealers. Its lineup includes a small
plastic-bodied hatchback that can travel 55 miles fully charged, a
golf cart-like open vehicle for use in closed communities and two
models of electric bicycles. The hatchback is only sold in Norway
now; a redesigned version will go on sale in the United States
within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
	   Cos. Settle With FTC on Coupons
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three companies agreed today to modify coupon
and cash rebate programs that federal regulators called ``false and
misleading.'' Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc., Memtek Products Inc. and
UMAX Technologies reached agreements with the Federal Trade
Commission to compensate some consumers and speed rebates to
others. The public has until Feb. 9 to comment before the FTC
decides whether to make the agreements final. None of the companies
admitted any violations of law.
</P>
<P>
	   Virgin Net Has Hacker Scare
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Thousands of Virgin Net e-mail users were given
new passwords after the company uncovered a potential security
breach. More than 170,000 Virgin Net customers had their service
temporarily withdrawn after technicians discovered a hacker
attempting to tap into the British-based system, the company said.
A notice was posted on Virgin's Web site this weekend warning users
of the potential breach, and individual letters were mailed to all
those affected, the company said. Only about 25 percent of Virgin's
customer base was potentially involved, company said today. Virgin
Net, which provides e-mail services for 800,000 British customers,
said the accounts potentially affected all belonged to a certain
``type,'' but would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Seeks Long-Distance OK
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications asked federal regulators
today for approval to become the second Baby Bell to offer
long-distance service to its local customers. Hot on the heels of a
decision by the Federal Communications Commission to let Bell
Atlantic provide long-distance in New York, SBC filed an
application with the FCC seeking to do the same in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa Earnings Up 53 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa's fourth-quarter earnings rose 53
percent, beating Wall Street expectations, as the No. 1 aluminum
maker cut back on its inventory and also paid less tax on its
operations in Australia. Alcoa also announced today it was raising
its dividend and splitting its stock. The company reported earnings
of $333.9 million, or 89 cents per share, compared with $218.3
million, or 59 cents per share, in 1998's fourth quarter. Analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson financial had predicted earnings of
76 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
	   New Cases of Mad Cow Disease Found
</P>
<P>
	   PARIS (AP) -- French officials have discovered two new cases of
mad cow disease, the Agriculture Ministry said today. The cases,
detected late last year, bring to 31 the number of cows discovered
with the disease in France in 1999. One of the diseased cows was in
the northwest region of Brittany, while the other was found in the
central region of Creuse. Their herds, a total of 341 cows, were
slaughtered late last week. New cases of the disease are expected
to appear until 2001, five years after stringent prevention
measures were taken to prevent outbreaks, the Agriculture Ministry
has said. The disease has an average incubation period of five
years.
</P>
<P>
	   LA Times Promotes Two Editors
</P>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times has promoted newsroom
veteran Leo Wolinsky to executive editor and created a new position
to oversee the relationship between the editorial and business
departments. Wolinsky, one of four managing editors, was promoted
to the new position. Ardith Hilliard, editor of the paper's San
Fernando Valley edition, was named associate editor with
responsibility for implementing new ethical guidelines. Both will
report to Editor Michael Parks. The new guidelines were adopted by
the paper in response to a much-criticized revenue-sharing deal
with the city's Staples Center arena.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador Pegs Peso to Dollar
</P>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's president has sought to
stabilize the nation's plummeting currency by pegging it to the
U.S. dollar, despite opposition from the central bank. Amid calls
for his resignation and a worsening economic crisis, President
Jamil Mahuad also announced late yesterday in a 20-minute televised
address to the nation that his 15-member Cabinet had tendered its
resignation. He said he would name replacements in the coming days.
A deal was hammered out with Congress to pave the way for approval
of several economic reforms, he said, including ``the modernization
of the state'' -- a term interpreted by many to mean the
privatization of state industries.
</P>
<P>
	   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Gains in telecommunications and telecom stocks
drove European stock indexes higher today, boosted by merger plans
between America Online Inc. and media company Time Warner Inc.
Investors were spurred on by the prospect of similar mergers
between leading media and Internet players. The Dow Jones Stoxx
Index of 606 European companies closed up 5.64 points at 365.39,
while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended up 6.05 points at
401.40. The media sector of the Dow Jones Stoxx Index overshadowed
the rest of the market with a massive 9.4 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday: Jobless claims
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday: Retail sales
</P>
<P>
	   Friday: Consumer prices
</P>
<P>
	   Friday: Business inventories
</P>
<P>
	   Friday: Industrial production
</P>
