<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transportation Funds To Be Proposed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will propose $300 million more for
transportation research, such as projects to extend the life span of bridges,
discourage drunken driving and fight fatigue behind the wheel, Transportation
Secretary Rodney Slater said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The fiscal 2001 budget Clinton will present to Congress next month would
raise the Transportation Department's funds for research and development and
technology from $900 million to $1.2 billion -- a 35 percent increase, Slater
said. He spoke at the annual conference of the Transportation Research Board of
the National Research Council, part of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
	   The increase would provide additional funds for the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration to develop a whole family of crash dummies -- adding a
female and three children to the male dummies used for years, said NHTSA's
acting director Rosalyn Millman.
</P>
<P>
	   The money also would help complete work this year on a driving simulator at
the University of Iowa. ``The simulator uses a real person,'' she said. ``For
example, we're looking at ways to counter fatigue. Some companies have proposed
releasing different kinds of smells to wake drivers up.''
</P>
<P>
	   The extra research money also would be used to try to find ways to put
polymer coatings on bridge spans to make them last 10 or 12 years longer, said
Peter Basso, assistant secretary for budget and programs.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, the research money would be spent on so-called ``intelligent
transportation systems,'' such as using cameras and sensors to monitor traffic
and congestion or developing car phone systems that would automatically summon
emergency vehicles in case of an accident by pinpointing the location with
satellites, Basso said.
</P>
<P>
	   The increased research money will be included in the overall Transportation
Department budget proposal Clinton is to announce on Feb. 7, Basso said. The
department's current budget is about $50 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
