<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 2 Pentagon Official Resigns  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Hamre, the deputy secretary of defense who oversaw
the Pentagon's largely successful inoculations against the Y2K computer bug, is
resigning to become head of a major think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing the surprise move Monday, Defense Secretary William Cohen said
he had recommended that President Clinton nominate Rudy de Leon to replace
Hamre. De Leon has been the Pentagon's under secretary for personnel and
readiness for the past two years and previously was under secretary of the Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre, 49, came to the Pentagon in 1993 to be comptroller during Les Aspin's
tenure as defense secretary. He held that post until Cohen made him his top
deputy in July 1997, a position Hamre used to push for modernizing the
Pentagon's business practices and improving the security of its computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John Hamre has been my friend and partner in running the department,''
Cohen said in a written statement. ``He approaches all issues with extreme
confidence and an extraordinary sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen credited de Leon with tackling many of the Pentagon's toughest
problems, including most recently a growing controversy over the way the
services implement the administration's policy on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   De Leon also has been overseeing an Army investigation of allegations that
American troops killed hundreds of South Korean civilians during the opening
weeks of the Korean War in 1950. He also has been at the center of efforts --
unsuccessful so far -- to regain Navy use of the Vieques training range in
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
	   De Leon was undersecretary of the Air Force from 1994-97. He was staff
director for the House Armed Services Committee for four years before Aspin
brought him to the Pentagon to be a special assistant in 1993.
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre will leave March 31 and become president and chief executive officer
of the Center for Strategic and International Studies, or CSIS. In joining that
think tank he will be reconnecting with Sam Nunn, the former Democratic senator
from Georgia who was chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee while Hamre
was a committee staff member. Nunn is chairman of CSIS's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre took the lead role in preparing the Defense Department's far-flung
computer networks for the Y2K rollover. At a cost of $3.6 billion, the effort
was successful except for a temporary breakdown New Year's Eve of a ground
station computer that processes information from a constellation of intelligence
satellites.
</P>
<P>
	   In his new job at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, Hamre
will head one of the nation's most prominent public policy research
institutions. It was founded in 1962 by David M. Abshire and the late Adm.
Arleigh Burke.
</P>
<P>
	   The center's current president is Richard Fairbanks, former
ambassador-at-large in the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
	   rb
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1515 </TRAILER>
