<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 80.66; Nasdaq Up 162.48  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today as investors reacted
enthusiastically to the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner. Technology shares led the market.
</P>
<P>
	   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 80.66 at 11,603.22, extending a Friday rally that put
the blue-chip index at an all-time closing high of 11,522.56. In earlier
trading, the Dow had risen as much as 115.10 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was up 162.48 at 4,045.10. The
technology-dominated index is up more than 300 points in the past two sessions,
wiping out most remnants of a three-day slump that knocked 400 points off the
Nasdaq last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 18.48 at 1,459.95.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology and media companies led a broad advance as investors speculated
that the combination of America Online and Time Warner will spur many more
mergers between new-line and old-line information providers.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared 28 1/4 to 93 and AOL slipped  1/4 to 73 3/16 after the
announcement of their deal, which would be the largest corporate merger ever.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's bold move to acquire Time Warner, an old-line traditional media
powerhouse, gave investors added evidence that the Internet will be one of the
most dominant features in the economy of the future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This deal took great vision and courage," said Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. "It shows that the high valuations that many
analysts have been uncomfortable with may be justified."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal helped lift shares of other Internet service providers like Yahoo!,
up 31 1/2 to 446 1/2, and Lycos, which rose 8 1/8 to 80.
</P>
<P>
	   Media companies also rose as analysts forecast a wave of new partnerships.
Disney rose 4 1/4 to 35 3/8, and News Corp. rose 6 1/8 to 43 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts suggested the combination of AOL and Time Warner stimulated
interest in cable and wireless companies as well as Internet and media
companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology companies also provided the strongest boost to the Dow today.
Hewlett-Packard was up 7 7/16 at 111 5/16, and IBM rose 4 7/16 to 117 15/16.
</P>
<P>
	   The industrial companies that led the Dow higher last week while technology
stocks languished in a slump continued to provide good news, but had a tough
time attracting as much attention as technology and media stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa rose just 1/16 to 84 11/16 after reporting it earned 89 cents per
share in the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per
share. Alcoa's board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its
stock 2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Corporate earnings for the recently ended fourth quarter are widely expected
to show strong growth, setting a stage for further gains by U.S. stocks. Later
this week, high-profile technology companies including Yahoo! and Intel will
release their fourth-quarter figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 830.73 million shares, behind Friday's busy
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 12.99 to 501.30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
