<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco industry victory in smoking-relating illnesses case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The tobacco industry won a significant legal victory
Monday when the Supreme Court refused to let union health funds sue cigarette
makers to recover the cost of treating smoking-related illnesses.
<P>
	   The justices rejected appeals in which union health funds from Pennsylvania,
Oregon and New York argued they should be allowed to sue tobacco companies under
federal racketeering and antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're gratified," said Herbert Wachtel, a lawyer for Phillip Morris Inc.
"Four courts of appeals have held unanimously that these third-party cases are
without merit. Hopefully, this will put an end to them."
</P>
<P>
	   Although Monday's action set no national precedent, the three unsuccessful
appeals had been viewed as health funds' best chance to reverse rulings that
have thwarted their lawsuits against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
	   John Banzhaf of Action on Smoking and Health lamented the court's action.
"The tobacco industry gets to keep its ill-gotten gain and the public health
loses," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Banzhaf said the court's denial of review "sounds the death knell for these
types of lawsuits by health funds and possibly by other third parties as well."
</P>
<P>
	   Federal appeals courts also have disallowed smoking-related lawsuits by Blue
Cross, foreign countries and smokers' employers.
</P>
<P>
	   The health funds' lawsuits accused the tobacco industry of defrauding them
into paying to treat illnesses caused by health-plan participants' smoking.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuits contended cigarette makers and related industry organizations
withheld accurate information about smoking's health effects that might have led
the funds to more aggressively discourage their members from smoking.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuits were patterned after similar state claims that led to
settlements in which the tobacco industry will pay the states $246 billion for
health care costs. The Justice Department also sued the industry; its pending
lawsuit was not directly affected by Monday's action.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal appeals courts ruled unanimously that the union health funds could
not sue because they were seeking payment for damages suffered by their members,
who could sue on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   In dismissing the lawsuit by seven Pennsylvania union health funds, the 3rd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said the states could sue because they were
authorized to do so under state law, or because of the "political power of
governmental bodies" - authority and power union health funds do not have.
</P>
<P>
	   In their Supreme Court appeals, the health funds' operators argued their
members cannot sue under the federal laws they tried to invoke - laws that
provide for tripled damages.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a clear national interest in holding tobacco companies accountable
for the public health devastation they have wreaked," one of the appeals said.
</P>
<P>
	   Banzhaf said tobacco companies are being given future immunity from such
lawsuits. "Even if the tobacco industry's conduct costs health plans billions of
dollars in the future, they're not going to be able to collect a dime," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He suggested that all such funds protect themselves by charging higher
premiums for smokers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1525 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Plans Th!nk Electric Vehicles  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co., the company that put the world on wheels
powered by gasoline, will soon sell a plastic-bodied hatchback, a golf cart and
bicycles -- all powered by electricity.
</P>
<P>
	   The line of electric vehicles, under the brand name Th!nk, will become the
company's home for vehicles powered by something other than internal combustion
engines. It will not only build vehicles, but act as a research center for Ford.
</P>
<P>
	   "The idea of Th!nk is to work on vehicles and technology that's a little
more out there," said Ford president and CEO Jac Nasser on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're using the Th!nk as a way of incubating and hatching new technologies
such as fuel cells. The technology will then migrate to other vehicles."
</P>
<P>
	   Th!nk, the name of a Norwegian electric car that Ford bought a year ago,
will sell its models over the Internet as well as through Ford dealers.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford showed off the Th!nk line Monday during previews for the North American
International Auto Show. The show opens to the public on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Th!nk City is a small plastic-bodied hatchback that can travel 55 miles
fully charged, though it's currently only available in Norway. Ford will
introduce a redesigned version in about two years and could not offer an
estimated cost.
</P>
<P>
	   The Th!nk Neighbor is a golf cart-like open vehicle for use in closed
communities, with speed limited to 25 mph and an estimated price tag of about
$6,000. The two bikes have ranges of up to 30 miles, and will cost between
$1,000 and $1,200.
</P>
<P>
	   While several automakers have built electric vehicles, none has had much
success at selling them, due to their high costs, limited range and long
recharge times. GM sold only 137 of its futuristic EV1 coupes last year, while
Ford sells electric versions of its Ranger pickups, but mostly to governments
and business fleets.
</P>
<P>
	   But Nasser said even though Th!nk might not be a major source of revenue for
Ford, it still made good business sense.
</P>
<P>
	   Th!nk "is clearly meant to push the envelope of new technologies that are a
stretch in terms of technological and business aspects," Nasser said. "But we
really believe that consumers want alternative products. I think all of these
have a place."
</P>
<P>
	   Ford also said Monday it was committing to selling a hybrid gas-electric
sedan by 2003. The unnamed vehicle would use an internal combustion engine mated
to an electric motor, and will be based on Ford's work with a federal government
program aimed at producing a car that gets 80 miles on a gallon of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
	   The company declined to say whether the hybrid's engine would use gasoline
or diesel fuel. Auto industry researchers have focused on diesel engines for
such vehicles, but environmental groups have said diesel engines create too much
pollution.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford said the hybrid power would add about $3,000 to the car's sticker
price, and suggested that the government create a tax credit for such vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1529 </TRAILER>
