<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaye calls for private collection agencies to go after fines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Private collection agencies will be called in to try
to get people to pay court-imposed fines and surcharges, New York's court
administrators said Monday.
<P>
	   "We're going to go ahead and try it and try to collect every penny we can,"
Chief Judge Judith Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye also called in her annual State of the Judiciary address for the
bolstering of drug and community courts so they can handle many more misdemeanor
cases, the establishment of an inspector general to investigate whether the
appointments of fiduciaries and other lawyers are politically motivated and for
the state to continue jury reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye said officials hope private collectors will be more adept at getting
people to pay up than have court officials.
</P>
<P>
	   "Experience has shown that governmental institutions are not equipped to
function as collection agencies and are therefore not particularly successful at
this task," Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Office of Court Administration said private agencies would be used
at first to collect fines and surcharges imposed in six court jurisdictions:
Suffolk County Court, Suffolk District Court, Nassau District Court, Queens
state Supreme Court, New York City Criminal Court and Rochester City Court.
</P>
<P>
	   Jonathan Lippmann, chief state administrative judge, said those courts were
picked because of the large amounts of outstanding payments due. Kaye said that
if the private agencies are successful in those six areas, she wants the
practice to be expanded statewide.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye proposed using the money the collection agencies raise to help pay for
an increase in the fees paid to court-appointed lawyers who defend indigent New
Yorkers. Those fees are currently $40 an hour for in-court work and $25 an hour
for out-of-court time.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye called those fee levels "absolutely ludicrous" and "totally
unrealistic" and said too many inexperienced lawyers are handling too many such
cases because they aren't worth the time of veteran lawyers. The entire legal
system suffers because of it, Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
	   She proposed increasing the assigned counsel fees to $75 an hour for felony
and Family Court cases and to $60 an hour for non-felony cases.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye acknowledged that low-level nonviolent misdemeanor offenders are a
problem to the police, the communities the offenders live in and to the courts.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Gov. George Pataki proposed prosecuting as a felony a fourth
misdemeanor charge against a person with three prior misdemeanor convictions. He
said some criminals had dozens of such convictions on their records for offenses
such as shoplifting, marijuana possession and disorderly conduct without ever
serving prison time.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye advocated a different approach. She said the prosecution of misdemeanor
offenders often turns into "human recycling" because the court system doesn't
have the capacity to hold actual trials. Of the 375,000 arrest cases in the New
York City Criminal Court last year, for example, only 822 or 0.2 percent, were
resolved at trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaye said the constant plea-bargaining serves neither the defendants nor the
court system.
</P>
<P>
	   She said she will ask the Legislature to create 23 new Criminal Court
judgeships in New York City and also temporarily reassign state Supreme Court
justices to hear misdemeanor cases.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, Kaye advocated changing the law so that more bench trials can
be held in misdemeanor cases and that more resources be given to drug and
community courts.
</P>
<P>
	   State Sen. James Lack, a Suffolk County Republican who chairs his chamber's
judiciary committee, said he favors putting more emphasis on drug courts and
other alternative forms of adjudicating cases to provide more room for trying
felony cases in the courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1529 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
