<HEADLINE> Corn At 2-Mo. High; Other Grains Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn futures reached a two-month high Monday on the Chicago
Board of Trade amid bullish sentiments that the long price slump may be over.
</P>
<P>
	   Other grains also were mostly higher, while soybeans finished sharply lower.
</P>
<P>
	   Grain prices slipped early in the trading session when soybeans sank,
pressured by weekend rains in South America and forecasts for more showers ahead
in key growing regions.
</P>
<P>
	   But when corn held its own, investors jumped in and bought more contracts to
send it up to its highest level since November. The modest rally sent prices
further away from the $2-a-bushel mark that held like a magnet for weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat also shook off the initial pressure from soybeans, settling up
somewhat on technically driven fund buying. Forecasts for dry weather in much of
the U.S. winter wheat belt helped push the price higher.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.53 1/2 a bushel; March corn
rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.08 1/2 a bushel; March oats were unchanged at $1.09 1/2 a
bushel; March soybeans fell 5 1/4 cents to $4.73 1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures edged lower on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork
futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle fell .10 cent to 70.77 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle fell .02 cent to 86.85 cents a pound; February lean hogs rose .03 cent to
55.65 cents a pound; February pork bellies fell 1.32 cents to 80.90 cents a
pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
