<HEADLINE> Microsoft Temps May Be Rewarded  </HEADLINE>
   By TED BRIDIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court refused Monday to free Microsoft Corp.
from having to pay as many as 10,000 temporary employees who were not allowed to
join the company's lucrative stock-purchase program.
</P>
<P>
	   The ruling, the latest against Microsoft on the issue, could have enormous
implications on the nation's high-tech industry, which has classified some
employees as temporary workers to avoid paying certain benefits and to cut
costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The decision opens the way for attorneys representing these former Microsoft
employees to begin calculating how much each might be owed based on stock they
hypothetically could have purchased at a discount.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of that stock has risen nearly 2,400 percent since the original
lawsuit was filed in 1992. An attorney for the former employees, Stephen Strong,
said the case affects more than 6,000 workers -- and possibly as many as 10,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft said it now has between 5,500 and 7,000 temporary or contingent
workers in the United States, in addition to its roughly 32,000 permanent
employees.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Microsoft was a startup company that wanted to be efficient,'' Strong
said. ``Over time it grew, but it hasn't really matured in treating its normal
employees in ways they should be treated.''
</P>
<P>
	   The justices on Monday, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that, according to Microsoft's unsuccessful appeal, ``has far-reaching
implications for the field of employment law.''
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft spokesman Dan Leach said the company was ``disappointed the high
court has decided now is not the time to review those issues. We look forward to
putting the case behind us, and we value the contributions of everyone who makes
great software for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Eight people who once worked for the Redmond, Wash., computer software
company sued in 1992, saying they and thousands more ``permatemps'' illegally
had been shut out of an employee stock purchase plan that allows employees to
buy Microsoft stock at a 15 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
	   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals twice ruled, most recently in May,
that the temporary employees wrongly had been treated as ``independent
contractors'' or employees of employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   They had been entitled under Washington state law to be considered regular
employees, the appeals court said, instructing a federal trial judge to
determine what damages each of thousands of Microsoft's former temporary
employees is owed.
</P>
<P>
	   In the appeal acted on Monday, Microsoft contended the appeals court allowed
too large a ``class'' of former temporary employees to have a stake in the case.
That class could include current temporary employees and any temp who worked at
Microsoft since 1987.
</P>
<P>
	   The appeal also argued that the 9th Circuit court wrongly concluded ``that
an individual employed by an employment agency can simultaneously claim employee
benefits from both the employment agency and the agency's client for which the
individual performs services.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although the case acted on today centered only on Microsoft's stock-purchase
plan, temporary employees also are suing the company for health insurance and
pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   The case acted on today is Microsoft Corp. vs. Vizcaino, 99-498.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1601 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SBC Wants in Texas Long-Distance  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications asked federal regulators Monday to let
it provide long-distance telephone service in Texas, hoping to round out the
package of services it offers to local customers in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   The request comes shortly after a landmark decision by the Federal
Communications Commission to permit Bell Atlantic to offer long-distance to
local customers in New York. SBC filed an application Monday with the FCC
seeking to do the same in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC wants to position itself to complete the bundle of services -- local
phone, Internet, wireless and even direct satellite broadcast television --
already available to Texas customers. Long-distance calling is a key piece in
giving consumers a one-stop-shopping option.
</P>
<P>
	   Company officials said their bid to enter Texas' long-distance business
would put pressure on other carriers in both the local and long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will be the impetus for lots of competition here,'' said Bob Ferguson,
SBC president for federal relations. The company eventually wants to offer
long-distance throughout its territory. California is likely to be among the
next states it seeks approval for.
</P>
<P>
	   While not tipping their business plans, company officials pledged that their
future long-distance customers would not be charged a minimum monthly fee.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think you can expect our company to be a very aggressive and innovative
competitor in this market,'' said Jim Shelley, president of SBC regulatory
affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   If its application is approved, SBC would become the second Baby Bell to
offer long-distance service to its local customers. Bell Atlantic won the right
to do so in New York last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts say the prospects for SBC getting approval are good, especially
since one Bell already has forged a path. They added that the company has worked
hard to show that its local Texas phone business is open to competition -- a
standard that must be met under a 1996 telecommunications law for a Bell company
to offer long-distance in its calling region.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They've got a lot of evidence and a lot of support behind this
application,'' said Mel Marten, telecommunications analyst with Edward Jones in
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC asserts its market is open, noting that about 115 of their rivals have
signed up 1.4 million customers in the state. The company also has undergone a
third-party review to ensure that it is properly processing orders from rivals
seeking to switch customers to their service, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The FCC has 90 days to decide on the application. It must give substantial
weight to an evaluation by the Justice Department. The Texas Public Utility
Commission also will have an opportunity to weigh in.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas regulators already gave their unanimous approval in December to SBC's
plan, with the commission's chairman declaring that the company had opened its
local markets to competitors. That important endorsement will help boost SBC's
proposal at the FCC.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also has agreed to $289 million in penalties if it does not
continue to give its rivals fair access to its systems.
</P>
<P>
	   But some competitors, including MCI WorldCom, which offers local service to
business customers in metropolitan Texas markets, argue that SBC has not passed
the necessary hurdles.
</P>
<P>
	   ``SBC's bid for long-distance authority in Texas is premature. Unlike the
situation in New York, substantial barriers to competition still exist in
Texas,'' the company said in a statement. It called SBC's systems inadequate for
processing orders from competitors.
</P>
<P>
	   Southwestern Bell operates SBC's Texas business. SBC phone systems cover
most of the Southwest and Midwest. Its other units include Pacific Bell, Nevada
Bell, and Southern New England Telecommunications Corp. in Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1605 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
