<HEADLINE> Turkish Pop Star Returns for Draft  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Eager fans weren't the only ones waiting for pop
star Tarkan to land at Istanbul airport Monday after more than a year abroad. So
were the police.
</P>
<P>
	   They scooped the singer off his Air France jet from Paris and handed him
over to military authorities, who wanted him for failing to report for his
obligatory service.
</P>
<P>
	   Tarkan -- whose Arabic-influenced tune ``Simarik,'' or ``Spoiled,'' was at
the top of the French charts last year-- was released from custody after
applying for a new program to reduce his time in uniform.
</P>
<P>
	   Desperate to raise relief money after a devastating August quake, the
government is offering draft-age men -- those between 26 and 40 -- a chance to
reduce their time in the service from 18 months to one month by paying $8,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Tarkan, who uses one name, failed to report to the military last November.
Turkish authorities filed a desertion case that could have cost him his
citizenship.
</P>
</TEXT>
