<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Higher With Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies on Monday,
fueled by big gains on Wall Street that boosted demand for the U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0259, down from $1.0276
late Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors cheered the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner, which would be the largest corporate merger ever. The Dow Jones
industrial average soared to a new high, and technology stocks were up sharply.
</P>
<P>
	   Big gains on Wall Street helped to offset some early weakness in the dollar
against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
	   That was a result of rising concerns that Japan won't be able to get other
Group of Seven nations to help it stem the yen's strength. The G-7 meeting is
scheduled to take place on Jan. 22 in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   When the yen rises, Japanese goods become more expensive and less attractive
in foreign markets, unless manufacturers cut prices and thereby reduce their
profits to keep market share. A strong yen also reduces the value of sales
proceeds in foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was quoted at 105.20 Japanese yen, down slightly from 105.21.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.5685 Swiss francs, up from 1.5652, and
1.4551 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4560. The British pound fell to $1.6369
from $1.6375.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Monday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9065 German marks, up from 1.9033; 6.3940
French francs, up from 6.3834; and 1,887.39 Italian lire, up from 1,884.26.
</P>
</TEXT>
