<HEADLINE> German Union Deal May Not Spur Jobs  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- An industry/union compromise on lowering the
retirement age has rescued Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's key initiative to
combat unemployment, but economists said Monday it would do little to promote
the government's goal of creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   After weeks of stalled negotiations, Schroeder brokered the compromise
Sunday to lower the retirement age to 60 from 65, a contentious point in the
talks aimed broadly at reviving the sagging German jobs market.
</P>
<P>
	   "Schroeder is the winner because it avoided a total collapse of talks, but
as far as the two other sides are concerned, we don't know yet," said Thomas
Mayer, a senior economist with Goldman Sachs. "One thing is for sure, the early
retirement schemes will not create more jobs."
</P>
<P>
	   Early retirement was proposed as one way to bring down German unemployment,
which hit 10.3 percent in December -- just slightly above the politically
sensitive 4 million person mark. But economists question the fundamentals behind
the plan.
</P>
<P>
	   "Basically, unions don't represent the economy at large or the unemployed,
and in Germany they represent mainly aging members of the work force who are
quickly approaching retirement age," said Mayer, adding that retirement at 60
would give workers a fat pension, while driving up labor costs for their
employers.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, early retirement falls short of creating more jobs because
it simply replaces older employees with younger ones, said Ralph Solveen, an
economist with Commerzbank.
</P>
<P>
	   The next round of talks will continue in late spring and should address
other issues such as pension and tax reform. But after Sunday's meeting, even
unions that had pushed for earlier retirement were lukewarm about the agreement,
which stops short of mandating early retirement, allowing companies to make up
their own rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Germany's most powerful union IG Metall had promised to peg future wage
demands to economic growth if the deal went through. The union had been
targeting a 4 percent raise, above the projected economic growth rate of 2.5
percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   But IG Metall president Klaus Zwickel said he was "not enthusiastic" about
the outcome and was seeking language for "clearly more than 4 percent" wage
increases.
</P>
<P>
	   Dieter Schulte, boss of the powerful Association of German Unions, called
the deal an important first step, but added that it was vague enough to still
leave room for higher wage demands when unions and firms sit down for upcoming
wage talks.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the president of the Association of German Industries maintained that
the agreement obliged unions to scale back their demands, and cited the
Netherlands as a model for creating jobs through reducing wage demands.
</P>
<P>
	   "Over the years there, unions have made contracts that are far under the
economic growth rate, with the result that unemployment is now under 4 percent
there," Hans-Olaf Henkel said.
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment rates in Germany are forecast to dip slightly over the next
year, but mainly because of a resurgent industrial sector and a demographic
shift of more people leaving the work force.
</P>
<P>
	   Economists say more constructive reforms are needed to anchor real job
growth, including tax breaks for lower income workers and labor market
deregulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1626 </TRAILER>
