<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Nasdaq High; Dow Ends Up 49.64  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology and media shares led the Nasdaq composite to its
biggest point gain ever and the Dow Jones industrials to a new closing high as
investors celebrated the $166 billion planned merger of America Online and Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index rose 166.97 to 4,049.59, according to preliminary
calculations. The technology-dominated index has risen more than 300 points in
the past two sessions, wiping out most remnants of a three-day slump that
knocked 400 points off the Nasdaq last week.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow rose 49.64 to 11,572.20, topping Friday's record close of 11,522.56.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader market indicators were also higher.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks posted eye-popping gains in a wide range of sectors.
Internet service providers, biotechnology companies and businesses that build
computer networks all soared in active trading on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
	   But the biggest story on Wall Street was AOL, whose bold move to acquire
Time Warner spurred a wave of speculation about additional mergers between
new-line and old-line information providers.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner soared and AOL slipped modestly after the announcement of their
deal, which would be the largest corporate merger ever.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL's quest for Time Warner, an old-line traditional media powerhouse, gave
investors added evidence that the Internet will be one of the most dominant
features in the economy of the future, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This deal took great vision and courage," said Alan Ackerman, senior vice
president at Fahnestock &AMP; Co. "It shows that the high valuations that many
analysts have been uncomfortable with may be justified."
</P>
<P>
	   Enthusiasm for the deal spread quickly to other Internet service providers
like Yahoo! and Lycos. Media companies like Disney and News Corp. also rose as
analysts forecast a wave of new partnerships.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts suggested the combination of AOL and Time Warner stimulated
interest in cable and wireless companies as well.
</P>
<P>
	   "A deal of this size indicates that we will start to see more
consolidation," said Robert Freedman, chief investment officer for the John
Hancock Funds in Boston. "There's a great deal of excitement surrounding these
industries."
</P>
<P>
	   Technology companies also provided the strongest boost to the Dow today.
Hewlett-Packard and IBM made solid advances.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past two sessions on Wall Street, technology stocks have returned to
the form that led the Nasdaq to an unprecedented 86 percent gain in 1999. Many
investors took profits from those gains last week, driving the Nasdaq 10 percent
lower over the course of three sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   Many analysts expected the Nasdaq to fall further. But investors' enthusiasm
for technology stocks, already running high, was kindled again by the AOL deal,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "These stocks had so much momentum that it's very tough to break their
cycle," said Freedman. "Shareholders appear ready and willing to buy on any
dips."
</P>
<P>
	   The industrial companies that led the Dow higher last week while technology
stocks languished continued to provide good news, but had a tough time
attracting as much attention as technology and media stocks.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa rose just slightly after reporting it earned 89 cents per share in the
fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated earnings of 76 cents per share. Alcoa's
board also voted to raise the company's dividend and split its stock 2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
	   Corporate earnings for the recently ended fourth quarter are widely expected
to show strong growth, setting a stage for further gains by U.S. stocks. Later
this week, high-profile technology companies including Yahoo! and Intel will
release their fourth-quarter figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1627 </TRAILER>
