<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europeans Share U.S. Flu Misery  </HEADLINE>
   By AUDREY WOODS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Overburdened British hospitals canceled operations to make
room for flu victims, Israeli doctors treated patients in hallways and
cafeterias on Monday, and the Dutch and Danes shared the flu misery that is
making its way across the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Parts of Europe and the Middle East have been hard hit this year by
influenza, which kills thousands of vulnerable people every year and leaves
millions more ill.
</P>
<P>
	   In Britain, Health Secretary Alan Milburn said Monday the number of flu
cases had quadrupled in the last month and if the outbreak didn't peak soon,
``we could be heading for the worst epidemic in the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
	   And that's not counting the large number of cases that go uncounted because
victims turn to pharmacists or a National Health Service help-line for advice,
rather than going to a doctor, said Liam Donaldson, the government's chief
medical officer.
</P>
<P>
	   Israeli hospitals have increased their staff and many are operating at 175
percent capacity because of the flu outbreak, the Health Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
	   At Laniado Hospital in the coastal Israeli town of Netanya, Dr. Gershon
Lieber said patients were turned away overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are clearing out all sorts of places, cafeterias and offices, so we can
admit as many patients as possible,'' Lieber said, speaking on army radio.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Netherlands, health officials said they expected the flu epidemic to
leave 20 percent of the country coughing and sniffling in the weeks ahead. The
country's eastern provinces have reported nine times the usual number of cases,
according to the National Center for Influenza.
</P>
<P>
	   Spain's Health Ministry said cases were up about 30 percent over last year,
but attributed that to the flu season starting about two weeks earlier than
usual.
</P>
<P>
	   Danish authorities said the country seemed to be in the early stage of an
epidemic, while in the Finnish capital, Helsinki, about 60 percent of people
being treated in health clinics were diagnosed with the flu.
</P>
<P>
	   A flu wave in the German states of Bavaria, Baden-Wuerttemberg and Thuringia
was reported to be slightly higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
	   Rolf Heckler, chief of the National Reference Center for Flu in Hanover,
said doctors were reporting about 30 percent of their patients with respiratory
infections have the flu virus.
</P>
<P>
	   In the United States, flu that struck the western states hard last month has
been making its way along the East Coast. By the weekend, 19 states, including
Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey and Virginia, had reported widespread or
regional flu outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
	   New York State Health Department officials were reporting a dramatic
increase in the number of flu outbreaks statewide -- 80 compared with 19 at the
same time last year.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Dr. Keiji Fukuda of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in
Atlanta said Monday that this year's flu outbreak didn't appear to be unusually
severe so far.
</P>
<P>
	   The Type A Sydney strain of the flu is the major culprit in the United
States and worldwide, Fukuda said.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the flu had been ``picking up'' in the last three weeks and ``it's
pretty clear in some local areas they really have gotten hit pretty hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1634 </TRAILER>
