<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cloning May Work for Extinct Goat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    MADRID, Spain (AP) -- A rare goat native to a mountainous region of northern
Spain has become extinct, with the last known animal found dead last week under
a fallen tree, authorities said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Fearing the worst, veterinarians working for the Aragon regional government
captured the 13-year-old female mountain goat last spring and took a tissue
sample from its ear, in case they needed to clone it. Then they attached an
electronic tracer to the animal and released it.
</P>
<P>
	   The sample cells have been preserved, but no decision has been made on
whether to try to use the genetic material to try to clone the animal, said
Carlos Ontanon, Aragon's environmental director.
</P>
<P>
	   He added, however, that cloning one goat would not be enough to get the
species started again, since a male goat would be needed for mating.
</P>
<P>
	   The animal belonged to one of several subspecies of Pyrenees mountain goat
and was known in Spanish as a "bucardo." Its scientific name is capra pyrenaica
pyrenaica.
</P>
<P>
	   It is distinguished by a thick coat suitable for frigid mountain weather
and, in the case of females, horns with a broader base than that of other goats.
</P>
<P>
	   Forest rangers in Ordesa National Park in Huesca province found the lone
female last Thursday under a tree. Its skill had been crushed.
</P>
<P>
	   Park director Luis Marquina said the species dwindled steadily over the past
century as a result of poaching and environmental factors, in some cases natural
disasters like landslides.
</P>
<P>
	   The species was declared protected in 1973.
</P>
<P>
	   Last April, Massachusetts researchers announced they had cloned three goats.
The cloned goats were born last fall on a farm in Charlton, the Tufts University
School of Veterinary Medicine and Genzyme Transgenics Corp. of Framingham said.
The first cloned animal was a sheep born in Scotland in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1639 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Probing Gay Harassment  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Army leaders, stung by the murder of a gay private by a
fellow soldier last summer, are investigating the incident at Fort Campbell,
Ky., defense officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The investigation also will examine how the Defense Department's policy on
gays in the military is being implemented by commanders in the field throughout
the Army. The policy has come under increasing attack from critics in the
aftermath of the killing at Fort Campbell, and Defense Secretary William Cohen
last month ordered a 90-day review after President Clinton declared it was not
working as intended.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army robe will be headed by it inspector general, Lt. Gen. Michael
Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ackerman investigation was requested by the commander of Fort Campbell,
Maj. Gen. Robert T. Clark, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Ackerman will look into the harassment that witnesses said Pfc. Barry
Winchell suffered at Fort Campbell before he was beaten to death by a fellow
soldier last July. Last Saturday, a military court sentenced Winchell's
roommate, Specialist Justin R. Fisher, to 12 1/2 years in prison as part of a
plea bargain. The deal enabled Fisher to avoid more serious charges of being an
accomplice to the murder and helping cover it up.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, Pvt. Calvin Glover was convicted and sentenced to life in
prison for beating Winchell to death with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
	   Outrage over the incident has put a renewed spotlight on the effectiveness
of the Defense Department's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy of allowing gays to
serve in uniform so long as they keep their sexual orientation private. Critics
say that in practice the policy doesn't work because suspected gays are
threatened and harassed.
</P>
<P>
	   One sergeant who testified at Glover's trial said he had questioned Winchell
about his sexuality, which is a violation of the ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to examining the circumstances leading up to Winchell's death,
Ackerman is to look at what the military calls the ``command climate'' -- the
on-base environment created by its leaders. Ackerman also will look more broadly
at the way the ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy is implemented throughout the
Army.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1640 </TRAILER>
