<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki polishes 2000-01 budget; Bruno talks reform again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - With 5,000 criminals' DNA samples being collected
monthly, Gov. George Pataki said his state budget presentation to the
Legislature Tuesday will propose almost doubling state funds for genetic testing
and analysis.
<P>
	   Pataki said the value he places on the crime-fighting capabilities of DNA
will be reflected in the $11.8 million he will ask lawmakers to appropriate in
the new budget. That would be up from the $6.5 million the state is spending for
DNA programs in the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki is scheduled to release the 2000-01 spending plan on Tuesday. It will
be for the fiscal year beginning April 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the governor, the state DNA database has taken in 5,473 samples
since a new law expanding the scope of the project took effect on Dec. 1, 1999,
and officials expect about 5,000 samples to come in every month for the next
year and a half. People convicted of the most serious crimes had been required
since 1994 to submit samples, but starting in December more minor offenders were
also included under the database.
</P>
<P>
	   Inmates already in state prisons for committing certain crimes also became
subject to the DNA sampling program on Dec. 1 for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the funds for maintaining the database, the governor said he
would ask that $850,000 be distributed to the New York City Police Department,
the New York City Medical Examiner's Office, the Suffolk County Crime Lab, the
Westchester County Crime Lab and the State Police Forensic Center for
DNA-related purposes.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki said the four labs will be able to analyze evidence in 600 unsolved
cases while the NYPD will use the money to improve DNA crime scene collection
techniques.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile Monday, state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said he would
ask Pataki not to call any of the "three-men-in-a-room" budget meetings this
year. Those are the sessions, much criticized by reformers and many legislators,
where the governor, the Assembly speaker and the Senate majority leader sit
behind closed doors and hash out the most important aspects of new budgets and
other crucial matters.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm going to ask the governor not to call any, and the governor is the
governor and he'll do whatever he sees fit," Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
	   There was no immediate comment from Pataki's office on Bruno's pledge.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno, who has advocated for a more public budget process, wouldn't pledge
not to go to any of the private meetings if Pataki decided to call them,
however.
</P>
<P>
	   "I guess it would depend on the time and the place," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno also said that he would advocate conference committees on budget
reform if the Assembly passed a budget reform package. The Senate will pass its
budget reform package Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "If the speaker will pass his package and we pass our package, yes,
absolutely, it's a very valid public forum," Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki's budget proposal will be his sixth as governor and the first for
Acting Budget Director Carole Stone. She was appointed by Pataki after the
state's former budget director, Robert King, was selected late last year as the
new chancellor of the State University of New York system.
</P>
<P>
	   During an appearance Monday near Buffalo to make an economic development
announcement, the governor tried to console Buffalo Bills' fans for their team's
heartbreaking last-second playoff loss over the weekend to Tennessee. The Bills
gave up a touchdown with three seconds to play on a kickoff in which many Bills'
fans thought Tennessee had illegally lateraled the ball forward.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki held up a sign Monday saying, "It was a forward pass.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1643 </TRAILER>
