<HEADLINE> Iran Minister Chided for UK Visit  </HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Iran's foreign minister said Monday he is paying a heavy
price at home for being the first Iranian Cabinet official to visit Britain
since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
	   But things were not much easier in London, where about 30 protesters hurled
eggs and paint at Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi's limousine as he headed to a
45-minute meeting with Prime Minister Tony Blair. Police said a woman was
arrested and charged with criminal damage.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Council of Resistance in Iran, among the dissident Iranian
exile groups that dogged Kharrazi at the start of the two-day visit, said its
supporters were responsible.
</P>
<P>
	   Jewish demonstrators also mounted a two-hour vigil near Blair's Downing
Street office to demand the release of 13 Iranian Jews held for a year on spying
charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Kharrazi shrugged off the protests about his visit, which has aroused strong
opposition in Iran among anti-Western groups.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the legitimate right of people who are not involved in terrorist
activities to express themselves,'' he commented at a news conference with
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside Cook's residence, a few dozen Iranian communists yelled ``Robin
Cook, shame, shame'' through megaphones.
</P>
<P>
	   Kharrazi said he had explained to Blair the difficulties the Iranian
administration faced in responding to Western overtures.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My Foreign Ministry is paying a high price ... in Iran for planning to
normalize relations with the United Kingdom,'' Kharrazi said in English. ``This
can be successful only if the British government participate.''
</P>
<P>
	   The meeting with Blair underlined the importance the Labor Party government
attaches to a visit it says is part of a policy of ``engagement'' to encourage
moderate elements in the onetime pariah state.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics, including some in the United States, regard the European moves as
premature while Iran continues to denounce Israel, criticize the Middle East
peace talks and support extremist groups, including Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A very substantial lingering concern in Washington is whether Iran will
use the terrorist establishment it does support -- it is a state sponsor of
terrorism -- to wreck the peace process,'' said Steven Simon, assistant director
of the London-based International Institute of Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter Temple-Morris, among the legislators on two parliamentary committees
who met Kharrazi, said the aim is to ``bring Iran completely back towards the
Western fold.''
</P>
<P>
	   Relations between Britain and Iran warmed after Iran ended support in
September 1998 for a ``fatwa,'' or religious edict, to kill British author
Salman Rushdie. Many Muslims found Rushdie's novel ``The Satanic Verses''
offensive and insulting to Islam.
</P>
<P>
	   Britain and Iran exchanged ambassadors in May for the first time since 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
