<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge To Hear Cuba Boy Arguments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A judge said Monday that her court has jurisdiction over the
case of a 6-year-old Cuban boy and issued a temporary protective order, allowing
his Miami relatives to fight for custody of him.
</P>
<P>
	   Miami-Dade Circuit Judge Rosa Rodriguez said she will listen to arguments
filed by the attorneys on behalf of Elian Gonzalez, an apparent positive first
step for the relatives to have their appeal for custody of the boy heard in a
U.S. court.
</P>
<P>
	   A hearing was set for March 6.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian was found Thanksgiving clinging to a raft off the coast of Fort
Lauderdale. His mother and stepfather drowned in the failed trip from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   The Immigration and Naturalization Service ruled last week that the boy
should be returned to his father in Cuba by Friday. President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno have endorsed that ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives filed a petition on Friday to appoint a
temporary guardian for the boy, a first step toward preventing his return to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   The petition was filed on behalf of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., issued a subpoena on Friday in an effort to delay
Elian's departure. The subpoena requires the boy to testify before a House
committee Feb. 10.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Monday, Vice President Al Gore questioned whether the INS has the
expertise to decide Elian's fate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd like to see the dispute adjudicated in our courts, where traditionally
questions like what is best for this child are decided,'' Gore said in an
interview on NBC's ``Today'' show. He added: ``This child's mother died in an
effort to get her child's freedom.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore proposed that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, ``come to a place
where he can speak freely and settle the matter.''
</P>
<P>
	   At the White House Monday, President Clinton would not comment on Gore's
comments.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Well, anybody's free to express their opinion about this on whether they
think they did right or wrong,'' the president said. Like Gore, he also would
not comment on Burton's subpoena.
</P>
<P>
	   But Burton's subpoena drew fresh criticism from Robert Edgar, general
secretary of the U.S. National Council of Churches, which sent representatives
to visit Elian's father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Little Elian deserves to be reunited immediately with his biological
father and closest family members in Cuba,'' Edgar said in a statement. ``The
longer this whole process drags on, the more disconnected this small child
becomes from those who have raised him and who love him.''
</P>
<P>
	   In Miami, Elian and his relatives watched a Three Kings Day parade on Sunday
as citywide protests over plans to send him back to Cuba remained on hold.
</P>
<P>
	   The parade was a welcome celebration for the city, which earlier in the week
was beset by protests and traffic slowdowns incited by anti-Castro groups angry
by the INS decision to send Elian back to his father in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   But the city was quiet Sunday, a day after Cuban-American leaders issued a
temporary halt to the demonstrations because of Burton's subpoena.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, a representative of the U.S. National Council
of Churches who visited Elian's father in Cuba, said the boy talks with his
father on the telephone every day from the relatives' home in Miami.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The father is very devoted to this child,'' the minister said Sunday from
New York. ``You can maybe fake a lot of stuff ... but the relationships clearly
were there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
