<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philip Morris lobbyist's case referred to district attorney  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Philip Morris tobacco lobbyist banned from
working in New York for violating state lobbying statutes may also face a
criminal investigation, state lobbying officials said Monday.
<P>
	   The state Lobbying Commission referred the case of Philip Morris lobbyist
Sharon Portnoy, who admitted violating state lobbying laws, to Albany County
District Attorney Sol Greenberg for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission settled its investigation with Portnoy and Philip Morris by
banning the lobbyist from working in the state in the next three years and
fining the company $75,000. But it also has the power to ask for a criminal
investigation if it thinks violations were deliberate.
</P>
<P>
	   "The commission believed that the violation was willful," said David
Grandeau, the commission's executive director.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission investigated Philip Morris for not reporting some of the
gifts it gave to state lawmakers. State law requires lobbyists and their clients
to disclose all expenses, with a specific description of those expenses that
exceed $75.
</P>
<P>
	   It is illegal in New York to give lawmakers and officials any gifts worth
more than $75 if they are intended to influence their official duties.
</P>
<P>
	   Portnoy, Philip Morris' chief lobbyist, allegedly treated more than 60
lawmakers and their aides to more than $12,000 in meals in the first half of
1996 alone but few of those were publicly disclosed.
</P>
<P>
	   Philip Morris officials have said they were unaware of the improper lobby
filing, would cooperate with the Lobbying Commission's investigation and
wouldn't violate the law again.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission said the $75,000 fines it gave Philip Morris were the most it
could have handed down under state law.
</P>
<P>
	   The district attorney could charge Portnoy with falsely filing documents, a
Class A misdemeanor. The maximum penalty is a year in jail and fines of up to
$1,000, Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
	   Greenberg said Monday he had not yet reviewed the file from the Lobbying
Commission, so he couldn't properly comment on it.
</P>
<P>
	   "We'll look at what we have and we'll march from there," said Greenberg, who
also has to worry about the fallout of the Amadou Diallo police brutality case
being tried in his county this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission historically sends reports to the appropriate district
attorney, not the state attorney general, Grandeau said.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorney General Eliot Spitzer reacted angrily after hearing that the
commission referred the case to Greenberg, calling it "outrageous" that the
commission didn't ask for an investigation of Philip Morris itself. He said
asking for an investigation of Portnoy and not Philip Morris protects the
tobacco company from criminal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
	   "This action constitutes an abdication of the commission's statutory duties
and makes a mockery of statutory enforcement procedures," Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Spitzer had earlier asked for the go-ahead to prosecute both Portnoy and
Philip Morris. It was unclear Monday whether Greenberg and Spitzer can share the
jurisdiction in the case.
</P>
<P>
	   That troubled Blair Horner of the New York Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our concern is that this doesn't fall into a prosecutorial black hole,"
Horner said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the state Senate on Monday passed a resolution saying its members
would not accept gifts from lobbyists at all if Assembly members did so as well.
Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno promised earlier that his Senate members
would not accept gifts anymore in light of the Portnoy case, and Democratic
senators soon followed suit.
</P>
<P>
	   A Democratic attempt to pass a rule binding the Republican-controlled Senate
to its promise failed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1717 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Moves on Cuban Boy Case  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Members of Congress are moving on various fronts to block
efforts to return Elian Gonzalez to his father in Cuba. One such tactic --
subpoenaing the 6-year-old boy to testify before a House committee -- was being
reviewed Monday by government lawyers.
</P>
<P>
	   Legislative activity was building as a state court judge in Miami asserted
jurisdiction, granted the boy's Florida relatives temporary custody and ordered
a March 6 hearing on the guardianship issue.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers for the Justice Department and the Immigration and Naturalization
Service were evaluating the earlier congressional subpoena issued by Rep. Dan
Burton, chairman of the House Government Reform Committee, in an effort to delay
Elian's departure.
</P>
<P>
	   Also from Capitol Hill, Sen. Jesse Helms is seeking to make the boy a U.S.
citizen, while other lawmakers are weighing resident status for the father.
</P>
<P>
	   The subpoena issued late Friday requires the child to testify before his
committee Feb. 10. But Burton, R-Ind., does not expect to compel the boy to
appear, spokesman Mark Corallo said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The INS ruled last week that Elian, who was rescued from an inner tube in
the Atlantic Ocean on Thanksgiving Day after his mother drowned while fleeing
Cuba, should be returned to Cuba and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Monday's court ruling in Miami appeared to have the same effect as Burton's
subpoena -- assuring Elian would not soon go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
	   Some committee members questioned whether the subpoena could be enforced,
anyway, given the boy's age and disagreement over who is his legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
	   Corallo said the subpoena was ``intended to give the courts a chance to hear
this case.'' If the boy is returned to Cuba, he said, Burton will subpoena INS
officials ``to explain to the American people why they would do such a thing.''
</P>
<P>
	   But Rep. Henry Waxman of California, the senior Democrat on the committee,
said the subpoena ``is unenforceable and shouldn't have any effect on the
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Congressional subpoenas should be used for legitimate investigative
purposes, not political stunts,'' Waxman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, is
proposing legislation granting Elian full U.S. citizenship. Colleagues,
including Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., flocked to add their names
to the cause.
</P>
<P>
	   Cuban President Fidel Castro ``has won a single round. He did not win the
war,'' said Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., one of the sponsors of the
citizenship bill, .
</P>
<P>
	   In the House, GOP Rep. Benjamin Gilman of New York, chairman of the
International Relations Committee, proposed that Elian's father be granted
resident status if he can make it to the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, R-Fla., a sponsor of the citizenship bill said she
and other members of the Florida delegation also might support such an approach,
although she wanted to give the Florida family a chance to be heard.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Despite all the international intrigue, this all boils down to a custody
battle,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the campaign trail, Al Gore broke ranks with President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno in questioning the INS decision.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd like to see the dispute adjudicated in our courts, where traditionally
questions like `what is best for this child' are decided,'' the vice president
said on NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
	   He said he doubted that the INS had ``the experience and the expertise'' to
make a custody decision. Gore also cited a lack of compelling evidence that
Elian's father was sincere ``about what is in his child's best interest.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, continuing to support the INS, said Monday: ``I think the INS tried
to do what was right by the child and I think that they did the best they could
with a difficult and controversial situation.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about Gore's comments, Clinton said, ``Well, anybody's free to express
their opinion about this.'' The president, addressing Burton's subpoena, just
said that Burton's moves were ``always interesting.''
</P>
<P>
	   Torricelli, who supports Burton's decision to issue the subpoena, said in an
interview, ``This is a legitimate area of policy inquiry'' and not an example of
congressional meddling. The senator visited the child in Miami last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
