<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, activists call for feds to monitor Diallo trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Further questioning the change in venue from the
Bronx to Albany, lawmakers and activists called on the U.S. Justice Department
Monday to monitor the upcoming murder trial of four police officers.
<P>
	   The New York State Black, Puerto Rican and Hispanic Legislative Caucus
argued that moving the trial to Albany is an attempt by the defendants to avoid
facing a predominately black and Hispanic jury pool and constitutes special
treatment for the police.
</P>
<P>
	   The four officers are accused of killing West African immigrant Amadou
Diallo in a hail of bullets after mistaking him for a rape suspect.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Diallo incident is another example that something is wrong with the
relationship between communities of color and law enforcement agencies,"
Democrat Assemblyman Keith Wright of Manhattan, chairman of the caucus, said.
"Now more than ever there is a need to take a look at how our police officers
are trained and prepared for the communities in which they perform their
duties."
</P>
<P>
	   Wright expressed particular concern that the percentage of black and
Hispanic jurors be representative of the community. The caucus is also
requesting that New York City and Albany residents be given access and seats in
the court room to monitor the trial.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawmakers also called Monday for the Justice Department to monitor the
trial to make sure there are no violations of civil rights. Justice Depatment
officials say they will pay close attention to the trial, making sure there are
no violations of federal law.
</P>
<P>
	   "There will be a lot of anger in the streets of Albany and in New York City
if justice is not served and that's the primary reason that we have requested
that the Justice Department monitor the trial," Wright said.
</P>
<P>
	   A grand jury indicted the plain clothes officers in March after they fired
41 bullets at Diallo, an unarmed street vender, while searching a Bronx
neighborhood for a rape suspect on Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Attorneys for the officers - Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon and
Richard Murphy - have said their clients mistakenly believed the victim was
reaching for a gun. The four officers were charged with second-degree murder and
all pleaded innocent. Jury selection in their trial is scheduled to begin on
Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
	   The shooting touched off weeks of angry protests leading to more than 1,100
arrests. Activists had planned to demonstrate outside the Bronx courthouse once
the officers went on trial.
</P>
<P>
	   But in an extraordinary decision, a state appeals court moved the trial of
the officers to Albany. In its 11-page ruling, the court said it would be
impossible for the officers to get a fair trial in the Bronx because of media
treatment of the incident.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one is saying that justice won't be served, but we've asked the Justice
Department to monitor the trial just the same," state Sen. David Paterson, a
Manhattan Democrat and another member of the caucus, said. "Because if things do
go awry and there are problems, the Justice Department will be able to put into
process items that might prevent a similar incident occurring again."
</P>
<P>
	   Anne Pope, president of the Albany branch of the NAACP, compared the Diallo
trial to a recent incident in which 33-year-old Tracy Grady allegedly wrested a
gun from two Albany police officers and shot them before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
	   Following the incident, police swarmed through a black neighborhood dressed
in combat fatigues and helmets, allegedly using excessive force and brutalizing
residents in their search for the gunman.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are concerned to make sure that no one thinks Albany is a safe haven for
police who have acted brutally and irresponsibly, whether in New York City or
right here in our own neighborhoods," Pope said.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo supporters in Albany Monday announced the formation of a Capital
Region Justice for Diallo Committee. Its members said they will "monitor" the
trial, provide support for members of Diallo family when they are in Albany for
the proceedings and to continue pushing for formation of a civilian review board
to oversee the activities of Albany police.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1724 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New media, old media: AOL buys Time Warner for $160 billion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - You've got mail. And movies. And music. And magazines.
<P>
	   In the most daring media merger yet, online pioneer America Online is buying
venerable Time Warner Inc., the largest media and entertainment conglomerate in
the world. The $160 billion stock deal would be the biggest corporate merger of
all time as well as an aggressive bet that online delivery of media is the wave
of the future.
</P>
<P>
	   "This merger will launch the next Internet revolution," said Steve Case,
America Online's chairman and chief executive, told a news conference. "We're
still just scratching the surface."
</P>
<P>
	   Case will be chairman of the new company, which will be called AOL Time
Warner Inc., and Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin will be its chief executive.
America Online shareholders will own 55 percent of the company, and Time Warner
shareholders the rest.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal marks a major turning point in the media industry, providing
irrevocable proof of the massive power and value that Internet companies like
AOL have built up over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
	   In combining the leading Internet company with the leading traditional media
company, the deal also shows that despite the many differences between vanguards
of "new media" and "old media," the two sides need each other more than ever
before.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL needed access not only to Time Warner's media content machine - which
produces films, music, TV shows and magazines - but also to Time Warner's large
network of cable TV lines, which is second only to AT&AMP;T's and reaches 20 percent
of U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner, like other major media companies, has been in the middle of a
major effort to reinvent its own Internet strategy. Last year it named its chief
financial officer Richard Bressler to lead a company-wide charge to take
advantage of Internet opportunities and set aside $500 million to invest in
them.
</P>
<P>
	   With the AOL deal, Time Warner acquired a large, well-established online
platform for delivering its content to users, a goal it has had for some time.
"This really completes the digital transformation of Time Warner," Levin, said.
"These two companies are a natural fit."
</P>
<P>
	   At a news conference announcing the deal, Levin deliberately blurred the
lines on the question of which company was the "old media" and which was the
"new" one. Dressed in khaki pants, an open-collar shirt and sports coat while
all the AOL executives wore suits, Levin opened his remarks by saying: "It's a
great pleasure to welcome the suits from Virginia to New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Levin stressed the point that Time Warner itself was the product of a series
of large mergers, and Case said the experience in integrating disparate
companies was a major factor that drew him to the Time Warner management team.
</P>
<P>
	   Time Warner was formed 10 years ago, combining the entertainment company
that grew out of Warner Bros. movie studio with Time Inc., whose flagship
magazine Time was founded in 1923 by Henry Luce. Time Warner bought Ted Turner's
cable company TBS in 1996, which included the all-news channel, CNN, to add to
Time Warner's cable lineup of HBO and Cinemax.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL has been no stranger to deals itself since being formed in 1985. Last
year it acquired Netscape Communications and MovieFone, and it also bought
online competitor CompuServe and a stake in Hughes Electronics, a maker of
electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Painfully aware that telephone dialup connections are far too slow to
provide the kind of online services like TV, movies and music that people want,
AOL has been on a campaign to force cable providers to open up access to their
lines, which can provide much faster access than phone lines. Consumer groups
now fear that with AOL set to own a major cable provider, it may ease up on its
efforts to ensure "open access."
</P>
<P>
	   Coming just four months after the latest blockbuster media merger, the
proposed combination of CBS Corp. and Viacom Inc., also raised concerns from
consumer groups and senators about the increasing consolidation of ownership
among major media companies.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Mike DeWine, chairman of the antitrust subcommittee, said the deal
"raises a whole host of competition and public policy issues."
</P>
<P>
	   "Is this merger the effective beginning of the end of the Internet as an
effective counterweight to traditional media outlets, or is this just another
step on the road to making the Internet a more useful and viable source of
information?" said DeWine, a Republican from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   Several consumer advocacy groups, including the Consumers Union and the
Center for Media Education, released a joint statement expressing disappointment
with the deal, which it called the "sad result of the Clinton administration's
weak competition policy."
</P>
<P>
	   "Consumers do not want to be beholden to a giant media-Internet
dictatorship, even if it promises to be a benevelont one," the groups said. "We
want the Federal Communications Commission to require open access, regardless of
the promises made by the players."
</P>
<P>
	   Case said the company remains committed to providing consumers with as many
choices as possible, and predicted that the deal would result in several new
companies offering Internet access service.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal is subject to regulatory approvals and the approval of AOL and Time
Warner shareholders. The companies said the merger was expected to be finalized
by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department said Monday it was unclear whether it or the Federal
Trade Commission will be asked to approve the proposed merger. Each agency has
its own group of antitrust experts, and they typically split regulatory reviews
after deciding among themselves whose experts are most appropriate to decide the
questions that such a mega-meger might raise.
</P>
<P>
	   Case said he first approached Levin about a possible combination in October.
The fact that no advance word leaked out about the discussions was a sign that
the new executive team likes and trusts each other, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Turner, who owns 9 percent of Time Warner, where he is vice chairman, will
keep the title with the new company. He signed over his shares Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal values Time Warner at about $106.87 1/2 a share, a rich premium of
65 percent over its price of $64.75 a share late Friday. Time Warner shares
soared 39 percent on news of the deal, climbing $25.25 to $90 a share as of the
4 p.m. EST close of the New York Stock Exchange. AOL shares fell $2.50 to $7.25,
which caused the value of the deal to fall from $166 billion when the
acquisition was announced before stock markets opened.
</P>
<P>
	   Other Internet and entertainment stocks also got a lift on anticipation of
other deals. Among them, Walt Disney jumped $4.75 to $35.87 1/2 and News Corp.
rose $7.31 1/4 to 45.06 1/4 on the NYSE, while Lycos leaped $9 to $79.75 and
Yahoo! climbed $28.81 1/4 to $436.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   Wall Street analysts were bullish on the deal, saying it extended the reach
of both companies. "It makes a lot of sense," said Tom Wolzien, media analyst at
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
	   The transaction would surpass the biggest proposed takeover before Monday,
the $150 billion hostile bid for German telecommunications company Mannesmann by
Britain's Vodafone, the world's largest mobile phone company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
