<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL is acquiring Time Warner for about $166 billion in stock in what would
be the biggest corporate merger ever. America Online shareholders would own 55
percent of the combined company, which will be called AOL Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberty Media owns 9 percent of Time Warner shares.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies said they will jointly develop technology that delivers
Internet access, navigation, e-mail and emergency assistance to drivers in their
cars.
</P>
<P>
	   Gateway said it will begin using chips made by AMD in its personal computers
after supply problems with chip maker Intel hurt its sales in the most recent
quarter. Robertson Stephens raised its rating on AMD shares.
</P>
<P>
	   The insurance company said it expects fourth-quarter earnings to come in at
about 5 cents to 10 cents a share, well below analysts' estimates of 58 cents a
share. Aon cited pretax charges related to an insurance settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   Telephone company Nextlink has agreed to acquire Internet-access provider
Concentric for about $2.9 billion in stock. The deal will give Nextlink the
ability to provide high-speed Internet access and other data services to its
customers.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinical trials of the company's citicoline drug showed that it failed to
significantly improve the neurological functions of stroke victims. Interneuron
said it was disappointed with the results of the trial, but hasn't decided
whether to work on developing it further.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
