<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court: $175,000 award to AC cop should stand  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday upheld a
$175,000 award to a veteran police officer who was sexually harassed by
colleagues and supervisors.
<P>
	   Without comment, the justices rejected an appeal by the Atlantic City Police
Department, which said Sgt. Donna Hurley's 1996 award was due in part to a
flawed instruction to jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   Hurley, the first woman in the department to reach the rank of sergeant,
accused supervisors and fellow officers of harassing her with obscene comments
and drawings. Once, she said, a sanitary napkin with sergeant's stripes was hung
above the podium where she conducted daily roll call. Another time, someone hung
one from the rearview mirror of her patrol car.
</P>
<P>
	   The harassment was condoned by department officials, who passed her over for
promotion, she said in her 1993 civil suit.
</P>
<P>
	   A jury originally awarded her $1.2 million, but the amount was later reduced
to $875,000 by U.S. District Judge Joseph Irenas in Camden.
</P>
<P>
	   On appeal, the U.S. 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the $175,000 in
compensatory damages but ordered a new trial on the $700,000 punitive damages
verdict.
</P>
<P>
	   The new trial has yet to be scheduled. Lawyers for both sides were waiting
for the outcome of the Supreme Court case before returning to court, according
to Dennis Tuohy, the police department's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
	   The police department's appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court said that the
jurors should not have been presented with a quid pro quo theory of liability in
regard to Hurley's claims against Capt. Henry Madamba.
</P>
<P>
	   Hurley claimed that Madamba asked her to have sex with him, promising a
promotion if she did and retaliation if she didn't. But Madamba denied it and
Hurley's lawyer never offered evidence that she was punished for rejecting the
alleged advances, Tuohy said.
</P>
<P>
	   As a result, Tuohy said, there was no quid pro quo - a Latin expression
meaning "something for something."
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Madamba nor then-Chief Nicholas Rifice was found liable in the case.
</P>
<P>
	   Hurley and her lawyer, Clifford Van Syoc of Cherry Hill, could not be
reached for comment on the ruling Monday. The telephone rang unanswered at her
office in the police department's community relations division.
</P>
<P>
	   Van Syoc was trying a case, according to a woman who answered the telephone
at his Cherry Hill law office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
