<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:40 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, Jan. 10, 2000
Record Nasdaq Gain; Dow Has Record
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology and media shares led the Nasdaq
composite to its biggest point gain ever and the Dow Jones
industrials to a new closing high as investors celebrated the $160
billion planned merger of America Online and Time Warner. The
Nasdaq composite index rose 166.97 to 4,049.59, according to
preliminary calculations. The technology-dominated index has risen
more than 300 points in the past two sessions, wiping out most
remnants of a three-day slump that knocked 400 points off the
Nasdaq last week. The Dow rose 49.64 to 11,572.20, topping Friday's
record close of 11,522.56. Technology stocks posted eye-popping
gains in a wide range of sectors. But the biggest story on Wall
Street was AOL, whose bold move to acquire Time Warner spurred a
wave of speculation about additional mergers between new-line and
old-line information providers.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
Dow Industrials:        11572.20  + 49.64
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1776  Declines 1348  Unchgd  432
