Gold(final) -    $281.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   $5.270  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
AOL To Buy Time Warner for $160B 
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner stock soared about 39 percent today
on news of its planned merger with America Online. Aol stock was
down 2 1/2 at 71 1/4 but Time Warner was up 25 5/16 at 90 1/4. Time Warner,
the world's largest media and entertainment company, is being
acquired by America Online for about $160 billion in stock in what
would be the biggest corporate merger ever. The deal announced
today raises the stakes in the consolidation scramble in the media
industry and comes just four months after another blockbuster media
merger, the proposed combination of CBS Corp. and Viacom Inc. The
deal is subject to certain conditions, including regulatory
approvals and the approval of AOL and Time Warner shareholders. The
companies said the merger was expected to be finalized by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   Asian Nations Top Economy List
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two societies under authoritarian regimes were
cited by international economists today as the most economically
free in the world -- Hong Kong and Singapore. An index compiled with
the help of think tanks in 53 countries ranks countries on a
variety of economic issues. It reaches the same conclusion about
the top of the list as a similar report by the conservative
Heritage Foundation last month. Both also scored New Zealand third
and the United States fourth. Hong Kong topped economic freedom
lists before it was returned to China in 1997 and has not slipped,
said the report's principal author, James Gwartney.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM Gives a Nod to Linux
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM today announced that all of its powerful
network computers will be able to run on the Linux operating
system, embracing the fast-growing rival to other Unix formats and
Microsoft's Windows as the best platform for Internet commerce. The
leading manufacturer of computer servers said all four of its
product lines will now be compatible with Linux, a Unix-based
operating system that has grown hugely popular among independent
software developers since its Finnish creator started giving it
away for free. Coming from IBM, the announcement essentially
finalizes the mainstreaming of Linux.
</P>
<P>
	   GM To Buy Remainder of Saab
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors continued its international
shopping spree Monday, picking up the 50 percent of Swedish luxury
automaker Saab Automobile AB that it does not already own. The
deal, terms of which were not disclosed, was the latest GM has made
with foreign automakers as it shores up positions in overseas
markets. Last year, GM bought 20 percent of Subaru, agreed to buy
engines from Honda and began negotiations to buy struggling Korean
automaker Daewoo. GM bought a 50 percent stake and management
control of Saab in December 1989 for $600 million and a $100
million investment in Saab's operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Ford Plans Th!nk Electric Vehicles
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor, which put the world on wheels powered
by gasoline, will soon sell a plastic-bodied hatchback, a golf cart
and bicycles -- all powered by electricity. The line of electric
vehicles, under the brand name Th!nk, will become the company's
home for vehicles powered by something other than internal
combustion engines. It will not only build vehicles, but act as a
research center for Ford. Ford showed off the Th!nk line Monday
during previews for the North American International Auto Show. The
show opens to the public on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Cos. Settle With FTC on Coupons
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Three companies agreed today to modify coupon
and cash rebate programs that federal regulators called ``false and
misleading.'' Bumble Bee Seafoods, Memtek Products and UMAX
Technologies reached agreements with the Federal Trade Commission
to compensate some consumers and speed rebates to others. The
public has until Feb. 9 to comment before the FTC decides whether
to make the agreements final. None of the companies admitted any
violations of law.
</P>
<P>
	   Aetna May Split Off Online Ventures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna, the nation's largest health insurer, is
considering spinning off its online health division into a separate
public company. The Hartford, Conn.-based Aetna may combine its
popular InteliHealth Internet site with its other online services
into a separate subsidiary, spokeswoman Joyce Oberdorf said today.
A decision is expected by this summer. InteliHealth.com, a joint
venture with Johns Hopkins Health System, is one of the most
visited health care sites on the Internet. Taking the online
division public would help Aetna's stockholders because they would
get a piece of an Internet company at a time when such entities are
the rage on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   SBC Seeks Long-Distance OK
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications asked federal regulators
today for approval to become the second Baby Bell to offer
long-distance service to its local customers. Hot on the heels of a
decision by the Federal Communications Commission to let Bell
Atlantic provide long-distance in New York, SBC filed an
application with the FCC seeking to do the same in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa Earnings Up 53 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa's fourth-quarter earnings rose 53
percent, beating Wall Street expectations, as the No. 1 aluminum
maker cut back on its inventory and also paid less tax on its
operations in Australia. Alcoa also announced today it was raising
its dividend and splitting its stock. The company reported earnings
of $333.9 million, or 89 cents per share, compared with $218.3
million, or 59 cents per share, in 1998's fourth quarter. Analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson financial had predicted earnings of
76 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
	   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Gains in telecommunications and telecom stocks
drove European stock indexes higher today, boosted by merger plans
between America Online Inc. and media company Time Warner Inc.
Investors were spurred on by the prospect of similar mergers
between leading media and Internet players. The Dow Jones Stoxx
Index of 606 European companies closed up 5.64 points at 365.39,
while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended up 6.05 points at
401.40. The media sector of the Dow Jones Stoxx Index overshadowed
the rest of the market with a massive 9.4 percent rise.
</P>
