<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Launches China WTO Campaign  </HEADLINE>
   By TERENCE HUNT AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton, stung by the collapse of global trade
talks at Seattle, urged Congress to vote ``at the earliest possible time'' on a
trade deal with China to keep it from becoming embroiled in election-year
politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton launched a drive Monday to line up votes for granting China
permanent normal trading relations with the United States as part of a deal to
allow the world's most populous nation to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This agreement is a good deal for America,'' the president said. U.S.
companies would gain better access to China's market in every sector from
agriculture to telecommunications to automobiles as Beijing cuts tariffs on
American goods by half or more over five years, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The China agreement likely will be the last major trade initiative of
Clinton's presidency. Clinton named Commerce Secretary William Daley and Steve
Ricchetti, deputy chief of staff in the White House, to lead the congressional
effort.
</P>
<P>
	   The campaign faces stiff resistance from organized labor, environmental
groups and their Democratic allies, who believe that low wages and lax pollution
standards in China will undercut American workers. Religious groups are expected
to raise objections about China's human rights problems.
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Clinton is counting for support from Republican lawmakers
and American business, which is eager to dive into China's huge market. Thomas
Donahue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, praised Clinton's selections
of Daley and Ricchetti.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Daley brings the sophistication of a commerce secretary who has traveled
around the world and the background of a Chicago politician. That is just what
we need,'' Donahue said.
</P>
<P>
	   Donahue said the business community would mount an all-out lobbying campaign
and cautioned lawmakers against trying to delay a vote trying to take the issue
into the fall campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The president was right on target when he said we have to move
aggressively and quickly,'' Donahue said. ``People who try to use this as an
election-year political issue will find themselves in an unhappy situation with
the business community.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president said chances for approval are ``quite good if we can get a
vote early in the year. I think this is something that is in the national
interest. I have made it clear to the leaders of Congress that I strongly
support it and that I think it should be scheduled for a vote at the earliest
possible time.
</P>
<P>
	   ``And if we do that,'' he said, ``I think we've got an excellent chance to
pass it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. David Dreier, R-Calif., chairman of the House Rules Committee and a
leader on trade matters, urged Clinton to exert his influence on reluctant
Democrats rather than rely wholly on Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am certain that if the president can convince a majority of Democrats in
the House to support him on this important trade initiative that we will prevail
in Congress,'' Dreier said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's trade campaign suffered a major setback last year when World Trade
Organization talks in Seattle failed under the weight of massive street protests
and internal bickering among the 135 nations in the WTO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
