<HEADLINE> Palladium Futures At New High  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Palladium futures surged to another all-time high Monday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in a continuing rally resulting from tight world supplies
and uncertainty about exports from Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   In other commodities markets, corn prices reached a two-month high and
coffee jumped after a long-awaited estimate pegged the crop lower than expected
in Brazil, the world's No. 1 producer.
</P>
<P>
	   Palladium has pushed through its previous price ceiling several times in
recent weeks because of the lack of Russian exports on the market. Russia is by
far the world's leading producer of the metal, which is used heavily in
automobile catalytic converters and to a lesser extent for electronics,
dentistry and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
	   Russian officials are still trying to undo a bureaucratic tangle that has
prevented the metal's sale by the nation's export agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Acting President Vladimir Putin has signed platinum export quotas for this
year, but it remains uncertain what will happen with palladium.
</P>
<P>
	   Palladium for March delivery settled up $8.05 at $451.95 per ounce after
hitting an all-time high of $456.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have seen considerable demand in this market for the last several weeks,
hence the reason for new highs, it seems, every other day," said David Meger,
senior metals analyst for Alaron Trading in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
	   He said Moscow is expected to resume palladium exports within a month, but
"until the actual product hits the market, there is going to be a lot of
uneasiness."
</P>
<P>
	   Corn's modest rise of late on the Chicago Board of Trade is attributed to
bullish sentiments that the long price slump may be over. On Monday, it also was
helped by news that the U.S. Department of Agriculture has received partial
funding for its food aid program, which could result in shipments to Russia that
would ease the U.S. grain glut.
</P>
<P>
	   March corn rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.08 1/2 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Coffee traders went on a buying spree early in the session at New York's
Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange after respected agronomist Leon Yallouz estimated
Brazil's drought-affected 2000-01 crop at 25 million to 27.5 million 60-kilogram
(132-pound) bags -- 1-2 million bags less than had been expected.
</P>
<P>
	   The drought slashed production from what was once pegged at a bumper crop of
40 million bags.
</P>
<P>
	   Some Brazilian experts cautioned, however, that it's still too early to get
an accurate reading on the crop, and the price fell back after surging.
</P>
<P>
	   March coffee ended up 3.6 cents at $1.1175 a pound after initially rising
11.85 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1747 </TRAILER>
