<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alcoa Earnings Up 53 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Alcoa's fourth-quarter earnings rose 53 percent, beating
Wall Street expectations, as the No. 1 aluminum maker cut back on its inventory
and also paid less tax on its operations in Australia.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa also announced Monday it was raising its dividend and spliting its
stock.
</P>
<P>
	   The company reported earnings of $333.9 million, or 89 cents per share,
compared with $218.3 million, or 59 cents per share, in 1998's fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson financial had predicted earnings of
76 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
	   Revenue rose 1 percent to $4.2 billion to $4.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa's stock, which has risen sharply so far this year as investors have
embraced the stocks of manufacturers such as Alcoa, fell 25 cents Monday to
$84.37 1/2 a share in trading at 5:15 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa said it had a $31 million, or 8 cent per share, benefit from inventory
reductions. It also attributed its performance to a drop in its Australian tax
rate, from 29.9 percent from 32 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also reported an increase in its administrative costs during the
latest quarter. But CEO Alain Belda said in a statement that Alcoa's operations
have become more streamlined.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, the company said earnings went up 23 percent. Net income
was $1.05 billion, or $2.82 per share, compared with $853 million, or $2.42 per
share, for 1998. The company said it was the first time its one-year earnings
surpassed $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Full-year revenues came to $16.32 billion, up from $15.34 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said it was raising the quarterly dividend on its common stock
to 25 cents a share from 18.75 cents. On an annual basis, the dividend is rising
to $1 per share from 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa's board also voted to split the company's stock 2 for 1. The split,
subject to shareholder approval at the company's annaul meeting May 12, is
scheduled to take effect June 9 for shareholders who hold Alcoa stock on May 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
