<DOCNO> APW20000110.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Temps May Be Rewarded  </HEADLINE>
   By TED BRIDIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court refused Monday to free Microsoft Corp.
from having to pay as many as 10,000 temporary employees who were not allowed to
join the company's lucrative stock-purchase program.
</P>
<P>
	   The justices let stand a federal appeals court ruling that Microsoft had
said ``has far-reaching implications for the field of employment law.'' The
nation's high-tech industry has classified some employees as temporary workers
to avoid paying certain benefits and to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The court action opens the way for attorneys representing these former
Microsoft employees to begin calculating how much each might be owed based on
stock they hypothetically could have purchased at a discount.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of that stock has risen nearly 2,400 percent since the original
lawsuit was filed in 1992. An attorney for the former employees, Stephen Strong,
said the case affects more than 6,000 workers -- and possibly as many as 10,000.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft said it now has between 5,500 and 7,000 temporary or contingent
workers in the United States, in addition to its roughly 32,000 permanent
employees.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Microsoft was a startup company that wanted to be efficient,'' Strong
said. ``Over time it grew, but it hasn't really matured in treating its normal
employees in ways they should be treated.''
</P>
<P>
	   The justices on Monday, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court
ruling that, according to Microsoft's unsuccessful appeal, ``has far-reaching
implications for the field of employment law.''
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft spokesman Dan Leach said the company was ``disappointed the high
court has decided now is not the time to review those issues. We look forward to
putting the case behind us, and we value the contributions of everyone who makes
great software for our customers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Eight people who once worked for the Redmond, Wash., computer software
company sued in 1992, saying they and thousands more ``permatemps'' illegally
had been shut out of an employee stock purchase plan that allows employees to
buy Microsoft stock at a 15 percent discount.
</P>
<P>
	   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals twice ruled, most recently in May,
that the temporary employees wrongly had been treated as ``independent
contractors'' or employees of employment agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   The appeals court rulings apply only in the nine Western states -- Alaska,
Arizona, California, Hawaii, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, Oregon, and Washington --
in the 9th Circuit.
</P>
<P>
	   They had been entitled under Washington state law to be considered regular
employees, the appeals court said, instructing a federal trial judge to
determine what damages each of thousands of Microsoft's former temporary
employees is owed.
</P>
<P>
	   In the appeal acted on Monday, Microsoft contended the appeals court allowed
too large a ``class'' of former temporary employees to have a stake in the case.
That class could include current temporary employees and any temp who worked at
Microsoft since 1987.
</P>
<P>
	   The appeal also argued that the 9th Circuit court wrongly concluded ``that
an individual employed by an employment agency can simultaneously claim employee
benefits from both the employment agency and the agency's client for which the
individual performs services.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although the case acted on Monday centered only on Microsoft's
stock-purchase plan, temporary employees also are suing the company for health
insurance and pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   The case acted on today is Microsoft Corp. vs. Vizcaino, 99-498.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1757 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chrysler Unveils New Minivans  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- For all the $2.8 billion that DaimlerChrysler AG spent to
develop the new versions of its Chrysler and Dodge minivans, one of its most
important tools was a collection of bent Cross metal pens.
</P>
<P>
	   The pens belong to Chrysler president Jim Holden, who stuck them into the
power sliding doors on competing models to test how badly they would get
mangled. He ordered his developers to design power doors that would keep pens,
fingers and other objects from the same fate.
</P>
<P>
	   The 2001 minivans unveiled Monday reflect that attention to detail, which
Chrysler hopes will be enough to keep its old customers and win back defectors.
</P>
<P>
	   "In the Chrysler, Jeep and Dodge brands we're famous for a few things. First
and foremost it's minivans," Holden said at the North American International
Auto Show preview. "It's extremely important to us."
</P>
<P>
	   The minivans are one of the staples of Chrysler's profits, and one of the
products most beloved within the company; Holden had spent time as head of the
minivan program before becoming Chrysler president last year. It's important
enough that after the merger between Chrysler Corp. and Daimler-Benz AG in 1998,
Mercedes killed off a minivan it had been developing.
</P>
<P>
	   The basic formula for a successful minivan was set mostly by Chrysler in
1984; a front-wheel drive vehicle that drives like a car, with plenty of space.
Since then, the company has sold 8 million copies.
</P>
<P>
	   But in the 1990s, other automakers figured out the formula and had to rely
on nifty features like multiple cupholders, built-in child seats and power doors
to lure customers. Minivans also picked up an image as the driving choice for
suburban soccer moms. Sport utility vehicles offered similar room and a better
self-image for many drivers.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales growth slowed. Chrysler kept up with the trends and held onto 40
percent of the market, but saw its toughest challenges emerge last year. Power
doors turned out to be a must-have feature, and Chrysler held off while
competitors added them. New models from Honda Motor Co. and Ford Motor Co. began
to capture customers away from Chrysler's aging designs, last updated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Honda's Odyssey was especially popular, and some dealers even had waiting
lists. Chrysler felt the blow -- its U.S. minivan sales were down 4 percent last
year, to 503,830, and the company has recently increased incentives on all
models.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's tough and there are many, many competitors," Holden said. "It puts a
bigger obligation on us to invent and innovate, and that's what we did."
</P>
<P>
	   The new models -- the Chrysler Voyager, the Dodge Caravan and the Chrysler
Town &AMP; Country -- are completely new, but look fairly similar to their
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
	   Chrysler leap-frogged into the power door battle with three per vehicle --
two on the sides and a power rear gate. When activated, the gate lets out two
seconds of warning beeps before opening. If something blocks its path opening or
closing, it stops. And it has a "finger-guard" -- a sensor running along the
seal between the door and the frame that also stops the gate if it detects an
object like a metal pen.
</P>
<P>
	   The company also touts a new design for power side doors. Chrysler engineers
wanted the doors to close smoothly under manual power, a problem they saw in
other designs. So they put the motor inside the door, and connected it to the
body with a special plastic linkage that looks like a thick bike chain running
below the door.
</P>
<P>
	   The frame was made stiffer for a more stable ride, and the engines were
reworked to improve power, with the strongest V6 now turning out 230 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
	   The interior also features a removable console that can go in the first or
second rows and contains ports for charging cell phones. Engineers also worked
to make the interior quiet enough that passengers in the third row could be
heard by the driver.
</P>
<P>
	   The new models will be priced within the current range, from about $18,000
to $37,000, and will go on sale this summer. Holden said sales this year will
slow down temporarily while the company converts its plants to building the new
models, but should rebound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1758 </TRAILER>
