<HEADLINE> Man Shot in U.S. Embassy in Moscow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A man identified as a Russian soldier was shot and wounded on
the grounds of the U.S. Embassy compound Monday after breaking in and apparently
trying to steal a car, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The report conflicted with that given by Russian police, who said two
soldiers broke into the embassy and were stopped by a Marine guard, who opened
fire, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the two men was wounded, and was turned over to Russian authorities.
Interfax identified him as Yevgeny Taynakov, 23. He was operated on, but
officials at a Moscow hospital declined to comment on his condition.
</P>
<P>
	   A U.S. Embassy spokesman confirmed that an intruder had been wounded, but
refused to give details or confirm whether the incident was a shooting involving
a Marine guard.
</P>
<P>
	   The embassy statement made no mention of a second intruder. Interfax
reported that police seized a man suspected of being a second intruder near a
subway station a few hundred yards north of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
	   Both the wounded man and the suspect detained later Monday are servicemen in
an Interior Ministry paramilitary unit, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
	   The embassy spokesman said he did not know how the intruder gained access to
the heavily guarded compound located in the heart of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
	   The ITAR-Tass news agency, citing Russian police, said the intruder was
trying to steal a car and was intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
	   The intruder was spotted breaking into and trying to start up an embassy
vehicle, which he then crashed, the embassy spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the intruder was using
the vehicle in ways that ``potentially endangered the lives and safety of
embassy personnel.''
</P>
<P>
	   Security was heavy around the embassy Monday night, with at least two
Russian police standing outside entrances that generally are guarded by one
officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
