<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> City hands in proposal for arena, with or without state aid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The city presented several versions of a plan Monday
to build a basketball and hockey arena in Newark, insisting it could build the
arena without the state's help and with only one team.
<P>
	   "It would be a very heavy burden, but it can be done," Al Faiella, the
city's deputy mayor for economic development and housing, said of the
possibility of an arena unfunded by the state and occupied only by the New
Jersey Nets.
</P>
<P>
	   The owners of the NBA team bought the Nets with the intention of moving the
team from the Meadowlands complex in East Rutherford to the state's largest
city.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey Devils owner John McMullen, however, has said he wants to take
his team from the Meadowlands to Hoboken. Gov. Christie Whitman and sports
finance experts have said that two teams would have to play at the same arena to
make it profitable.
</P>
<P>
	   Without the promise of either state or corporate aid, the city pressed
ahead, presenting its proposals for an 18,500-seat arena to the city's Central
Planning Board Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
	   The city's most ambitious plan for the arena is a $360 million proposal that
would include the arena, indoor parking garages that would hold up to 2,700 cars
and a covered walkway from Penn Station. The plan requires $70 million in state
aid, $170 million from Prudential Insurance Co. of America and city support.
</P>
<P>
	   A scaled-down, $290 million plan would have less parking, no walkway and
less commercial development around the arena, Faiella said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayor Sharpe James said an arena and the business that would accompany it
would revitalize the city.
</P>
<P>
	   "When we go to Baltimore, we go to Cleveland, Detroit, you see how those
fans enjoy those facilities," James said Monday. "When you look at jobs that
will be created, when you look at the new stores, the hotels, the retail, the
economic development, the escalation of value of property, it becomes a win-win
for the entire community."
</P>
<P>
	   But Whitman spokesman Peter McDonough said the state's decision to
contribute to the Newark arena likely will depend on whether two teams decide to
play there.
</P>
<P>
	   If the state gave money to Newark's arena with only one team in it, "they
would have to demonstrate the arena could work with one team," McDonough said.
"It's awfully hard to see how that could get done."
</P>
<P>
	   City officials say the arena can be used for rock concerts, circuses and
other large-scale entertainment.
</P>
<P>
	   Devils and Nets management didn't return telephone calls on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Prudential signed a letter of intent last summer to contribute $170 million,
raising more than half of it from other corporations. The insurer said at the
time it would prefer that two teams play in the arena.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesman Bob DeFillippo wouldn't say whether the company would still
contribute to a one-team arena, but said Monday "the status of our commitment
hasn't changed."
</P>
<P>
	   "We believe that the project continues to be viable. It would be a very good
thing for downtown Newark," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   A public hearing on the city's arena proposals is scheduled for Feb. 7. The
city would need approval from the planning board and City Council to go ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1811 </TRAILER>
