<HEADLINE> Kohl Successor Admits Scandal Role  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- The man who succeeded Helmut Kohl as leader of the
Christian Democratic Union admitted Monday that he and others in the party bore
responsibility for a finance scandal swirling around the former chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfgang Schaeuble said on ARD national television that on some occasions
during party meetings, Kohl spoke of ``financial sources.''
</P>
<P>
	   Schaeuble said he and other party leaders ``all had a part in the
responsibility for not questioning'' Kohl's remarks.
</P>
<P>
	   Schaeuble also admitted receiving $52,000 cash after a 1994 party-sponsored
affair from businessman Karlheinz Schreiber, who is fighting extradition from
Canada for suspected tax evasion in Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   Schaeuble said he turned the money over to party finance administrators and
only became aware recently that it had not been recorded as required.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In view of the current situation, one should have asked more questions,''
Schaeuble said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl, who led the Christian Democrats for 25 years until his election defeat
in 1998, admitted accepting up to $1 million in cash donations in the 1990s that
were kept off the party's books, apparently in violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
	   He has refused to identify the donors, saying he will not break his word to
keep their identities a secret.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl has said the money was used to get the conservative party a foothold in
eastern Germany after unification in 1990. He denied ever using any of the money
for himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
