<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 54-Year-Old Woman Has Triplets  </HEADLINE>
   By LINDA ASHTON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) -- At an age when most women are going through menopause,
54-year-old Arcelia Garcia is once again dealing with diapers and night
feedings.
</P>
<P>
	   She gave birth to triplets over the weekend -- 16 years after her last child
was born.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Garcia of Sunnyside delivered three healthy girls -- Ariana, Brianna
and CeCelia -- by Caesarean section at about 5 p.m. Saturday at Yakima Valley
Memorial Hospital. The babies were conceived without fertility drugs, a rare
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Garcia and her husband, Guillermo, 60, now have 11 children and 13
grandchildren, with two more grandchildren on the way.
</P>
<P>
	   She said she never worried that she might be too old to rear three more
little ones.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To receive a child, no woman is too old,'' Mrs. Garcia said in Spanish at
a news conference Monday. ``My love for my children that just came here is the
same as for the first one.''
</P>
<P>
	   She said learning that she would have triplets was a big, but wonderful,
surprise. Since their birth, she has seen them three times.
</P>
<P>
	   Arianna, the first born and smallest at 3 pounds, 7 ounces, is in an
incubator. Brianna, the second born, is in a crib and taking a bottle. She
weighed 5 pounds, 12.5 ounces at birth.
</P>
<P>
	   Third-in-line CeCelia, 5 pounds, 1.5 ounces, is in an incubator like her big
sister Arianna.
</P>
<P>
	   A woman in her 50s bearing triplets is extremely rare, especially without
the aid of fertility drugs. Arceli Keh of Highland, Calif., who gave birth at
63, holds the record for the world's oldest mother.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a very extraordinary case,'' said Dr. Diana Smigaj, Mrs. Garcia's
obstetrician.
</P>
<P>
	   The average age for menopause is 51, and Mrs. Garcia was showing some signs,
such as several consecutive missed periods, Smigaj said.
</P>
<P>
	   A single ``menopause baby'' isn't all that uncommon, but triplets are, she
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She just hit the Lotto,'' said Mrs. Garcia's third child, Guadalupe
Garcia, 30, of Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
	   Seven of Mrs. Garcia's eight older children attended the news conference
with her. Her husband was at home, but he has seen pictures of the triplets,
said son Francisco Garcia, 34, of Sunnyside.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's very proud,'' Francisco Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
	   While Mrs. Garcia earlier said she planned to return to work on the family
farm soon, her children have already nixed that idea.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Maybe after six years,'' said son Miguel Garcia, 35, of Santa Rosa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   The babies were born in the 35th week of Mrs. Garcia's pregnancy. A
full-term pregnancy lasts 40 weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Rafaela Rodriguez, 29, was present when her mom's triplets were born. She
said her first thoughts were: ``It's a miracle, for one, and I'm glad it's over
for my mom.''
</P>
<P>
	   Originally from Michoacan, Mexico, Mrs. Garcia and her family moved to
Sunnyside, a town about 30 miles southeast of Yakima, in 1976. She has been a
U.S. citizen since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1827 </TRAILER>
