<DOCNO> APW20000110.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall As Stocks Soar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bond prices fell Monday as traders awaited new
reports on inflation and as stock markets rallied.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond fell  1/2 point, or $5.00 cents per $1,000 in
face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 6.58
percent from 6.54 percent late Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonds fell as stocks staged a broad and sharp advance on news of the planned
merger of Time Warner Inc. and America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to shifting some funds into stocks, bond traders have been edgy
in advance of next month's meeting of Federal Reserve policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised rates three times last year. There are expectations of
another boost in rates to cool off the economy and keep inflation under control
now that fears of a Year 2000 computer disaster have dissipated. But analysts
are divided on how much higher rates will go.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors will get a better reading on inflation later this week when the
federal government issues reports on wholesale and consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates hurt bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
	   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities fell 3/32
point and intermediate maturities fell 3/16 to 9/32 point, reported Bridge
Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.39 percent as the discount rose
0.01 percentage point from Friday to 5.24 percent. Six-month yields were 5.62
percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point from Friday to 5.39 percent.
One-year yields were 6.04 percent as the discount rose 0.05 percentage point to
5.70 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was
5.87 1/2 percent, up from 5.68 3/4 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer said the new contract for its index
of 40 actively traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 to 91 13/16. The average yield
to maturity remained unchanged at 6.26 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
