<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurts so bad: Buffalo Bills fans lament  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Buffalo sports fans are a beat-up bunch. Many drive
through the city with "No Goal" bumper stickers on their cars, and the phrase
"wide right" can still make a grown man cry.
<P>
	   That's why Saturday's loss to the Titans (22-16) hurts so bad: Buffalo just
can't seem to win.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's got to be a conspiracy," said John Stone, a Buffalo contractor and
sports fan. "Somebody - or something - just won't let us have it. It's an evil
force that let's us get close enough to taste a win, but then snatches it from
us."
</P>
<P>
	   Many fans here are still licking their wounds from Scott Norwood's "wide
right" that gave the New York Giants Super Bowl rings in 1991. And then there's
the Bills' Super Bowl losses of 1992, 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   Fast forward to 1999's Stanley Cup Finals where Brett Hull's goal won the
game for Dallas, but not without controversy. Bitter Sabres fans still won't
call it a real victory: Hull's foot was in the crease.
</P>
<P>
	   Saturday just made matters worse.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was devastating," said Jacki DiPirro, president of the Nashville Bills
Backers. "To have that type of swing in emotion in 13 seconds is just
unbearable."
</P>
<P>
	   With 16 seconds left, Ms. DiPirro along with Bills fans everywhere
celebrated Steve Christie's 41-yard field goal, assuming it won the game.
</P>
<P>
	   But then it happened: Titan's tight end Frank Wycheck passed a disputed
lateral to Kevin Dyson who won the game with a 75-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
	   "If it was blatantly a great play that won the game, it would be easier to
swallow," Ms. DiPirro said. "I'm tired of losing with controversial calls. I
mean, I have a 'No Goal' sticker right here on my wall in Nashville."
</P>
<P>
	   President of the Buffalo Bills Booster Club, John Opalka, has a new two-word
mantra for Buffalo fans: "What Lateral?"
</P>
<P>
	   "It hurts that human error is still a part of the game," said Opalka, who
thinks Buffalo's market size has something to do with its sports teams' bad
luck.
</P>
<P>
	   "If a bad call like Hull's no goal happened in New York City, the media and
fans there would create such controversy that it would shatter the league," he
said. "Same thing with Saturday's backward pass."
</P>
<P>
	   Erin Arrigo, a Buffalo State College student, agrees. "We're an underdog
team in an underdog market. It's sick."
</P>
<P>
	   It's logical to wonder how much more Buffalo fans can take. One area
supermarket chain put "Flutie Flakes" on sale this week, a sign that some think
fan support might wane.
</P>
<P>
	   But Buffalo's rabid fans swear that won't happen.
</P>
<P>
	   Opalka, who said the sale is nothing more than a reason to "stock up" on
Flutie Flakes, explained the Boosters are so optimistic about the Bills, they
plan to bury a Bills time capsule at the February meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "When we open it in 25 years, the Bills will still be here and so will the
fans," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "People don't get it when you try to explain, but Buffalo teams get into
your blood," DiPirro said. "They're a part of you."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 1831 </TRAILER>
