<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Rain pelted much of the nation Monday, and snow lightly powdered several
states.
</P>
<P>
	   Low pressure moving across the Great Lakes produced rain and snow in parts
of Wisconsin, Michigan and Minnesota -- although most of the snowfall was light,
with the heaviest (4 inches) occurring in West Ironwood, Mich.
</P>
<P>
	   A cold front extending southward from that low pressure area brought rain to
the East Coast before skies began to clear by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   Fair to partly cloudy skies stretched from southern sections of the Ohio
Valley, south and west across most of the Mississippi Valley and Gulf Coast.
Fair skies also extended west into the southern Plains, with some high clouds
over Oklahoma and western Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
	   Winds -- some gusting to 50 mph-plus -- blew through the northern Plains,
while snow showers were scattered across the Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
	   Scattered areas of rain and mountain snow fell from Colorado, west across
Idaho and northern Nevada.
</P>
<P>
	   Snow also hit Salt Lake City, while rain fell -- and some snow -- stretched
from western Washington south into northwestern California.
</P>
<P>
	   Temperatures in the Lower 48 on Monday ranged from 75 degrees in Key West,
Fla., to zero in Yellowstone, Wyo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
