<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- A Boston television station invited the top Republican and
Democratic presidential candidates to debate weekly until the Feb. 1 primary in
New Hampshire, but only Sen. John McCain jumped at the chance for more
prime-time exposure.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arizona senator accepted the invitation from WCVB-TV to face-off during
its regular newscasts against Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Bush's campaign
declined, saying eight all-candidate debates are on the schedule through January
and three before Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are going to be three debates in three weeks,'' said Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``I think we're also uncomfortable with a TV station
ruling out some other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush campaign is aware that meeting one-on-one with McCain could elevate
his status as a chief rival. Some Bush supporters said privately that direct
comparisons almost always benefit the underdog, and that Bush runs a greater
risk in a one-on-one session of not comparing favorably.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Democrats, Bill Bradley's campaign said the former senator would not
accept the invitation. There was no immediate answer from Vice President Al
Gore's camp.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Saying he is ``one of us,'' Republican Gov. Frank
Keating filed papers Monday on behalf of Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the
state's presidential primaries on March 14.
</P>
<P>
	   Surrogates also filed papers on behalf of the two Democratic candidates --
Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush is considered the front-runner for the GOP contest in Oklahoma, while
polls have cast Gore as the favorite in the Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
	   The filing period for presidential candidates opened Monday and ends
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials also have received filing papers, by mail, from GOP
contenders Steve Forbes, Sen. John McCain and Gary Bauer. Lance Ward, Election
Board secretary, said Forbes' filing was posted, but the filings from McCain and
Bauer were being delayed until the campaigns could fix an error on the checks
for the $5,000 filing fee.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidates George W. Bush
and Sen. John McCain are locked in a very close race, while Bill Bradley has an
apparent lead over Al Gore in the Democratic race, says a new poll of New
Hampshire primary voters.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush had 35 percent and McCain 31 percent, according to the tracking poll
done Friday though Sunday by the American Research Group of Manchester. In a
similar poll taken over the first three days of January, McCain was at 33
percent and Bush at 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In the latest tracking poll, Steve Forbes was at 15 percent. Alan Keyes,
Gary Bauer and Sen. Orrin Hatch each had between 1 and 3 percent with 12 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the Democrats, Bradley had 46 percent and Gore 41 percent with 13
percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
	   The Republican survey included 507 likely Republican voters and 107
independents who said they plan to vote in the Republican primary. The
Democratic survey included 528 likely Democratic voters and 92
Democratic-leaning independents. In New Hampshire, independents can vote in
either party's primary.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press writer Ron Jenkins contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
