<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial of Ex.-La. Governor Opens  </HEADLINE>
   By NATALIE GOTT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Jurors will be known by numbers, not names, when
they begin hearing evidence against Edwin Edwards, the flamboyant former
Louisiana governor who faces federal corruption charges that could land him in
jail for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards' trial opened Monday with U.S. District Judge Frank Polozola
assuring 96 potential jurors that their identities will be protected. He gave no
reasons for the secrecy, other than to say it was ``to ensure both sides will
get a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors had sought juror anonymity in pre-trial hearings that were
closed to the press. Their reasons were not made public. The practice is usually
used in organized crime cases to prevent jury bribery or intimidation.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards, 72, is on trial with six others -- his son Stephen Edwards, state
Sen. Greg Tarver, state gambling board member Ecotry Fuller, and three longtime
associates: former aide Andrew Martin, businessman Bobby Johnson and cattleman
Cecil Brown.
</P>
<P>
	   They are accused of shaking down people who sought licenses to run riverboat
casinos. The scheme allegedly began during Edwards' final term in office, which
ended four years ago, and continued after he was out of office but still
considered influential.
</P>
<P>
	   A partial list of potential witnesses in the trial, released Monday,
includes Gov. Mike Foster, who was sworn in Monday to his second term after a
landslide re-election last fall; Foster's executive counsel, Cheney Joseph; and
the state's new treasurer, John Kennedy, who was revenue secretary in Foster's
first term. None of them is accused of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Witnesses will also include several former Edwards associates who made plea
bargains with federal prosecutors, the most prominent being former San Francisco
49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
	   And the defendants' own words -- in more than 900 hours of secretly recorded
audio tapes -- will likely be used against them. Those tapes of unguarded
conversations are replete with offensive language, including the word
``nigger.''
</P>
<P>
	   Polozola asked a roomful of potential jurors if they would be offended by
``the use of the `n' word.'' Four blacks and 13 whites raised their hands to
indicate they would.
</P>
<P>
	   Edwards, who could not discuss case details because of a strictly enforced
gag order, said as he entered the courtroom, ``We will present an effective
defense and, in the long run, all will come out well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1852 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regent J. Edward Meyer retiring in March  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state's longest-serving Regent, J. Edward Meyer,
announced Monday he will retire in March in part to help Bill Bradley become the
Democratic nominee for president.
<P>
	   "After 23 years, I'm hanging up my Regents' spikes," said Meyer, who will be
65 in April.
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer, who was first elected to the Board of Regents in 1977, said he felt
that campaigning for Bradley as a presidential delegate and working on the
Regents board would be a conflict of interest. In addition, "A lot of things I
fought for have been accomplished," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer listed finding current Education Commissioner Richard Mills,
developing a "meaningful" high school diploma and having a more visible Board of
Regents as some of the things he fought for.
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer said he was concerned about five years ago that Gov. George Pataki
would ask the Legislature to abolish the Board of Regents and that lawmakers
would agree.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think that is now possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Regents are chosen by joint sessions of the state Legislature. Because
Democrats dominate the 211 seats in the Legislature overall, that means
Democrats select and elect the Regents. Pataki, a Republican, has called for
more direct authority over the Regents and the state education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
	   The Regents are in the middle of an effort to increase the education
standards in New York. Starting this year, seniors will have to be able to pass
at least one Regents exam before getting their high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
	   "Throughout his tenure, he has advocated higher standards for students,
schools, colleges and the professions," Education Commissioner Richard Mills
said. "And he has consistently fought to provide the extra help people need to
reach those standards. We will miss his leadership."
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer said Bradley, whom he is supporting for the Democratic nomination over
Vice President Al Gore, supported him when Meyer first ran for Assembly in 1970.
</P>
<P>
	   "Bill Bradley has been my friend for 30 years," Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Polls show Bradley and Gore in a tight race in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer's retirement becomes official on March 31. He said he does not know
who will replace him but has suggested to legislators that they choose a
"layman," not a professional educator. "The board has to be strong and
independent, and I think a lay person could be better at that," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meyer, who lives in Chappaqua in Westchester County, served two terms in the
Assembly and was also an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern District of
New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Regents are not paid for their service on the board but they get expenses
when on official business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
