<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2000 Auto Sales To Stay in Fast Lane  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- Automakers will sell perhaps 1 million fewer cars in the
United States in 2000 than they did in the record-setting year of 1999, but that
would be only a slight bump as the industry stays in the fast lane, company
economists said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Most of the (economic) indicators are still flashing green," said Ellen
Hughes-Cromwick, manager of Ford Motor Co.'s corporate economic group.
</P>
<P>
	   Including medium-duty and heavy trucks, automakers sold a record 17.4
million vehicles in the United States last year. According to projections by Ms.
Hughes-Cromwick and her counterparts at DaimlerChrysler AG and General Motors
Corp., that total will fall to between 16 million and 17 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Factors that could cause sales to drop this year include the possibility of
higher interest rates and households shifting a bigger share of their income
into savings, the economists told a meeting of the Society of Automotive
Analysts during the North American International Auto Show on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   A trend toward stronger foreign currencies could weaken the U.S. dollar,
boosting the price of domestic-made products and making imports, particularly
those from Japan, more attractive to U.S. buyers, said G. Mustafa Mohatarem,
GM's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
	   Gasoline prices will be "considerably higher" in 2000, said Mohatarem, who
pegged U.S. sales for 2000 at between 16 million and 16.5 million. At the same
time, he said, "Cars will be more affordable in 2000 than they've been in two
decades."
</P>
<P>
	   The influence of gas prices on consumers' vehicle choices has declined since
the oil shocks of the mid 1970s, when there was a wider gap between low- and
high-mileage cars, said W. Van Bussmann, chief economist of DaimlerChrysler's
Chrysler Corp. unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Keeping sales from slipping too far below last year's record levels, they
said, will be continued productivity gains driven by technological advances, and
another year of low inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   "U.S. consumers really have enjoyed a golden age," said Bussmann, who
predicted that sales would total about 16.6 million this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
