<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Reviews 'Dirty Blonde'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    An AP Entertainment Review
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's hard putting famous people on stage without getting
bogged down in biography, but Claudia Shear, with the help of director James
Lapine, has done right by Mae West, the woman best known for doin' men wrong.
</P>
<P>
	   Shear's evocative play, "Dirty Blonde," crosscuts West's show-business saga
with a sweet little love story involving two lost souls who happen to be big
fans of the stage and film icon.
</P>
<P>
	   West was anything but sweet. She was all about sex, which, in fact, was the
title of one of her plays. By the time she was a teen, West was something of an
expert. She walked with her whole body, swung her hips and tossed her hair, and
the more the blue noses disapproved, the more she did it, according to one
description in "Dirty Blonde."
</P>
<P>
	   It was an act West kept up until she died, at age 88, in 1980. By then the
woman was a scary parody of herself, but still, people couldn't take their eyes
off her. West was, in the words of one of the play's characters, "the movie star
equivalent of Venice."
</P>
<P>
	   Shear's homage, playing off-Broadway at New York Theater Workshop, takes
shape slowly. In fact, it's a tad too languid. Some tightening would give the
evening more dramatic muscle and make its charming finale even more successful.
</P>
<P>
	   Gradually, the audience becomes aware that West's story is alternating with
the present-day tale of Charlie and Jo, two lonely people who meet at the star's
grave in New York City's borough of Queens.
</P>
<P>
	   Charlie works in film archives at the New York Public Library; Jo, a
would-be actress, moonlights as an office temp. As a teen-ager, Charlie met West
on a trip to Hollywood and became a lifetime true believer. Their initial
encounter is poignantly portrayed by Kevin Chamberlain, as the shy fan, and
Shear, who doubles as both Jo and her idol.
</P>
<P>
	   Shear's portrait of West can't quite capture the star's larger-than-life
personality -- who could? -- but the actress projects a sassiness that goes a
long way toward convincing us that West could be even more fun off-stage and
off-screen.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet "Dirty Blonde" is about more than just West or the budding relationship
between two of her most ardent admirers. It also deals with the notion of
all-consuming desire, the fierce determination by fans to learn everything they
can about their idols. As Jo says of her West fixation, "Obsession grants the
patience to really fine-tune the details."
</P>
<P>
	   Yet those details are telescoped with care and don't overwhelm the piece.
Bob Stillman, a jaunty song-and-dance man, plays all the other men in West's
life. He is particularly effective as vaudeville cohort Joe Frisco -- "I used to
play the Palace, now I just play the horses" -- who remained loyal to the end.
</P>
<P>
	   There is a wonderful moment near the end of the evening when an elderly West
has Charlie dress up as her and go outside to give a little thrill to the
tourists who pass by her Hollywood apartment. Image is all, according to West,
and when she hit upon the right formula, she never changed it. And Charlie, of
course, is thrilled.
</P>
<P>
	   Lapine's direction is astute, quickly moving from past to present and then
back again, sometimes within the space of a few minutes. Douglas Stein's simple,
almost bare, settings make that possible. "Dirty Blonde" is rich in other ways,
particularly in its depiction of a star and what it means to worship her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 1905 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0229 </DOCNO>
