<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan Sidesteps Agency Consolidation  </HEADLINE>
   By PHILIP BRASHER AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A government task force's plan for improving food
regulation has sidestepped the issue of whether to consolidate the dozen federal
agencies responsible for food safety, a move supported by consumer groups but
opposed by the industry.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, the President's Food Safety Council will take comment on the
consolidation issue at a public hearing Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The overarching goal of the plan is to improve public health by improving
the safety of the food supply,'' Catherine Woteki, the Agriculture Department's
undersecretary of food safety, said in an interview Monday. ``The council is now
asking for public comment for what organizational options would further our
ability to achieve those goals.''
</P>
<P>
	   The council's draft strategic plan, which is dated Friday, said that the
agencies responsible for various food safety issues, ``have developed different
systems for protecting the food supply, and bring different strengths and
shortcomings to the current system.''
</P>
<P>
	   The National Academy of Sciences in 1998 urged Congress to ``establish a
unified, central framework for managing food safety programs'' headed by a
single person.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer advocacy groups criticized the council Monday for failing to
propose a consolidation plan.
</P>
<P>
	   The council, which is made up of officials from the agencies, ``seems to be
designed to fend off efforts to get a single food safety agency,'' said Caroline
Smith DeWaal of the Center for Science in the Public Interest. ``The council is
comprised of exactly the people whose ox would be gored if an independent agency
were to be formed.''
</P>
<P>
	   Carol Tucker Foreman of Consumer Federation of America also criticized the
plan for failing to propose specific goals for cutting cases of salmonella and
other pathogens.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Food Processors Association, which represents the food
industry, applauded the plan. ``What is needed is a single food safety policy,
rather than the creation of a single food agency,'' the group said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Most food safety responsibilities are handled by the Agriculture Department,
which is in charge of meat, poultry and eggs and some issues involving fresh
produce, and the Food and Drug Administration, which oversees other foods. But
agencies like the Environmental Protection Agency, Commerce Department and the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also have a role.
</P>
<P>
	   The strategic plan lays out a series of general goals in risk assessment,
management and public communication.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
