<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uncrowded Crowd Greets Bush in Mich  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- If you wanted to meet George W. Bush, this was
your chance.
</P>
<P>
	   Fewer than 150 people turned out Monday afternoon to greet the Republican
presidential front-runner as he arrived for a debate at Calvin College.
</P>
<P>
	   But he still got a loud cheer when he entered the hangar at the Gerald R.
Ford International Airport to the sounds of Van Morrison's ``Bright Side of the
Road.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly everyone got to shake the Texas governor's hand, get an autograph or
get a picture taken with him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think Bush is on the right track and he's got a tax break I like, and
he's sincere,'' said Tony Senagor, 74, of Grand Rapids, who described himself as
a straight-ticket Republican. ``I think he's going to be moderate.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The small turnout for Bush was in sharp contrast to an event several months
ago at the same airport hangar for GOP presidential rival Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arizona senator was at the airport to officially kick off his
presidential campaign. About 250 people turned out. Most said they liked McCain
but were unsure about backing an underdog.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has been running ads in Michigan and gaining in strength since the
opening.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Michigan Democratic Chairman Mark Brewer came armed with jelly donuts Monday
as he attacked Bush for having a poor record on health care in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We think George Bush's ideas are a lot like this donut,'' Brewer said,
holding one up during a pre-debate news conference in Grand Rapids.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It may look good, it may sound appetizing, but in fact it's bad for you.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said McCain's policies were equally poor.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Most of the 175 Calvin College students attending the debate were lucky
enough to win a ticket, but only a handful earned their seats.
</P>
<P>
	   The college held a contest for questions to ask the candidates in the
debate's third round. About 70 questions were submitted, and nine were chosen,
ranging from the effects of negative campaigning to the cost of tuition to
censorship on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   Dave Dykhouse, a sophomore business major, wanted to know how the
candidates' religion would influence them if elected.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It was interesting to hear them talk about religion in New Hampshire,'' he
said. ``I want to hear more of that.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   It was easy for Brewer, the state Democratic chairman, to pick the winner of
Monday's debate: Michigan GOP Chairwoman Betsy DeVos, who arranged it without
first checking with Gov. John Engler, a staunch Bush backer.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush at first said he wouldn't participate, then changed his mind. Monday's
debate was the third in four days for the six-man GOP field.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This (debate) was done by Betsy DeVos to embarrass Engler, and so far she
seems to have the upper hand,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
	   DeVos said a no-show by Bush could have hurt him. ``That's a possibility,''
she said, adding she was neutral in the race.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Calvin College students hoped the debate would put their Christian liberal
arts college on the map -- literally.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Not a lot of people outside the Midwest have heard of Calvin College,
unless they are Christian Reform,'' said junior Jeremy Johnson of Lakewood,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I tell people I go to Calvin, they say, 'Oh, where's that?''' said
Melissa Keeley, a political science freshman from Midland Park, N.J.
``Especially since this is a political debate, maybe it will open the door for
internships in (Washington) D.C.''
</P>
