<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infertile couples to get medical coverage under new bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Infertile couples, coping with the emotional and
physical toll of trying to conceive, may have one less thing to worry about:
medical bills.
<P>
	   A measure that passed the state Assembly Monday would require some health
insurance policies to cover infertility treatments.
</P>
<P>
	   Treatments can cost thousands of dollars. Some couples, desperate to have
children, dig into savings accounts, take out loans and borrow from family and
friends, said Susan Slotnick, vice president of Resolve of New Jersey, a
statewide support and information group for people struggling with infertility.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have members who have mortgaged their homes, who have run up their
credit cards, borrowed money from their parents," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The costs are prohibitive for the majority of our membership. How can you
tell somebody who can afford the technology, 'OK, you can have a family,'
whereas those who don't have the resources are not entitled to have a family.
That's what we feel this bill remedies - the difference between the haves and
have-nots."
</P>
<P>
	   The bill passed the state Assembly with 45 members voting for it, 11 against
and 15 abstaining. It passed the Senate in December and now heads to Gov.
Christie Whitman's desk for consideration.
</P>
<P>
	   It's uncertain whether Whitman will sign it.
</P>
<P>
	   "Some early indications are that the legislation would be a costly mandated
benefit," said Jayne O'Connor, Whitman spokeswoman. "But the governor has not
taken a position on it. We'll review it."
</P>
<P>
	   The bill requires employers and other groups with 50 or more members to
cover infertility treatments if the medical insurance they offer includes
pregnancy-related benefits. An estimated 535,000 New Jerseyans are infertile,
Slotnick said.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure targets a wide range of treatments, including expensive in vitro
fertilization in which an egg is fertilized outside the uterus and then
implanted. But insurers can require patients to try less expansive treatments
before being eligible for the costly high-tech procedures.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure stipulates that a woman under 35 would have to try to conceive
for two years before being considered infertile and eligible for benefits. Women
over 35 would have to fail to conceive for one year before being eligible.
</P>
<P>
	   Thirteen states already require some type of coverage, according to Diane
Aronson, executive director of Resolve, the National Infertility Association,
located in Massachusetts, one of the states that requires coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   The requirement would increase the cost of health insurance, pushing it even
farther out of reach of the 1.3 million New Jerseyans who don't have insurance
now, said Paul Langevin, president of the New Jersey Association of Health
Plans.
</P>
<P>
	   He said many insurance companies already cover infertility treatments and
employers can add that coverage, if they choose.
</P>
<P>
	   But Sen. Robert Martin, R-Morris, a bill sponsor, said the cost increase
would be slight.
</P>
<P>
	   "When we looked at data from other states, when the costs are spread over a
large pool of risk, it really isn't very expensive," he said. State workers
already have infertility coverage, he pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
