<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $2.7B Sought for Uninsured Kids  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURA MECKLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With millions of uninsured children eligible for federal
health programs, President Clinton will ask Congress for $2.7 billion to make it
easier for states and families to sign kids up, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore planned to highlight the plan Tuesday in Iowa. Health
policy, and how to get insurance to 44 million uninsured Americans, has emerged
as the most significant debate between Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, who
are locked in a battle for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore also will publicize a new report that finds enrollment in the
Children's Health Insurance Program has doubled in the last year to about 2
million children. Clinton signed CHIP, as the program is called, into law in
1997.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're really encouraged with the trend,'' Chris Jennings, Clinton's health
policy adviser, said Monday. ``The president feels that these numbers bode well
for the future. But he also feels strongly that we need to provide additional
tools for states to enroll kids and to eliminate barriers that have limited
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton's plan would make it easier for children in the federal school lunch
program to enroll in health programs and would allow child-care centers,
homeless shelters and other offices to immediately enroll children. It also
would require many states to simplify Medicaid application forms and let more
19- and 20-year-olds into the programs.
</P>
<P>
	   There are 11 million uninsured children in the United States, although more
than a third are eligible for Medicaid or for CHIP, which helps children whose
families earn too much for Medicaid but not enough to buy insurance on their
own.
</P>
<P>
	   The initiative, a part of Clinton's budget request to Congress for 2001,
would build on these existing programs. It's much like Gore's plan, and many of
the details are virtually identical.
</P>
<P>
	   Specifically, the new budget proposal would:
</P>
<P>
	   --Allow school lunch programs, which also serve low-income children, to
share information with Medicaid officials. A recent study found that almost 4
million uninsured children are in the lunch program, making it a prime place to
find them.
</P>
<P>
	   --Allow child care centers, homeless shelters and welfare offices to enroll
kids right away while their applications for health coverage are being
processed.
</P>
<P>
	   --Require states that have simple CHIP applications also use simpler
applications for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
	   Going further, Gore also would allow more people into CHIP, including
children in families with higher incomes and some parents. The White House is
considering making a similar budget request, but no decision has been made, a
White House official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley take an altogether different approach. He would scrap Medicaid and
CHIP and give poor families subsidies to buy coverage through the federal
workers' insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
	   Medicaid, which provides free health insurance for the poor, traditionally
has had trouble attracting all who qualify for it. Many parents don't even know
about it. Some who do see it as a welfare program and want to avoid what they
consider the embarrassment of accepting welfare. And many states have
complicated application forms or limited hours of service, which make signing up
difficult.
</P>
<P>
	   Those problems are highlighted in a report being released this week by the
Kaiser Commission on Medicaid and the Uninsured. The study of 1,335 low-income
parents found that two-thirds with eligible but uninsured children have tried to
enroll their children but couldn't. More than half gave up because of the
difficulty of the process or were denied coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   The new children's health program seeks to avoid many of those pitfalls with
simpler applications, friendly program names and cost-sharing, where families
pay a small part of the premium and avoid the welfare stigma.
</P>
<P>
	   The number of uninsured children rose in 1998, and CHIP enrolled only about
1 million kids in its first year. That left policy-makers wondering if that
program will suffer from similar problems. With the second year's enrollment
doubled, the White House is celebrating, and Gore, no doubt, will be too.
</P>
<P>
	   The new report notes that states are letting more children into the program
than the first year. Federal law allows into the program children whose
families' incomes are below 200 percent of the federal poverty level, or about
$33,000 for a family of four. Some states set the limit lower.
</P>
<P>
	   In March 1997, just four states covered youngsters up to 200 percent of
poverty. Today, 30 states are doing so or plan to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2005 </TRAILER>
