<HEADLINE> Agent: Mayor Milton Milan signed promissory note with accused  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Camden Mayor Milton Milan signed a $2,500 promissory
note with an alleged drug kingpin accused of running the largest cocaine cartel
in the city's history, a witness in a federal drug trial said Monday.
<P>
	   It is the second time that Milan's name has emerged in U.S. District Court,
where Jose "J.R." Rivera and Luis "Tun Tun" Figueroa are on trial on drug
conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Rivera and Figueroa are two of 14 people charged with operating a ring that
prosecutors say controlled a highly profitable city drug market for a decade.
They are the only ones to stand trial and many of their former associates are
expected to testify against them in exchange for plea agreements with federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, another witness dropped a bombshell when he alleged that Milan
bought cocaine from the organization in 1993 - before Milan became mayor in
1997. Milan has angrily denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest testimony came Monday from FBI Agent William Grace, who said the
promissory note was among nearly 200 documents seized by agents when they raided
Rivera's gym and auto parts business in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   The note was dated October 14, 1992 and was on the letterhead of MTM
Contracting Co., Grace said. It was titled "promissory note to pay" and read, in
part:
</P>
<P>
	   "Milan hereby promises to pay back Jose Rivera the amount of $5,000," Grace
testified. That amount, however, was scratched out and $2,500 was written in, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The note was initialed "M.M." and signed by Milan and Rivera, Grace said.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors did not question Grace about the document and declined to
elaborate on it. The document was among dozens of items presented in court
Monday, including weapons and ammunition seized in the raids, a bulletproof
vest, bank records and a safe that contained more than $200,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
	   Milan declined comment from his City Hall Office and referred inquiries to
his lawyer, Carlos Martir, who also represents Figueroa. Martir said he was
unaware of any business relationship between Milan and Rivera.and
</P>
<P>
	   "The document speaks for itself," Martir said. "It may have been a loan. I
don't know what for."
</P>
<P>
	   Milan is not charged in the drug case. However, last summer federal
authorities raided his home and City Hall as part of a federal investigation
into alleged corruption in Camden.
</P>
<P>
	   Last week, Camildo Cruz, the same witnesses who alleged that Milan purchased
cocaine in 1993, testified that he worked briefly for Milan at his construction
company in 1995 and that Rivera contacted Milan for help in getting Cruz the
job.
</P>
<P>
	   Cruz, 34, returned to the stand Monday, undergoing several hours of
cross-examination by the defense, which tried to undermine his testimony. He
made no reference to Milan.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors say Rivera, 40, was the major drug procurer and financier for
the cartel and Figueroa, 34, was an enforcer who used violence to protect the
ring.
</P>
<P>
	   Law enforcement officials have said the organization ran a
multi-million-dollar-a-year business, and was the most entrenched and
significant drug cartel in Camden's history.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities allege that the ring moved large quantities of cocaine from
Puerto Rico through Florida and New York. The ring infiltrated the Camden police
department, and a former detective assigned as a bodyguard to Milan admitted
supplying the ring with an illegal weapon.
</P>
<P>
	   Testimony in the trial resumes Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-10-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
