<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Accused of Bungling Project  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Development of the world's largest laser has been marred
by overly optimistic expectations, management bungling and inadequate attention
by senior officials, a task force of scientists said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The $1.5 billion Energy Department project at Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory has been under intense scrutiny since last September, when it was
found to be three years behind schedule and facing $350 million in cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
	   Only six months earlier, the head of the California weapons laboratory had
told a congressional hearing the project was on schedule and within budget.
</P>
<P>
	   The so-called National Ignition Facility project consists if an
unprecedented array of sophisticated and powerful lasers that are to be key to
monitoring and maintaining America's nuclear weapons without actual bomb
testing.
</P>
<P>
	   A report Monday by a panel appointed by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to
review the project found significant shortcomings in both management and how the
project was designed from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
	   While the panel said it had not uncovered ``any technical or managerial
obstacles'' to completing the project, ``serious challenges and hurdles
remain.''
</P>
<P>
	   The report to Richardson amounted to scathing critique of the handling of
the 3-year-old laser project by both the Energy Department, which underestimated
its complexity and cost, and by Lawrence Livermore, which was accused of not
giving it top-level attention.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said senior DOE officials and those at Livermore viewed the
project as if it were conventional construction and failed to grasp the
complexities of fabricating and assembling a laser system 40 to 50 times more
powerful than anything now in use.
</P>
<P>
	   Since its inception in 1997, the project has been the target of a dozen
scientific and management reviews.
</P>
<P>
	   Last March, Bruce Tarter, Livermore's director, told a congressional hearing
the project was ``on budget and on schedule'' to be completed by 2003.
Laboratory officials gave the same optimistic assessment to Richardson in June.
</P>
<P>
	   Then last September, Richardson was told that serious problems had developed
in assembling the sophisticated laser optics for the 192-beam system, requiring
a $350 million cost overrun and probably four years of delay.
</P>
<P>
	   The task force report reiterated findings that were much the same but said
the project, although technically feasible, is being broadly reworked. The
reworking will be completed in March, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   John McTague, a former vice president of Ford Motor Co. and the task force
chairman, said underestimation of the project's complexity had resulted in
``unrealistic expectations.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were unrealistic because there wasn't enough fleshing out of the
hows, the practical hows, of getting the system built,'' McTague said in a
telephone exchange with reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel urged that the project adopt a new, two-phase approach: build only
half of the system, or a 96-beam laser, then proceed with the other 96 beams
after a two-year test period. McTague said that could bring the project to
completion by 2007.
</P>
<P>
	   In reviewing the project, the panel said DOE's senior defense officials
underestimated its cost because they didn't take into account its complexities
and uncertainties. Instead, the panel said it approved a budget ``appropriate
for (building) an apartment building but ... not appropriate for a
technologically intensive project'' such as the ignition facility.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel also sharply criticized Lawrence Livermore top management and the
University of California, which manages the federal weapons lab, for not paying
close enough top-level attention to the project.
</P>
<P>
	   Tarter, Livermore's director, did not take ``visible or unambiguous
ownership'' of the laser project or ``create an environment that will not allow
for surprises,'' the report said. McTague said a problem was that while the NIF
project was as large as any of the lab's departments, it did not report directly
to the lab director's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25 Species of Apes Said Endangered  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- Not one species of primates has been lost in the past
century, but now 25 species of apes, monkeys, lemurs and other primates are
imperiled and may soon disappear, experts warned Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "As we enter the new millennium, we risk losing our closest living relatives
in the animal kingdom," said Russell Mittermeier, president of Conservation
International.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservation group issued a report that said the main causes of decline
of the primates are the destruction of tropical habitat and attacks by local
hunters as well as the animals' capture for the pet trade and export for
biomedical research.
</P>
<P>
	   The most endangered primates, according to the study, include the golden
bamboo lemur in Madagascar, the yellow-tailed woolly monkey in the tropical
Andes, the mountain gorilla in central Africa and the Tonkin snub-nosed monkey
of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
	   "The plight of primates is a jarring wake-up call," said Peter Seligmann,
chairman of Conservation International. "Our planet is on the brink of a major
extinction crisis."
</P>
<P>
	   Other primates on the 25-most-imperiled list are:
</P>
<P>
	   The Lac Alaotra bamboo lemur, the Perrier's sifaka, the silky sifaka and the
golden-crowned sifaka, all in Madagascar and the Indian Ocean islands; the
golden lion tamarin, the black lion tamarin, the black-faced lion tamarin, the
buff-headed capuchin and the northern muriqui, all in Brazil; the Miss Waldron's
red colobus, white-naped mangabey, Sclater's guenon, the drill gorilla, and the
cross-river gorilla, all in West Africa; the sanje mangabey in Kenya and
Tanzania; the Delacour's langur, Cat Ba Island golden-headed langur and the
gray-shanked douc langur, all in Vietnam; the Hainan gibbon in China; and the
Sumatran orangutan and the Javan gibbon, both in Indonesia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2033 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
