<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Journal Editor Cony Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Edward Cony, a former managing editor of The Wall Street
Journal, Dow Jones executive and Pulitzer Prize-winning reporter, has died. He
was 76.
</P>
<P>
	   Cony died Sunday at a nursing home in Aptos, Calif., said Dick Tofel, a
spokesman for Dow Jones &AMP; Co, which publishes the Journal. The cause was
complications from pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
	   Cony started at the Journal as a reporter in the San Francisco bureau in
1953 and stayed with the newspaper for 35 years. He received the Pulitzer Prize
for national reporting in 1961. He was bureau chief and regional news manager
before he was named the Journal's managing editor in 1965.
</P>
<P>
	   Cony was named executive editor of Dow Jones publications and news services
in 1970, and he took on the role of vice president of Dow Jones in 1972.
</P>
<P>
	   He served as president of the Dow Jones Newspaper Fund from 1981 through
1988, and he was an associate editor at the Journal from 1986 until his
retirement in 1988.
</P>
<P>
	   Cony served as a president of the American Society of Newspaper Editors and
the Associated Press Managing Editors Association. When Cony retired, the APME
newsletter called him ``the boss you would like to have.'' At about the same
time, Cony disclosed that he was suffering from the early stages of Alzheimer's
disease.
</P>
<P>
	   He was born in Maine and served in the Army during World War II. He
graduated from Reed College and earned a master's degree in journalism from
Stanford University in 1951.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2033 </TRAILER>
