<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No. 2 Pentagon Official Resigns  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John Hamre, the deputy secretary of defense who oversaw
the Pentagon's largely successful inoculations against the Y2K computer bug, is
resigning to become head of a major think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing the surprise move Monday, Defense Secretary William Cohen said
he had recommended that President Clinton nominate Rudy de Leon to replace
Hamre. De Leon has been the Pentagon's under secretary for personnel and
readiness for the past two years and previously was undersecretary of the Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton praised Hamre as ``a respected, decisive and forward-looking
leader.'' He said Hamre had implemented innovative defense management
initiatives and defense contracting reforms. ``His impact in these areas will be
felt long after his departure.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre, 49, came to the Pentagon in 1993 as comptroller during the late Les
Aspin's tenure as defense secretary. He held that post until Cohen made him his
top deputy in July 1997, a position Hamre used to push for modernizing the
Pentagon's business practices and improving the security of its computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John Hamre has been my friend and partner in running the department,''
Cohen said in a written statement. ``He approaches all issues with extreme
confidence and an extraordinary sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre took the lead in preparing the Defense Department's far-flung computer
networks for the Y2K rollover. At a cost of $3.6 billion, the effort was
successful except for a temporary New Year's Eve breakdown of a ground station
computer that processes information from a constellation of intelligence
satellites.
</P>
<P>
	   Hamre will leave the Pentagon on March 31 and become president and chief
executive officer of the private Center for Strategic and International Studies,
which ranks among the nation's most prominent public policy research
institutions.
</P>
<P>
	   Like Hamre, de Leon has worked in the Pentagon since the Clinton
administration began.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen credited de Leon with tackling many of the Pentagon's toughest
problems, including most recently a growing controversy over the way the
services implement the administration's policy on homosexuals in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   De Leon also has been overseeing an Army investigation of allegations that
American troops killed hundreds of South Korean civilians in the opening weeks
of the Korean War in 1950. He also has been at the center of so far unsuccessful
efforts to regain Navy use of the Vieques training range in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
	   De Leon was undersecretary of the Air Force from 1994-97. He was staff
director for the House Armed Services Committee for four years before Aspin
brought him to the Pentagon as a special assistant in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2112 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
