<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis of GOP Debate  </HEADLINE>
   By RON FOURNIER AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- The six Republican presidential candidates, like
the voters they are courting, support tax cuts. So what's the big debate?
</P>
<P>
	   Their third joint meeting in five days turned again and again to taxes,
particularly Texas taxes -- as the underdogs tried to undermine Gov. George W.
Bush and the front-runner sought to separate himself from ``those voices in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
	   Each scored political points on an issue almost certain to remain at the
core of the six-man contest. ``There are very thin distinctions between us,''
Sen. Orrin Hatch said. ``We're all going to be tax-cutters.''
</P>
<P>
	   Yes, but their motives differ.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush wants to bury the family legacy. His father, former President George
Bush, broke a no-new-tax pledge during his term and many conservatives harbor
doubts about his son because of it. Also, the two-term Texas governor crafted
his $483 billion package to bolster his case as a ``compassionate conservative''
by helping middle-class Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   John McCain, an Arizona senator running as a political reformer, wants to
change the subject from ethics to taxes. He spent last week answering questions
about his work in the Senate on behalf of political contributors. He was happy
to talk taxes; his letter-writing wasn't mentioned at all Monday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Steve Forbes, a millionaire publisher with enough money to pose a threat to
Bush, used taxes to make a broader point about the front-runner: He called Bush
a typical promise-breaking, word-parsing politician.
</P>
<P>
	   Only Gary Bauer passed on the issue, opting instead to make a broader appeal
to social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
	   `I will say to my party, it better find its voice ... in opposition to
same-sex marriage and in deference to the sanctity of life or it won't matter
how much we want to cut taxes because the country cannot survive another 10
years in the values meltdown it's in right now,'' said the conservative
activist.
</P>
<P>
	   The debate began with Bush being asked about Forbes' latest ad, which
accuses the Texan of breaking a no-new-tax pledge as governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush didn't directly answer the question, but he did note that he cut taxes
twice in Texas and is the only candidate with executive office experience. ``I'm
a tax-cutting person,'' he said. ``I know how to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
	   What Bush didn't mention was that he supported a bill that would have raised
sales taxes. The bill never passed, and Bush eventually signed a $1 billion tax
cut package stripped of the increases, but Forbes believes he can exploit the
doubts about the Bush sequel.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes runs the risk of looking too negative, reminding voters of his 1996
ad campaign that damaged eventual nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked in the debate if he would forgo negative ads, Forbes paused while the
audience tittered. The answer is no, he said finally.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If being negative is telling the truth, I will continue telling the
truth,'' said Forbes.
</P>
<P>
	   Replied Bush, ``I'll tell you something, I'll darn sure not do to candidates
what Mr. Forbes did to Bob Dole in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's tax-cut package is less than half the size of Bush's, but he also
targets middle-class Americans. The difference is in priorities: The Texan would
spend most of future surpluses on tax cuts while McCain would save 60 percent of
the extra money to bolster Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is a growing gap between the haves and have nots,'' McCain said, as
both he and Bush took the traditionally Democratic road to courting middle-class
voters with their tax packages.
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes didn't mention his signature flat tax, but worked hard to portray
Bush as evasive.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There was a lot of hedging about the pledge,'' he said. ``Pledges should
not be lightly made.'' Then, in a veiled reference to Bush Sr., Forbes said of
promise-breaking: ``We've been through that before.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Ron Fournier is chief political writer for The Associated
Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2114 </TRAILER>
