<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Foreign Car Sales Jump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Sales of imported autos in Japan rose in 1999 for the first
time in three years, an industry group said Tuesday, adding to evidence that the
world's second-largest economy is emerging from its deepest slump in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Boosted by a 10.2 percent increase in December imports, full-year sales of
foreign-made cars, trucks and buses rose 0.9 percent to 278,225 from 275,869 in
1998, the Japan Auto Importers Association said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The sales growth comes amid mounting signs that record amounts of public
spending and other government stimulus measures are increasing confidence among
Japan's recession-weary consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   The figures showed German brands led by Mercedes Benz remain overwhelming
favorites among Japanese car buyers, accounting for 58.1 percent of the import
market in 1999, up 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   General Motors was the best selling U.S. automaker in Japan last year, with
a 5.9 percent share of import sales. Total sales of U.S. imports, including
vehicles made by U.S. subsidiaries of Toyota, Honda and other Japanese
manufacturers, amounted to 19.76 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Big Three are finding the going tough in Japan even as the economy
gets back on the road to growth.
</P>
<P>
	   The most popular U.S. brand in Japan, Chevrolet, recorded a sales increase
of 8.5 percent in December, lagging behind the market average by two percentage
points. Chrysler sales skidded 17.4 percent, while Ford climbed 18.2
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2117 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
