<DOCNO> APW20000110.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2000 Auto Sales To Stay in Fast Lane  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- Automakers will sell perhaps 1 million fewer cars in the
United States in 2000 than they did in the record-setting year of 1999, but that
would be only a slight bump as the industry stays in the fast lane, company
economists said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   "Most of the (economic) indicators are still flashing green," said Ellen
Hughes-Cromwick, manager of Ford Motor Co.'s corporate economic group.
</P>
<P>
	   Including medium-duty and heavy trucks, automakers sold a record 17.4
million vehicles in the United States last year. According to projections by Ms.
Hughes-Cromwick and her counterparts at DaimlerChrysler AG and General Motors
Corp., that total will fall to between 16 million and 17 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   Factors that could cause sales to drop this year include the possibility of
higher interest rates and households shifting a bigger share of their income
into savings, the economists told a meeting of the Society of Automotive
Analysts during the North American International Auto Show on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Gasoline prices will be "considerably higher" in 2000, said G. Mustafa
Mohatarem, GM's chief economist, who pegged U.S. sales for 2000 at between 16
million and 16.5 million. At the same time, he said, "Cars will be more
affordable in 2000 than they've been in two decades."
</P>
<P>
	   The influence of gas prices on consumers' vehicle choices has declined since
the oil shocks of the mid 1970s, when there was a wider gap between low- and
high-mileage cars, said W. Van Bussmann, chief economist of DaimlerChrysler's
Chrysler Corp. unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Keeping sales from slipping too far below last year's record levels, they
said, will be continued productivity gains driven by technological advances, and
another year of low inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   "U.S. consumers really have enjoyed a golden age," said Bussmann, who
predicted that sales would total about 16.6 million this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Still Struggling in Iowa  </HEADLINE>
   By SANDRA SOBIERAJ Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COUNCIL BLUFFS, Iowa (AP) -- On some hilly stretches of the road from
Indianola to Osceola to Creston, Bill Bradley's bus caravan creeps at 15 mph --
much like the candidate's uphill struggle in Iowa to pull off a surprise against
what Bradley called ``the Gore-istas.''
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks before voting in the caucuses, Bradley holds out hope for a strong
showing although he has gained little traction in this farm state and remains 20
points behind Democratic presidential rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Remember Harry Truman and how they said to him, 'You're never gonna win;
you're never gonna beat that guy Dewey,''' Bradley declares. He says he'll be
happy with 30 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley spent his first days of the new year here preoccupied with damage
control on agriculture and education policy, areas where Vice President Gore has
accused him of neglect.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, he veered sharply onto the offensive, asking Democrats at a Boone
community college if they would help him ``against the Gore-istas.'' Bradley
called the vice president mistaken in his plan to increase defense spending, and
said that ``for Gore to come here and pose as if he's the defender of the family
farm is an insult'' to Iowans.
</P>
<P>
	   He swiped at President Clinton, too.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley told a Milwaukee hockey fan that he voted for the 1996 Freedom to
Farm Act, which is now despised in this farm state, only because Clinton
promised to follow up with safety-net legislation for family farmers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I took his word, which, you know, isn't always the best thing to do,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, he planned to attack Gore's record on tobacco, aides said.
Spokesman Eric Hauser dismissed the ``Gore-istas'' comment as not negative, but
``tongue-in-cheek and whimsical.''
</P>
<P>
	   Gore's campaign retorted: ``That slip-sliding sound that you hear is the
sound of an increasingly desperate politician,'' said spokesman Chris Lehane.
``It constitutes blatant hypocrisy given his numerous previous statements about
how he's not going to engage in negative politics.''
</P>
<P>
	   Since the vice president has a lock on the party activists who traditionally
dominate Iowa's caucuses, Bradley's challenge is to coax first-timers to the
Jan. 24 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Crowds for the former senator and basketball star can border on starstruck,
but they also are thin, offering little hope for a big turnout on caucus night.
Where the vice president draws about 500 to high schools and 4-H centers,
Bradley, with his wife, draws closer to half that.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Bradley told could-be supporters at the Crouse Cafe in Indianola,
``On election night, when the caucuses are counted, I want to surprise a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
	   He personally keeps count of the pledges voters sign at each stop -- 47 at
the cafe, he reported -- and likes to recall that no insurgent has done better
in the Iowa caucuses than the 31 percent Sen. Edward Kennedy took from winner
Jimmy Carter in 1980.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday alone, Bradley had 15 pages of ``call sheets'' to work through,
telephoning potential caucus goers.
</P>
<P>
	   There is encouragement in the response of such Iowans as retired airline
employee Dottie Lewis of Creston, who said Bradley's flood of straight-talking
TV ads persuaded her to plan to attend a caucus for the first time. ``I've never
been as interested in a candidate before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Defending his Senate voting record on farm issues is hardly what Bradley
hoped to be doing in January. ``When you're 20 points down it doesn't help,''
said Drake University political science professor Dennis Goldford. But Goldford
suggested the damage may be limited.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know how much of Bradley's support comes from the farm side,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The intensity of Bradley's effort hasn't turned him into a 24-hour grump.
</P>
<P>
	   Sitting on the bus with a diet A&AMP;W vanilla soda propped between his legs,
Bradley said he was tickled the other night when a couple of gals at the
American Legion, where he drank beer straight from the pitcher, coaxed him into
a ``tag dance.'' He was disappointed not to find a karaoke bar in downtown Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
	   The often-private Bradley also gabbed about his mental health -- no
depression or other mental illness, ``I can certainly tell you that'' -- and his
favorite recent movie -- ``The Green Mile.'' Both those questions were ruled
off-limits when reporters raised them last year.
</P>
<P>
	   An animated storyteller, Bradley spices his stump speech with dramatizations
of a Russian basketball player's elbow jabs.
</P>
<P>
	   But the elbows from Gore on his record and promises put an angry edge into
Bradley's voice.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore ``doesn't have a leg to stand on'' when it comes to farm policy, he
tells reporters. If he sounds negative -- a no-no among voters, according to
surveys -- he says Gore and his camp started it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I didn't open that door, but they did,'' Bradley said. ``I'm certainly not
going to lighten up.''
</P>
<P>
	   By caucus date, Bradley will have spent $1.4 million on television
advertising here, a sum that his campaign manager Gina Glantz said was
equivalent to Gore's Iowa ad expenses.
</P>
<P>
	   The Gore camp, trying to worsen the perception of Bradley's showing,
whatever vote percentage he gets, calls the ad spending evidence Bradley is out
to win.
</P>
<P>
	   This two-day bus swing through Iowa's heavily Republican southwest is
Bradley's 31st trip to the state as a presidential candidate. And yet, by way of
explaining his persistent double-digit deficit to Gore in polls, Bradley says
Iowans still don't know him. A poll last week said 13 percent of registered Iowa
voters were unsure or uncommitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Woman in Slave Case Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A former restaurant owner was sentenced to eight years in
prison for illegally bringing Thai women to the United States to work in
slave-like conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   Supawan Veerapol, a Thai citizen, was also ordered to repay more than
$85,500 to banks she defrauded by running up bills on the womens' credit cards
that she never paid.
</P>
<P>
	   Veerapol, 55, was convicted in August of 11 felonies, including one count of
involuntary servitude and charges of harboring illegal aliens and mail fraud.
</P>
<P>
	   Defense lawyer W. Anthony Willoughby said he planned to appeal. He argued
during the trial that his client ``is not this demon they portray.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``They came here voluntarily and wanted to be here,'' he said of the women.
</P>
<P>
	   Veerapol, the longtime companion of Thailand's ambassador to Sweden, was
convicted of arranging to have three Thai women brought overseas illegally to
work at her home and now-defunct restaurant.
</P>
<P>
	   Two women escaped and sought help in the Thai community two years ago,
leading to Veerapol's arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   They claimed they were forced to work up to 16 hours a day for little pay,
were denied medical treatment when sick and were forced to sleep on the floor
outside her bedroom in case she needed anything at night.
</P>
<P>
	   Veerapol allegedly threatened to harm the women's families in Thailand if
they tried to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
