<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protestant Militant Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A gunman killed a prominent Protestant
militant Monday outside his home, raising fears of a renewed bloody feud between
rival pro-British paramilitary groups in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
	   No group claimed responsibility for the attack in the predominantly
Protestant town of Portadown, 30 miles west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
	   Police and politicians blamed the outlawed Loyalist Volunteer Force for
gunning down Richard Jameson, who was the reputed local commander of the rival
Ulster Volunteer Force.
</P>
<P>
	   Jameson, 46, died after being shot point-blank in the head as he drove into
his driveway. The lone gunman escaped in a waiting car, police said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The people of Northern Ireland thought they had left these dark days
behind,'' said Portadown's leading Catholic politician, Brid Rodgers, who is a
Cabinet minister in Northern Ireland's new Protestant-Catholic government formed
last month.
</P>
<P>
	   The LVF was founded in 1996 by hard-line UVF members who were opposed to
observing a cease-fire in support of Northern Ireland's peace process.
</P>
<P>
	   The LVF tried to upset peacemaking efforts by killing Catholic civilians at
random, but called its own truce two years ago after its commander, Billy ``King
Rat'' Wright, was assassinated in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   The convicted members of both groups have been winning early paroles under
terms of the Good Friday peace accord of 1998. All are supposed to be free by
July.
</P>
<P>
	   But both gangs continue to operate competing criminal rackets in
working-class Protestant towns like Portadown, where tensions between the two
armed camps run particularly high.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, rival UVF and LVF mobs staged a vicious pub brawl after a soccer
game in the town. Jameson was among the dozen people hospitalized with injuries
following that fracas.
</P>
<P>
	   David Ervine, spokesman for the UVF-linked Progressive Unionist Party, said
he knew Jameson personally. Ervine said he'd been targeted by the Loyalist
Volunteers because of his efforts to get them to stop dealing illegal drugs in
the Portadown area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2205 </TRAILER>
