<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Idaho Postpones Legislative Session  </HEADLINE>
   By MARK WARBIS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Idaho postponed the start of its 2000 legislative
session Monday after the senate president pro tem died of a heart attack while
taking his regular morning jog.
</P>
<P>
	   The death of Jerry Twiggs led the House and Senate to convene only briefly
at midday before adjourning until Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Gov. Dirk Kempthorne sent letters to both houses reporting that
``the condition of the state is sound'' but postponed his State of the State
address for a week.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a sadness that hangs over this state Capitol now,'' the governor
said after meeting with Twiggs' widow, Sandra.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is not how folks thought we'd start the new millennium. But maybe
it's the mark of Idaho, the good people of Idaho that we will take this loss, we
will shoulder it, we will pray together, but we will move forward,'' Kempthorne
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Twiggs, 66, was a retired Blackfoot farmer in his eighth term in the Senate
and fourth as the chamber's president pro tem.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the second senior loss for the Legislature in three weeks. The dean
of the Legislature, Jim Stoicheff, died from a heart attack at home a week
before Christmas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2206 </TRAILER>
