<HEADLINE> Burger King President Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    MIAMI (AP) -- The president of Burger King's North American division, Paul
Clayton, said Monday he resigned to become chief executive officer of The Jamba
Juice Co.
</P>
<P>
	   Jamba Juice is a San Francisco-based business with 275 stores serving up a
wide variety of icy, all natural fruit smoothies and juices, as well as warm
soups and bread.
</P>
<P>
	   Clayton, 41, said the switch from flame-broiled beef to frozen drinks isn't
linked to recent bad press over the Miami-based burger giant's Pokemon
giveaways.
</P>
<P>
	   "My decision was based on the fact that they have a terrific brand, a rich
culture, a terrific product and a rich future," said Clayton, who will start his
new job Feb. 7 after 16 years with Burger King and three years as president. "I
look forward to being a part of their development process."
</P>
<P>
	   In November, Burger Kings across the nation ran out of the wildly popular
Pokemon toys and cards after children and parents gobbled up kids meals to get
the prizes inside.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, a 13-month-old Sonora, Calif., girl suffocated on a plastic ball that
holds the toys on Dec. 11. Federal officials accused the fast-food giant of
being too slow in recalling the millions of containers.
</P>
<P>
	   Clayton said Burger King did everything necessary to protect its customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
