<HEADLINE> Fujimori Ex-Wife Runs for Congress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori's former wife announced Monday
that she would run for Congress, ending supporters' hopes that she would
challenge Fujimori for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
	   But Susana Higuchi said her party, the Independent Moralizing Front, decided
against selecting a presidential candidate as an act of protest against
Fujimori's decision to seek a third consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
	   Higuchi, whose divorce from Fujimori was bitter and highly publicized, had
been touted in recent weeks as a possible presidential or vice presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   The couple's marital problems became public in 1994, after Fujimori's
supporters in Congress passed a law prohibiting the president's immediate family
members from running for national office. Many Peruvians believed the
legislation was tailored to thwart Higuchi's bid to challenge her husband.
</P>
<P>
	   When Higuchi accused Fujimori of tolerating widespread corruption in his
government and ignoring the needs of Peru's poor, he stripped her of her
ceremonial title of first lady, locked her out of the palace and soon after
filed for divorce. The divorce came through in 1996, removing the prohibition
against a Higuchi candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Fujimori has a wide lead over his rival candidates in opinion polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
