<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 100,000 Israelis Protest Syria Deal  </HEADLINE>
   By MARK LAVIE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- More than 100,000 Israelis, many waving huge maps
and banners, gathered in the drizzle Monday to demonstrate against the price
Israel would likely pay for peace with Syria -- return of the strategic Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
	   As Prime Minister Ehud Barak prepared to leave Shepherdstown, W.Va., after
the second round of Israel-Syria talks, leaders of the 17,000 Israelis who live
on the Golan Heights welcomed their supporters in the square in front of Tel
Aviv city hall.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will never leave the Golan Heights,'' declared Eli Malka, chairman of
the Golan Residents Committee, setting off cheers from the demonstrators.
Filling most of the square, they held banners and signs aloft with messages
including, ``The people are with the Golan'' and ``We will not leave the
Golan.''
</P>
<P>
	   The slogans appeared on stickers, hats and buttons in Hebrew and in Russian
-- an attempt to reach the tens of thousands of recent immigrants from the
former Soviet Union who could be crucial in a planned referendum on the Golan's
fate.
</P>
<P>
	   A huge 3-D map depicted the Golan and its settlements, and a two-story high
balloon declared, ``We will not descend from the Golan.''
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the protesters were teen-agers who were bused in. Before the protest
began, they sang nationalist songs.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Gen. Meir Dagan, just retired from his position as the government's
adviser on terrorism, warned that a Golan pullout would bring ''100 years of
terrorism'' into Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   In response to Barak's claim that failure to make peace would result in a
war, Dagan told the crowd, ``If we give back the Golan, there will also be a
war, and it will be bloodier and costlier than any other war in our history.''
</P>
<P>
	   Returning from the Shepherdstown talks Monday, Foreign Minister David Levy
said no progress was made.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no drawing of borders and there are no agreements,'' David Levy
told reporters. ``We can certainly not speak of results,'' he said, adding that
closing gaps between the two sides ``will have to wait for the next round.''
</P>
<P>
	   Alan Freishtat brought his 11-year-old son with him from Jerusalem to
demonstrate against concessions to Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They are not to be trusted with a peace treaty,'' said Freishtat, who
moved here 14 years ago from Silver Spring, Md. Syria is a dictatorship and
shows no signs of change, he added.
</P>
<P>
	   Farmer Yehoshua Weil, 52, faces eviction from the collective village of
Ramot if Israel gives up the Golan Heights. He sees the issue as more than a
matter of real estate. ``It's our home,'' he said, ``but it also appears to be a
change in the nation's values, that settlement is losing its importance.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although the turnout was impressive, organizers failed to produce what they
promised -- the largest demonstration in Israel's history -- reflecting a rift
between Golan Heights settlers and those from the West Bank. The record is
widely believed to be a demonstration against the war in Lebanon in 1982 that
drew between 300,000 and 400,000 protesters.
</P>
<P>
	   The lower-than-expected turnout might also have reflected a recent rift
between Golan Heights settlers and those from the West Bank. After joining
forces at one point, Golan settlement leaders had second thoughts. West Bank
settler leaders were not prominent at the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
	   Chaim Saperia, head of the Public Council for the Golan, said the joint
approach was a ``bad mistake.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said the Golan settlers must appeal to Israel's moderates, while the West
Bank settlers are identified with hawkish ideologues. He said it was essential
to break the link to maximize support among Israelis, though the well-organized
West Bank settlers could have brought in thousands more demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
	   Barak has pledged to put any agreement with Syria before the people in a
referendum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2224 </TRAILER>
