<HEADLINE> Dad Pleads Innocent in Kidnap Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An Italian man pleaded innocent Monday to a federal
charge that he kidnapped his 2-year-old daughter from Southern California and
took her to Rome, where her mother was killed during an argument when she went
to retrieve the child.
</P>
<P>
	   Carlo Alberto Ventre, 51, entered a plea to a count of international
parental kidnapping. His Los Angeles trial was scheduled to begin on Feb. 29. He
could face up to three years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventre has been ordered to stay at his brother's home in Las Vegas under
electronic monitoring pending trial.
</P>
<P>
	   A grand jury on Wednesday indicted Ventre on charges of allegedly taking his
daughter, Santina, to Italy in January 1998. Her mother, Toni Dykstra, had sole
custody.
</P>
<P>
	   Dykstra, 29, went to Italy to retrieve Santina and died of a blow to the
head during an argument with Ventre on July 28, 1998. Ventre, who claimed
self-defense, has not been charged in Italy in connection with the death.
</P>
<P>
	   Santina, now 4, was brought back to Southern California in November and has
been living with her maternal grandparents.
</P>
<P>
	   Ventre was arrested in the kidnapping case when he arrived in Los Angeles on
Dec. 19 on a flight from Milan.
</P>
</TEXT>
