<HEADLINE> Boy Gets Probation for Alleged Plot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT HURON, Mich. (AP) -- One of the teen-agers accused of planning a
massacre at his middle school was sentenced as a juvenile Monday to four years
of probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Justin Schnepp, 15, has been ordered to attend Kokomo Academy, a detention
facility in Indiana, said Judge James P. Adair.
</P>
<P>
	   Schnepp and three other boys from Holland Woods Middle School were arrested
in May. Police and prosecutors said the boys planned to carry out a killing
spree bigger than the April massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
	   Schnepp, who was 14 at the time of his arrest, pleaded guilty as a juvenile
last month to conspiracy to commit assault, which carries a lighter sentence
than conspiracy to commit murder, the original charge.
</P>
<P>
	   One of his co-defendants, Jedaiah ``David'' Zinzo, 15, was sentenced to four
years probation last week and will attend a Port Huron charter academy for
wayward teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
	   The complaint against one of the other boys was dropped and the fourth boy,
Daniel Fick, is to stand trial on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
