<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eds: Dollar amounts are in Canadian dollars By The Associated Press
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Dangerous Public Water Supplies Found in Newfoundland
</P>
<P>
	   ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) -- About a third of 197 public water supplies
tested in Newfoundland since 1985 contained high levels of potentially dangerous
chemicals, the province revealed Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Studies have shown consuming water containing high levels of these
chemicals, known as trihalomethanes or THMs, increases the risk of contracting
bladder cancer.
</P>
<P>
	   THMs are among the many by-products created when chlorine is used to
disinfect drinking water.
</P>
<P>
	   ``People should not be alarmed about THMs in their water supplies,''
Environment Minister Oliver Langdon said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The benefits of disinfecting drinking water is greater than the risk on
health from THMs. . . . It's not a crisis situation.''
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the minister said the province would hire a full-time employee to
work with municipalities to help them reduce their THM levels. A new Web site
and brochures are also being put together.
</P>
<P>
	   Sixty-three of the communities tested had unacceptable levels of THM,
prompting some of them to take matters into their own hands.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Natural Resources Minister To Meet With Striking Miners
</P>
<P>
	   POINT ACONI, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Federal Natural Resources Minister Ralph
Goodale did an about-face Monday and agreed to meet with union representatives
for hundreds of illegally striking Cape Breton coal miners.
</P>
<P>
	   But that didn't end the wildcat action at federally owned Devco, or bring 10
or so miners holed up at the bottom of Cape Breton's last working coal mine back
to the surface.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim Noble, a spokesman for the miners, said they want more than just talk.
</P>
<P>
	   He said they won't give up until they see movement from the federal
government on their demand for negotiations on improved severance and retirement
packages for about 1,600 employees of the Cape Breton Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa plans to sell its coal assets, including the Prince colliery in Point
Aconi, by the end of the year. It closed another mine, Phalen in nearby New
Waterford, in December.
</P>
<P>
	   ---
Amateur Boxing Association Gives Up Fight on No-Beard Rule
</P>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- Canada's amateur boxing association has thrown in the towel
in a legal fight with a Sikh boxer who argued the rule against beards in the
ring is discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
	   In an agreement expected to be approved by the courts on Wednesday, any
boxer who sports whiskers as a matter of faith will now be allowed to box, Hank
Summers, president of the Canadian Amateur Boxing Association, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They do have to have a bona fide religious (reason),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the agreement, the association will also have to try again for a
change to the international rule against beards.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue came to a head last month when the boxing organization went around
a last-minute Ontario court ruling by scrapping the entire light-flyweight
division at a national tournament in British Columbia rather than allow Pardeep
Nagra to fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
