<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delphi Acquires Diesel Co. From TRW  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- Delphi Automotive Systems has taken a step toward
increasing its presence in Europe by acquiring Lucas Diesel Systems from TRW
Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   The $871 million purchase was announced Monday by Delphi. Company officials
said the deal should allow the automotive component and systems company to raise
its sales in Europe by 20 percent, or to more than $5 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
	   "Delphi is now uniquely positioned to offer customers complete gas and
diesel engine management systems, including fuel handling, air control,
emissions after treatment, sensors, and actuators, and sophisticated electronic
control," Delphi President J.T. Battenberg III said.
</P>
<P>
	   Delphi officials said the purchase of Lucas will also increase by 16 percent
the company's revenue not derived from sales to General Motors.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucas will be renamed Delphi Diesel Systems and become part of the company's
energy and chassis systems division. Lucas' managing director Dominique Chauvin
will hold the same position at Delphi.
</P>
<P>
	   The operation will employ 8,600 at 12 manufacturing facilities in seven
countries.
</P>
<P>
	   "With the continued increase of diesel penetration around the world,
especially in Europe, we see tremendous growth opportunities," Battenberg said.
"In short, we believe this is the right move at the right time."
</P>
<P>
	   The Troy, Mich.-based Delphi has 210,000 employees and operates 180
manufacturing sites worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2251 </TRAILER>
