<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Minister To Visit S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- China's defense minister will visit military bases
and pay a courtesy call on President Kim-Dae-jung during a trip to South Korea
next week, South Korea said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Chi Haotian will also meet his counterpart in Seoul, Cho Sung-tae, during
his five-day visit, which starts Jan. 19, the Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cho visited Beijing in August last year and held the first talks between
defense ministers of the two nations, adversaries during the 1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
	   At that time, local media reported that Cho asked Chi to dissuade communist
North Korea from test-firing a long-range missile. China urged both countries to
reduce tensions on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, North Korea test-fired a missile, which flew over Japan and landed
in the Pacific Ocean. Pyongyang agreed not to go ahead with another test last
year after the United States agreed to a partial lifting of sanctions against
it.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States fought on South Korea's side while China backed North
Korea during the Korean War, which ended with an armistice, not a permanent
peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
	   Chi led a Chinese battalion against U.S. and South Korean forces during the
war.
</P>
<P>
	   China opened diplomatic relations with South Korea in 1992. China is
currently South Korea's third-largest trading partner, while South Korea is
China's fifth largest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2256 </TRAILER>
