<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karmapa Hasn't Requested Asylum  </HEADLINE>
   By DEEPAK SHARMA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DHARMSALA, India (AP) -- A teen-age Buddhist leader who fled Chinese-ruled
Tibet has not asked India for asylum, a member of the Dalai Lama's
government-in-exile said Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The 14-year-old Karmapa arrived in Dharmsala on Wednesday after an eight-day
trek over the Himalayas.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have not applied to the government of India,'' said K.A. Lontashiwangd,
religious affairs minister in the Dalai Lama's administration. ``But if the
government decided to give asylum, that can be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
	   India's Foreign Office spokesman, Raminder Singh Jassal, told an informal
press briefing that the government is looking into the circumstances and
consequences of the Karmapa's arrival.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa's defection is the most significant exodus since the Dalai Lama
and tens of thousands of Tibetans departed their homeland after a failed 1959
uprising against Chinese rule.
</P>
<P>
	   Both China and India have reacted cautiously to the defection.
</P>
<P>
	   China's fragile ties with India suffered a setback after India conducted
nuclear tests in May 1998, citing China as a security threat. India and China
fought a war in 1962.
</P>
<P>
	   Assistant U.S. Secretary of State Julia Taft arrived in India on Monday and
flew to Dharmsala, the seat of the Dalai Lama's government-in-exile, where she
will visit Tibetans as part of her job to investigate the conditions of refugees
and migrants.
</P>
<P>
	   Jassal said Taft's trip had been scheduled before the news of the Karmapa's
escape.
</P>
<P>
	   Early Sunday, the Karmapa left the Chonor Guest House, where he had stayed
since his arrival here. The Dalai Lama's administrators refused to say where he
went.
</P>
<P>
	   But local police and monks, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he had
moved to Gyuto monastery in Sidvari, 10 miles southeast of Dharmsala, where the
exile Tibetan community has its biggest university.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have shifted him to keep him away from the media and his followers,''
Longtashiwangd said. ``We want him to have a good rest.''
</P>
<P>
	   China approved the 17th Karmapa's enthronement in 1992 and used him as a
symbol to project its toleration of Tibetan Buddhism. He is the only high lama
whose accession had been agreed upon by both the Chinese authorities and the
Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
	   The Karmapa's Kagyu sect, known as the ``Black Hats,'' is one of four main
strands of Tibetan Buddhism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-10-00 2319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000110.0333 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-10 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Head of U.S. Army Visits No Gun Ri  </HEADLINE>
   By KYONG-HWA SEOK Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NO GUN RI, South Korea (AP) -- The head of the U.S. Army met Monday with
survivors of an alleged mass killing of refugees by American soldiers during the
Korean War and promised a thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Army Secretary Louis Caldera made the pledge when he visited No Gun Ri, a
hamlet in central South Korea where survivors say American soldiers killed
hundreds of refugees in the first weeks of the Korean War in 1950.
</P>
<P>
	   Caldera's first visit to No Gun Ri was part of a U.S. government inquiry. He
told a dozen survivors that the United States ``is committed to a thorough
investigation'' alongside South Korean authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, Caldera met with Chung Hae-joo, South Korea's minister for
government policy coordination. Caldera planned to meet with President Kim
Dae-jung later in the day.
</P>
<P>
	   Before Monday's meeting, Caldera, accompanied by 18 other American officials
and advisers, visited a railroad tunnel where survivors say up to 400 civilian
refugees were machine-gunned by American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Where exactly were the soldiers?'' Caldera asked during a briefing by a
survivor in front of the tunnel. ``How many machine guns were there?''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't know, but the bullets rained down from everywhere,'' Chung Ku-ho
responded through an interpreter. Chung, then 13, was one of several dozen
villagers who survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
	   Declassified U.S. military documents said American ground commanders feared
that enemy soldiers, disguised in the common white clothing of civilians, were
mixing in South Korean refugee columns.
</P>
<P>
	   During Caldera's visit to No Gun Ri, several Koreans raised a banner that
read in English: ``You must know what you did. You must repay. Wake up from your
ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in Seoul, Caldera met South Korean Defense Minster Cho Sung-tae and
his deputy, Park Young-ok.
</P>
<P>
	   In September, The Associated Press quoted dozens of villagers and U.S.
veterans as saying that hundreds of Korean civilians were killed at No Gun Ri by
American soldiers who feared communist North Korean soldiers were infiltrating
groups of refugees.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States and South Korea had previously dismissed the claims, but
opened investigations after the AP report was published.
</P>
<P>
	   Since then, South Koreans have come forward with more stories of alleged
mass killings of civilians by U.S. troops. Historians say Korean forces on both
sides of the conflict committed atrocities.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army secretary told the AP on Sunday that the United States could not
study ``every firefight, every battle'' of the 1950-53 Korean War. Caldera said
all loss of life was regrettable, but emphasized the need to establish whether
civilians were killed intentionally.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States led a 16-nation U.N. force in defense of South Korea
against North Korea, which was backed by China and the Soviet Union. About
55,000 Americans were killed and more than 8,000 are still listed as missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
