<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Citizen Charged in Bombings  </HEADLINE>
   By LARRY NEUMEISTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- An American citizen who allegedly once served as personal
secretary to Osama bin Laden was ordered held without bail Monday on charges
that he was part of the conspiracy behind the 1998 embassy bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
	   Wadih El Hage, who is from Arlington, Texas, was again denied bail after a
federal judge ruled that he still poses a danger to society and might flee. El
Hage was arrested in 1998 and ordered held without bail.
</P>
<P>
	   Bin Laden and El Hage are among 18 people indicted in a conspiracy to attack
Americans in the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. The
attacks killed 224 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal prosecutor Patrick Fitzgerald said El Hage returned to Texas in 1997
from a trip abroad and brought with him new terrorism directives from bin
Laden's group that made clear the organization's violent objectives, especially
in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ultimate results were the bombings which occurred in August 1998,''
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
	   The evidence cited by Fitzgerald was the closest the government had come
publicly to accusing El Hage of a direct role in the bombings. The prosecutor
said El Hage's role as a communicator in bin Laden's group made it likely that,
if freed on bail, he would try to tell the group the extent of the government's
knowledge of their activities.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand also cited a personal experience as he
ruled that El Hage should not be freed on bail.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge noted the day last June when El Hage, angry because he was not
allowed to have a letter read into the record during a hearing, leaped over a
railing and charged toward Sand. He got within several feet before he was
tackled by federal marshals.
</P>
<P>
	   Sam Schmidt, El Hage's lawyer, said prosecutors had failed to cite ``a
single thing'' that showed El Hage posed a danger to society. He said El Hage
offered no resistance as marshals handcuffed him against a wall that day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
